{"term": "1957", "caseName": "Cooper v. Aaron", "caseLink": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/1 MISC", "caseTranscripts": [{"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - August 28, 1958 (Part 1)", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/15571", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Court has now convened in special term to consider an application by the petitioners for vacation of the order of the United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit, staying the issue of its mandate and for a stay of the order of United States District Court for the Eastern District of Arkansas of June 21, 1958 in John Aaron et al., versus William G. Cooper et al.", "start": 0, "stop": 34.924, "duration": 34.92}, {"text": "The order of the argument will be, first the petitioner, second the respondent and then the Solicitor General.", "start": 34.924, "stop": 45.295, "duration": 10.37}, {"text": "And thereafter either of the parties can rebuttal of the Solicitor General if they are so advised, the respondent to speak last.", "start": 45.295, "stop": 55.392, "duration": 10.1}, {"text": "Mr. Butler we will now entertain a motion to admit for the purposes of this case any the associate that you may have.", "start": 55.392, "stop": 64.363, "duration": 8.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor in connection with this case, I have Mr. John Hailey of Little Rock Arkansas, who is not yet a member of this Court.", "start": 64.363, "stop": 75.153, "duration": 10.79}, {"text": "He is substituting for Mr. A. F. House.", "start": 75.153, "stop": 77.931, "duration": 2.78}, {"text": "I have also as co-counsel the President of the Little Rock School Board, who is an attorney Mr. (Inaudible) and we do not know at this point Your Honor whether they will participate in argument or not, we do not anticipate that they will.", "start": 77.931, "stop": 90.903, "duration": 12.97}, {"text": "We did not know the order until Your Honor just announced and if we have the rebuttal then I shall probably carry the burden of all of the argument.", "start": 90.903, "stop": 102.762, "duration": 11.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Should you wish -- should you wish later Mr. Butler to have either of these gentlemen admitted for the purposes of this case, we will be very glad to hear you.", "start": 102.762, "stop": 111.697, "duration": 8.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 111.697, "stop": 116.515, "duration": 4.82}, {"text": "And Your Honor one other thing I don't know that it's been made a matter of record yet and I don't believe that the Court has announced, the honorable William Fulbright, United States Senator from Arkansas has filed a motion for leave to file a brief together with the brief.", "start": 116.515, "stop": 134.067, "duration": 17.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "We have two --", "start": 134.067, "stop": 134.588, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Fulbright is present.", "start": 134.588, "stop": 136.671, "duration": 2.08}, {"text": "He does not expect to participate in the argument.", "start": 136.671, "stop": 140.262, "duration": 3.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes we have two, two motions of that kind which will be taken care of in due course.", "start": 140.262, "stop": 149.645, "duration": 9.38}, {"text": "Number 1, Miscellaneous John Aaron et al.", "start": 149.645, "stop": 152.578, "duration": 2.93}, {"text": "petitioners, versus William G. Cooper et al, Members of the Board of Directors of the Little Rock Arkansas Independent School District, and Virgil T. Blossom, Superintendent of Schools.", "start": 152.578, "stop": 165.506, "duration": 12.93}, {"text": "Mr. Marshall.", "start": 165.506, "stop": 177.511, "duration": 12}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "May it please the Court.", "start": 177.511, "stop": 181.841, "duration": 4.33}, {"text": "This afternoon's extraordinary session was necessitated because of the fact that the constitutional rights of the petitioners here, the Negro plaintiffs in the cases below, their right to remain attendance at a desegregated school in Central High School in Little Rock and this was pursuant to court order.", "start": 181.841, "stop": 208.807, "duration": 26.97}, {"text": "I like to emphasize at the outset the rights we are seeking protection for are not rights that are in the abstract, but rights that have been determined not necessarily by the Brown decision, but you -- the Court will remember that in this case the District Court approved the plan of desegregation.", "start": 208.807, "stop": 236.379, "duration": 27.57}, {"text": "The plaintiffs below appealed to the Court of Appeals of the Eighth Circuit.", "start": 236.379, "stop": 241.057, "duration": 4.68}, {"text": "It was affirmed, and court record also shows that in September of last year there were two applications for stay to Judge Davies sitting especially in the District Court for the Eastern District of Arkansas and they were both denied.", "start": 241.057, "stop": 258.447, "duration": 17.39}, {"text": "So the rights we seek are rights that have been recognized by the federal courts and as such we believe that they are in a different category from a normal litigant in an injunction proceeding prior to judgment.", "start": 258.447, "stop": 277.371, "duration": 18.92}, {"text": "But however the normal procedure in this case would have meant that the stay of judge Lemley's order would have been issued by Judge Lemley, but he did not.", "start": 277.371, "stop": 293.231, "duration": 15.86}, {"text": "He refused and declined to stay the judgment.", "start": 293.231, "stop": 297.397, "duration": 4.17}, {"text": "The Court will remember that at the end of this past session of this Court, we filed a petitioner for certiorari, seeking to have this Court review Judge Lemley's decision without first going through the Court of Appeals under the special section that provides that that shall happen, if there is some extraordinary situation which we thought existed.", "start": 297.397, "stop": 322.573, "duration": 25.18}, {"text": "And this Court denied the petition for certiorari, and the case went back, rather we went back to the Court of Appeals.", "start": 322.573, "stop": 331.489, "duration": 8.92}, {"text": "The Court of Appeals sat in extraordinary session and sat en banc, the entire court, and in short time decided the case, in unequivocal language that Judge Lemley's order was wrong.", "start": 331.489, "stop": 352.005, "duration": 20.52}, {"text": "I emphasize the language because I will need that in my argument later.", "start": 352.005, "stop": 359.62, "duration": 7.62}, {"text": "However, two days thereafter we having filed a motion for the mandate to issue forthwith, the respondent school board having filed a motion to stay the mandate, we arrived in this very extraordinary situation, I would like to call it anomaly in the law, of an order appealed from, reversed insofar as an opinion can and I have of course recognize it is judgments and not opinions to reversal orders, and then to have the stay issued.", "start": 359.62, "stop": 400.632, "duration": 41.01}, {"text": "And the truth of the matter is these entire proceedings, starting with the filing of the petition of the school board way back in February asking for time, the whole purpose of these proceedings is to get time.", "start": 400.632, "stop": 418.207, "duration": 17.57}, {"text": "The objective of the proceedings is that the Little Rock Schools be returned from desegregated to segregated status as of September school term.", "start": 418.207, "stop": 432.086, "duration": 13.88}, {"text": "The order having been declared in the opinion as being wrongfully issued the procedural device which is normal to stay the mandate of a Court of Appeals only for the purpose of preserving the record in the Court of Appeals so it can get up here that's the only purpose for it, but in this case the stay of the issuance of the mandate decided the merits of the case directly contrary to the opinion of the case.", "start": 432.086, "stop": 464.738, "duration": 32.65}, {"text": "The opinion said that the school board was not entitled to a suspension of the integration plan.", "start": 464.738, "stop": 474.541, "duration": 9.8}, {"text": "The stay of the mandate said you don't have to act on this until after the school term begins.", "start": 474.541, "stop": 482.983, "duration": 8.44}, {"text": "At that time the school term was to begin on September 2nd.", "start": 482.983, "stop": 487.271, "duration": 4.29}, {"text": "This Court can take judicial notice that that has been postponed to September 8th, but at any rate the staying of the mandate would effectively mean that if this Court would wait until October, the school term would be in session and I believe anybody will agree that it's not good educational policy to transfer children in the middle of a school term.", "start": 487.271, "stop": 512.881, "duration": 25.61}, {"text": "So we have this strange situation in the law of a procedural device of staying a mandate actually ruling on the merits in the case.", "start": 512.881, "stop": 526.459, "duration": 13.58}, {"text": "That point plus this additional point and that is that the Court certainly can take judicial notice of what is going on in the legislature in Arkansas today, it's quite obvious that anytime spent in delay in this matter will bring about not less litigation but more litigation and that is why and I think we are entitled to it.", "start": 526.459, "stop": 555.674, "duration": 29.22}, {"text": "We believe that this Court must not only and stay, vacate the stay of the eighth circuit, I mean the Court of Appeals for the eighth circuit, but I think that in the present posture of this litigation, in the very peculiar status that it's in, and the atmosphere that now exists in the State of Arkansas with the Governor and the legislature and everybody determined to set themselves up against the whole United States, that the only effective relief that this Court can give that will protect the rights of the petitioners here would be to stay the man -- I mean vacate the stay of issuance of the mandate.", "start": 555.674, "stop": 602.922, "duration": 47.25}, {"text": "Two, to stay Judge Lemley's order, suspending the previous orders of the District Court, and as was done in the Lucy case for an entirely different reason, to order that the existing orders of Judge Miller, who originally heard the case and Judge Davies who heard it, sitting specially assigned last September, be reinstated and in full force in effect.", "start": 602.922, "stop": 632.968, "duration": 30.05}, {"text": "A question immediately arises as to whether this Court has authority to do it.", "start": 632.968, "stop": 638.091, "duration": 5.12}, {"text": "Well as was pointed out in many cases, the All Writs Statute for one gives authority and indeed the procedural statute on the staying of the mandate gives credence to our position, and if there is any exact authority that's needed, we take the flat position that the Lucy case says specifically that this Court has that authority and needs go no further.", "start": 638.091, "stop": 667.443, "duration": 29.35}, {"text": "I don't believe as might be argued that this Court cannot and should not go into the merits of this.", "start": 667.443, "stop": 677.471, "duration": 10.03}, {"text": "It tends to raise the question in my mind what do we mean by the merits.", "start": 677.471, "stop": 683.275, "duration": 5.8}, {"text": "The merits in this case have already been decided by the stay and the stay is now being reviewed by this Court.", "start": 683.275, "stop": 692.254, "duration": 8.98}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I ask you a question?", "start": 692.254, "stop": 693.425, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 693.425, "stop": 694.023, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "You said on September 8th was the postponed opening day, is it 8th or the 15th?", "start": 694.023, "stop": 698.742, "duration": 4.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "The September 8th is the date fixed by the Superintendent of Schools.", "start": 698.742, "stop": 703.458, "duration": 4.72}, {"text": "There is a bill pending in the legislature postponing it until September 15, for the express reason as seeing what happens in Virginia, so they will know what to do in Arkansas, it has no relation to this case at all, but the September 8th date was done by the School Board, a day or so ago.", "start": 703.458, "stop": 723.373, "duration": 19.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But if that bill passes, I take it the Board order will be subordinated to the legislative direction, is that right?", "start": 723.373, "stop": 733.15, "duration": 9.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I should think that under the normal state procedure, the legislature could supercede the School Board, and indeed the difficulty out there is that it's all going along much in the -- I mean both are working the same way it seems to me insofar as the stay is concerned.", "start": 733.15, "stop": 752.597, "duration": 19.45}, {"text": "The merits of this case, the one issue in this case, is whether or not this order or these orders or the District Court approved by the Court of Appeals can be suspended for a time.", "start": 752.597, "stop": 772.453, "duration": 19.86}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Approved by the (Inaudible)", "start": 772.453, "stop": 774.098, "duration": 1.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, the first plan, no sir the original plan, the original that was approved by the Court.", "start": 774.098, "stop": 782.308, "duration": 8.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I ask you about -- I think you said a few minutes ago, which order of Judge Davies, the original order approving the plan proposed by the School Board was that you stated by Judge Miller.", "start": 782.308, "stop": 796.325, "duration": 14.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "By Judge Miller.", "start": 796.325, "stop": 797.375, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did Judge -- what judgment of Judge Davies later --", "start": 797.375, "stop": 803.096, "duration": 5.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then --", "start": 803.096, "stop": 804.032, "duration": 0.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- repeated in effect that other than the order relating to the intervention of truth didn't deal with that problem?", "start": 804.032, "stop": 812.005, "duration": 7.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "No Mr. Justice Frankfurter, what happened was as soon as the governor threatened to bring out the troops, the School Board went to Judge Davies and asked for instructions and he told them move ahead with the plan.", "start": 812.005, "stop": 827.566, "duration": 15.56}, {"text": "Subsequent to that time, a day or so later, I don't remember the exact date, I can get it for you though sir, they formally appeared before Judge Davies and asked for the right to postpone operation of the plan and Judge Davies ordered them “To proceed forthwith with the plan.”", "start": 827.566, "stop": 848.554, "duration": 20.99}, {"text": "And the petition filed by the respondents here requested the Court to stay the whole business saying that they considered the first order of Judge Miller to be in affect an injunction and if not, then the orders of Judge Davies, but it was aimed at all three, the petition as set forth.", "start": 848.554, "stop": 870.865, "duration": 22.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I was looking for it in the record in the Court of Appeals and never mind.", "start": 870.865, "stop": 876.418, "duration": 5.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "It is in the full record sir.", "start": 876.418, "stop": 881.683, "duration": 5.26}, {"text": "What actually happened was that the original was -- as I understand it rather informal request of Judge Davies, the second was a formal one, here in (Inaudible) prompt ruling then and there.", "start": 881.683, "stop": 895.501, "duration": 13.82}, {"text": "So that they were under orders to use the word of the District Court to proceed with the plan and they sought relief from --", "start": 895.501, "stop": 904.418, "duration": 8.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But am I right in understanding the meaning of various opinions that after the original order of the District Court presided over by Judge Miller in which he canvassed the order of the School Board at length.", "start": 904.418, "stop": 921.28, "duration": 16.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 921.28, "stop": 923.286, "duration": 2.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And issued an order for its carrying out.", "start": 923.286, "stop": 926.802, "duration": 3.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 926.802, "stop": 927.47, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That Judge Davies appears on the judicial scene on the basis of a petition or whatever it was called by the School Board itself asking for instructions.", "start": 927.47, "stop": 939.621, "duration": 12.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, and then a petition asking a postponement of relief, and the --", "start": 939.621, "stop": 945.642, "duration": 6.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Those are separate things.", "start": 945.642, "stop": 946.652, "duration": 1.01}, {"text": "They first ask for instructions in view of the imminent or actually executed order of Governor for the troops to enter, is that right?", "start": 946.652, "stop": 953.429, "duration": 6.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 953.429, "stop": 954.927, "duration": 1.5}, {"text": "No sir, to keep them from carrying the plan out.", "start": 954.927, "stop": 957.302, "duration": 2.38}, {"text": "It had nothing -- it adjust -- that they didn't -- because of this atmosphere situation, they wanted to be relieved from putting the children in school as of that September.", "start": 957.302, "stop": 967.43, "duration": 10.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is exactly what I want to know.", "start": 967.43, "stop": 968.81, "duration": 1.38}, {"text": "Were these two separate legal pieces of papers filed by the School Board, one for instruction and another and a separate petition by them to be allowed to postpone the direction theretofore given by the Court.", "start": 968.81, "stop": 983.262, "duration": 14.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's as I understand it, as I read it yes sir.", "start": 983.262, "stop": 985.74, "duration": 2.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Alright.", "start": 985.74, "stop": 986.854, "duration": 1.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "It will -- since with permission of the Court we can get those from the record, we don't have it with us though.", "start": 986.854, "stop": 994.382, "duration": 7.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that's your understanding, isn't it?", "start": 994.382, "stop": 995.592, "duration": 1.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, I think that along that line Mr. Judge Finley should also point out that while Judge Miller's opinion was appealed to the Court of Appeals and the Court of Appeals affirmed it, that we took the position that we would carry it no further and we went back to work along with whatever could be done, and I think that --", "start": 995.592, "stop": 1016.052, "duration": 20.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That order was not sought to be brought here.", "start": 1016.052, "stop": 1018.182, "duration": 2.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir.", "start": 1018.182, "stop": 1020.55, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "We let it stay right there and let it go back as such and considered ourselves bound by it.", "start": 1020.55, "stop": 1026.04, "duration": 5.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You could very well bring it here, since you were in the Court of Appeals.", "start": 1026.04, "stop": 1029.425, "duration": 3.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh no sir, no I mean the -- no we lost.", "start": 1029.425, "stop": 1032.333, "duration": 2.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What?", "start": 1032.333, "stop": 1032.915, "duration": 0.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Judge Miller's opinion approving this plan, we opposed that.", "start": 1032.915, "stop": 1037.72, "duration": 4.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 1037.72, "stop": 1038.06, "duration": 0.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "And we urged the Court of Appeals to reverse it, because it required too much time.", "start": 1038.06, "stop": 1042.663, "duration": 4.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Board was satisfied so they wouldn't bring it here and you will rest it on the ground as affirmed by the District Court, as confirmed by the District Court and the District Court's decree affirmed by the Court of Appeals.", "start": 1042.663, "stop": 1055.645, "duration": 12.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir with the theory that would see it worked out.", "start": 1055.645, "stop": 1063.399, "duration": 7.75}, {"text": "With the permission of the Court, I would like to just in a measure, to go into some of the background of this case, because as we see it the factual -- the facts in this case are so clearly set out in the opinion of the Court of Appeals, that in our brief and now we don't think its necessary to go into too great detail, but there are one or two points that I think need emphasizing and that is that the record will show that with the exception of the one time that the School Board asked for affirmative relief when a white parent obtain judgment in a Chancery Court to which Governor Faubus and other people had testified and the Chancery judge ruled that the School Board should be enjoined from carrying out the plan which the District Court had approved.", "start": 1063.399, "stop": 1123.539, "duration": 60.14}, {"text": "The School Board did on that occasion go into Judge Davies and properly Judge Davies enjoined the enforcement of that state judgment, and that was affirmed by the Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit.", "start": 1123.539, "stop": 1138.094, "duration": 14.56}, {"text": "Well with the exception of that, the only relief that the School Board has asked from the District Court is postponement.", "start": 1138.094, "stop": 1148.522, "duration": 10.43}, {"text": "They have asked for no relief in affirmative relief to help this thing along.", "start": 1148.522, "stop": 1153.938, "duration": 5.42}, {"text": "That goes back from the two requests in September of last year and bear in mind that the petition in this case which is before you today, was asked for way back in February, it was around February that they gave up.", "start": 1153.938, "stop": 1169.884, "duration": 15.95}, {"text": "That was when they asked for this relief and it sat there for a while until Chief Judge Gardner assigned Judge Lemley to hear it and the hearing took place in the early part of June.", "start": 1169.884, "stop": 1180.908, "duration": 11.02}, {"text": "So, on that basis it seems to us that as the government points out in its brief and as we point out in our brief, that there was an affirmative duty on the School Board to get help in this situation, and the only objection at all was that the community was opposed to it.", "start": 1180.908, "stop": 1202.704, "duration": 21.8}, {"text": "And the other point that they rely on in their memorandum and in their brief, is that a stay of this will help and in the District Court, in the Court of Appeals and in the response that they filed to our petition, and up to the present day, with the exception of two points, one that Governor Faubus might not be in office two-and-a-half years from now and that certain statutes of Arkansas now being litigated might be decided within two-and-a-half years, with the exception of those points as of this minute, the School Board has not given anybody any information of what they propose to do in the two-and-a-half years while these rights are being suspended.", "start": 1202.704, "stop": 1257.406, "duration": 54.7}, {"text": "And in the question of a stay or the vacation of a stay and in cases cited in our brief we point out that the law is quite similar between the two, especially the Virginia case and the Breswick case and a few others we cite in our brief, that there's got to be a showing of one the irreparable harm on one side as against that on the other side.", "start": 1257.406, "stop": 1281.758, "duration": 24.35}, {"text": "The record shows that these children will graduate.", "start": 1281.758, "stop": 1287.548, "duration": 5.79}, {"text": "So far as matters now stand, if they are in segregated schools next year their rights are just gone, I mean that's the end of that.", "start": 1287.548, "stop": 1297.072, "duration": 9.52}, {"text": "On the other hand, the statute which affirmatively gives the right of the Court, 2101 (f), of any court to stay issuance of mandates, provides that the Court may if necessary require supersedes of some form.", "start": 1297.072, "stop": 1322.113, "duration": 25.04}, {"text": "And again this case solely, because of the peculiar situation, the states is never required to give bond and so they're not even required to give and we have a complete change of status.", "start": 1322.113, "stop": 1337.593, "duration": 15.48}, {"text": "When this case was heard, those children in the Central High School now seven, there were nine, one graduated, Ernest Green graduated, one Minnijean Brown was expelled, leaving seven, those seven were in an integrated school system.", "start": 1337.593, "stop": 1357.464, "duration": 19.87}, {"text": "They had been there for a year.", "start": 1357.464, "stop": 1360.418, "duration": 2.95}, {"text": "Under Judge Lemley's order, they are taken out, and that's going to change the status, there is a physical change of status.", "start": 1360.418, "stop": 1368.688, "duration": 8.27}, {"text": "And they are taken out as of -- it would only be effective so far as they are concerned from the opening of the school, because school had been in recess, but that complete change of status must have some extraordinary reason to be sustained.", "start": 1368.688, "stop": 1384.303, "duration": 15.62}, {"text": "The normal procedure is to maintain the status quo, and I submit that Judge Lemley was the one that should have stayed an order, not the Court of Appeals to stay its order reversing it.", "start": 1384.303, "stop": 1396.93, "duration": 12.63}, {"text": "And we finally, we take the flat decision that on the merits of this case we are entitled to relief, not that we need to establish that point in order to get relief, but we take the position that the opinion of the Court of Appeals was so clear, that the respondents here had nothing that they could successfully bring to this Court, and in many of the rulings of this Court, in Chambers, that if taken into consideration, the possibility of whether or not you actually have a justiciable issue recognizable by this Court.", "start": 1396.93, "stop": 1439.138, "duration": 42.21}, {"text": "And the petitioners had no such case, and yet they can toy around with the situation, and effectively deny these rights by using procedural devices such a motion to stay.", "start": 1439.138, "stop": 1453.691, "duration": 14.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well there is a difference between a justiciable issue and eventually succeeding on it?", "start": 1453.691, "stop": 1461.395, "duration": 7.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "In this Court you need more than a justiciable issue.", "start": 1461.395, "stop": 1464.33, "duration": 2.93}, {"text": "You need an issue that one, is cognizable by this Court, and is sufficient to get a sufficient number of justices to agree with it, I mean it's more than just a justiciable issue.", "start": 1464.33, "stop": 1478.267, "duration": 13.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But when you say they have no justiciable issue, they have a justiciable issue.", "start": 1478.267, "stop": 1482.308, "duration": 4.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh yes, I think there is no question about that, but we take the position that under the Lucy case it has no weight at this time before this Court.", "start": 1482.308, "stop": 1491.241, "duration": 8.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1491.241, "stop": 1500.761, "duration": 9.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would say Mr. Justice Clark that there is considerable authority among educators that it's not well -- it's not good educational practice to transfer students in the middle of the year.", "start": 1500.761, "stop": 1514.869, "duration": 14.11}, {"text": "As to one or two days I imagine that would be all right, but in the mid --", "start": 1514.869, "stop": 1520.311, "duration": 5.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1520.311, "stop": 1524.264, "duration": 3.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, not at all.", "start": 1524.264, "stop": 1526.995, "duration": 2.73}, {"text": "Well I was basing that solely on good educational practices.", "start": 1526.995, "stop": 1532.454, "duration": 5.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Marshal?", "start": 1532.454, "stop": 1533.065, "duration": 0.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 1533.065, "stop": 1533.77, "duration": 0.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you (Inaudible)", "start": 1533.77, "stop": 1550.553, "duration": 16.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I am urging them and --", "start": 1550.553, "stop": 1553.502, "duration": 2.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Conjunctively?", "start": 1553.502, "stop": 1554.368, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Conjunctively and Mr. Justice I would also say that because of the developments now going on in Arkansas, that this case should be decided on its merits and it could be done, there are precedents in this Court where it has been done.", "start": 1554.368, "stop": 1575.523, "duration": 21.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is what you've asked for in your petition here?", "start": 1575.523, "stop": 1577.855, "duration": 2.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "And I also -- that's true Mr. Justice Frankfurter, but I also (Inaudible) to be perfectly frank, I'm thinking about the Lustig case, where as I remember the petition for certiorari was filed during argument and in this case I think that as we said in our original petition for certiorari, which this Court can reconsider on its own motion.", "start": 1577.855, "stop": 1603.051, "duration": 25.2}, {"text": "Our original petition for certiorari, when that was filed this Court said, you will remember that we have no doubt that the Court of Appeals will recognize the vital importance of the time element in this litigation, and that it will act upon the application for a stay or the appeal in ample time to permit arrangements to be made for the next school year.", "start": 1603.051, "stop": 1628.892, "duration": 25.84}, {"text": "And on the basis of that language, which was a basis for denying our petition for certiorari, I think present developments in the eight -- the Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit and conditions as they exist in Arkansas would at least impel this Court to order that it be heard on its merits.", "start": 1628.892, "stop": 1650.406, "duration": 21.51}, {"text": "Now we have no authority as such.", "start": 1650.406, "stop": 1652.787, "duration": 2.38}, {"text": "We could file a petition for certiorari, but we considered it, and to be perfectly frank with the Court, we took the position that it had been done before, and that this Court could reconsider our petition filed in June, and order argument on it or could consider it right here and now.", "start": 1652.787, "stop": 1677.421, "duration": 24.63}, {"text": "And I -- the only thing -- I believe that the way this case stands, there must be a definitive decision, and I use the two together, I mean it's bad English, but it's the best way I can do it, that there be no doubt in Arkansas that the orders of that District Court down there must be respected and cannot be suspended and cannot be interfered with by the legislature or anybody else.", "start": 1677.421, "stop": 1708.219, "duration": 30.8}, {"text": "And less than that, I don't think we'll give these young children the protection that they need and they most certainly deserve and so in answer to your question, I would say that we requested it both and not in the alternative.", "start": 1708.219, "stop": 1727.177, "duration": 18.96}, {"text": "And at this time we respectfully suggest that it would be even better for this Court to decide the case on the merits because the stay, which is being reviewed decided it on the merits, and so this Court in deciding the stay I don't see much chance of doing it, but I do know that technically it could be done without hitting the merits.", "start": 1727.177, "stop": 1752.909, "duration": 25.73}, {"text": "You consider the merits, but the ruling would either be, the stay of the mandate or -- I mean the stay of the -- the vacation of the stay of the mandate or the reverse of Judge Lemley's order.", "start": 1752.909, "stop": 1766.023, "duration": 13.11}, {"text": "But I don't believe that would give us what we thought would be enough, and it's because of the present developments out there, and I think this Court must consider the whole story.", "start": 1766.023, "stop": 1777.265, "duration": 11.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1777.265, "stop": 1778.88, "duration": 1.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 1778.88, "stop": 1779.476, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "You have briefed it (Inaudible)", "start": 1779.476, "stop": 1781.827, "duration": 2.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Brief.", "start": 1781.827, "stop": 1782.327, "duration": 0.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1782.327, "stop": 1784.022, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "We did not, no sir.", "start": 1784.022, "stop": 1786.343, "duration": 2.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1786.343, "stop": 1788.321, "duration": 1.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, we would be prepared to argue and with permission to submit a brief and we could do a brief on this case in less than half a day.", "start": 1788.321, "stop": 1797.467, "duration": 9.15}, {"text": "We are prepared to argue it now, with the right to submit a brief at a late time, because Judge Mathes' opinion of the Court of Appeals is so clear.", "start": 1797.467, "stop": 1809.808, "duration": 12.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Have you discussed with counsel on the other side the possibility or the propriety of arguing the merits here today?", "start": 1809.808, "stop": 1818.31, "duration": 8.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have not sir.", "start": 1818.31, "stop": 1820.372, "duration": 2.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I ask this Mr. Marshall, I can see where you would be interested in having both points raised by you decided, both the stay in the Court of Appeals and also a stay of the opinion below in the District Court, but if this Court should see fit to stay the District Court of opinion, would it then be necessary to also overrule the Court of Appeals on its stay of the mandate?", "start": 1820.372, "stop": 1853.784, "duration": 33.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, Mr. Chief Justice, and I think further that if the Court did it that way, it would still be preserved in the traditional function of the stay of the mandate of the Court of Appeals pending petition to the Supreme Court.", "start": 1853.784, "stop": 1869.169, "duration": 15.38}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "On certiorari?", "start": 1869.169, "stop": 1870.194, "duration": 1.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "On certiorari yes sir, but I think that as long as this case undecided on its merits, our plaintiffs, our petitioners in this case will still be under terrific pressure because of the uncertainty of it, which was recognized by this Court in its denial of original petition for cert.", "start": 1870.194, "stop": 1899.738, "duration": 29.54}, {"text": "And if it were not for the fact that it has been done, I would have hesitated to suggest it, but I think that in several occasions this Court has ordered cases brought up the -- I mean for example under some precedents, as I understand it, was kind of late in the morning when we read them, but we understand that this Court could order the school board to file its petition within one or two days and be heard properly before school is opened or you could consider as I said the petition that we filed.", "start": 1899.738, "stop": 1944.143, "duration": 44.4}, {"text": "May it please the Court on the -- finally I would like to wind this up because I don't think that there's too much law that is necessary because it is certainly not in conflict, we rely on the Virginia case and on down to the present time.", "start": 1944.143, "stop": 1966.835, "duration": 22.69}, {"text": "We also have the -- some British cases in there which all are on the same theory about the power and duty of the Court to stay or to vacate and what can properly be considered by the Court.", "start": 1966.835, "stop": 1981.249, "duration": 14.41}, {"text": "The government in its brief cites the same cases and additional cases and so I would say as said back here that when you weigh, and I for one cannot hardly talk about weighing anything against constitutional rights, I have never been able to find how to do it, but here we have negro children, and the record will show they have done nothing bad except the record will show that one did, the record will show, there's a dispute about it but it will show it and she was expelled so that's no problem, but that these children must be forced to surrender their constitutional rights is unimportant in this Court today.", "start": 1981.249, "stop": 2047.005, "duration": 65.76}, {"text": "The point is set forth in the Court of Appeals' decision and quoting from the Strutwear Knitting case, the government's case brief which was filed this morning points out that it's really a surrender to obstructionist and mob action and that is much more destructive of democratic government than it is of some few Negroes' rights.", "start": 2047.005, "stop": 2077.6, "duration": 30.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2077.6, "stop": 2083.203, "duration": 5.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not the Eighth Circuit's opinion.", "start": 2083.203, "stop": 2085.29, "duration": 2.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2085.29, "stop": 2105.274, "duration": 19.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 2105.274, "stop": 2106.792, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is the other point (Inaudible)", "start": 2106.792, "stop": 2111.858, "duration": 5.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 2111.858, "stop": 2112.226, "duration": 0.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2112.226, "stop": 2120.9, "duration": 8.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm complaining about Judge Lemley's order being in effect.", "start": 2120.9, "stop": 2127.429, "duration": 6.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Which is the first (Inaudible)", "start": 2127.429, "stop": 2131.431, "duration": 4}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Which is reversed by opinion and – yes sir.", "start": 2131.431, "stop": 2134.927, "duration": 3.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible) statement, isn't that right?", "start": 2134.927, "stop": 2150.467, "duration": 15.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2150.467, "stop": 2152.139, "duration": 1.67}, {"text": "The point I – I think I get it, I thought I cleared it up with the Chief Justice's question which is, as I understood the question, my answer was that if this Court stayed Judge Lemley's order, there would not be need for touching the Court of Appeals.", "start": 2152.139, "stop": 2176.809, "duration": 24.67}, {"text": "And I try to make it clear that what we wanted to get the original court orders in there.", "start": 2176.809, "stop": 2184.461, "duration": 7.65}, {"text": "And Judge Lemley's order was standing in the way and certainly that would be correct.", "start": 2184.461, "stop": 2189.223, "duration": 4.76}, {"text": "And I mean I'm making this statement on my feet but I – we have given it some thought and the reason we put both in was because originally, you were right sir it was thought among lawyers that are working on this that it was an all proposition.", "start": 2189.223, "stop": 2210.308, "duration": 21.09}, {"text": "And --", "start": 2210.308, "stop": 2210.559, "duration": 0.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2210.559, "stop": 2213.14, "duration": 2.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "And in the –", "start": 2213.14, "stop": 2213.818, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2213.818, "stop": 2217.135, "duration": 3.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think it would but I, as I said, in addition to that as things now stand I don't think either of them will be enough.", "start": 2217.135, "stop": 2224.895, "duration": 7.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2224.895, "stop": 2238.237, "duration": 13.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's absolutely normal, but I –", "start": 2238.237, "stop": 2240.952, "duration": 2.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2240.952, "stop": 2242.427, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- as I understand it is done every day in day – indeed the books so say.", "start": 2242.427, "stop": 2247.856, "duration": 5.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Would you be good enough to tell me, what consideration relevant to determining whether the stay of the Court of Appeals should be vacated, what method of equitable jurisdiction for this Court's power over the lower court, what matters that are relevant to determining whether that stay should be vacated would not be relevant in determining whether Judge Lemley's original order should be vacated?", "start": 2247.856, "stop": 2290.266, "duration": 42.41}, {"text": "Why do you – why does – what legal consideration is there for vacating Judge Lemley's stay disregarding the fact that he has been reviewed by the Court of Appeals and it has taken action on it and has reversed it and has then decided to grant a stay of its reversal.", "start": 2290.266, "stop": 2310.893, "duration": 20.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it's our position Mr. Justice Frankfurter that normally that's what's done in the state of mandate, but when in effect the decision, the issue of the case is a stay, a suspension, the merits of the case is a suspension, then when the Court of Appeals decides that the other side is not entitled to a suspension in its opinion and then suspends in its order as I said in the beginning it's an absolute anomaly.", "start": 2310.893, "stop": 2348.533, "duration": 37.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That maybe a very good reason why you should argue that the stay should be vacated, but I do not understand the argument that says we don't have to bother about that, we just deal with Judge Lemley's order and vacate that?", "start": 2348.533, "stop": 2365.424, "duration": 16.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh I understand you now Mr. Justice Frankfurter.", "start": 2365.424, "stop": 2368.91, "duration": 3.49}, {"text": "The – I think the real problem in this case is as to whether or not the court wants to go into the merits, I think that's it.", "start": 2368.91, "stop": 2379.763, "duration": 10.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The merits in which you use the term 'the merits' seem to equal, the same merits in determining on the propriety of the stay as in asking us to vacate the order which he originally refused to vacate.", "start": 2379.763, "stop": 2395.983, "duration": 16.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "We would make the same argument and indeed in our brief we said the argument applied to both situations.", "start": 2395.983, "stop": 2400.738, "duration": 4.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And I don't understand why you offer us the suggestion that we don't have to bother about the stay, we can deal with Judge Lemley, to me that is most unreal kind of thought.", "start": 2400.738, "stop": 2411.824, "duration": 11.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think sir, of course Mr. Justice Frankfurter I cannot getaway from the fact that it's Judge Lemley order that does the damage.", "start": 2411.824, "stop": 2423.733, "duration": 11.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes but that has been dealt with.", "start": 2423.733, "stop": 2425.662, "duration": 1.93}, {"text": "This Court refused to deal with Judge Lemley order last June.", "start": 2425.662, "stop": 2430.083, "duration": 4.42}, {"text": "It remitted the appealability of that to the Eighth Circuit.", "start": 2430.083, "stop": 2434.065, "duration": 3.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Circuit.", "start": 2434.065, "stop": 2434.912, "duration": 0.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Eighth Circuit has dealt with it.", "start": 2434.912, "stop": 2437.071, "duration": 2.16}, {"text": "The Eighth Circuit said it was wrong.", "start": 2437.071, "stop": 2439.312, "duration": 2.24}, {"text": "It then vacated -- it then granted a stay in order to give opportunity under the acts of Congress to have this Court apply for a certiorari and what you are here for, here I respectfully submit is to argue that that stay should never been granted.", "start": 2439.312, "stop": 2456.754, "duration": 17.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have argued it.", "start": 2456.754, "stop": 2458.108, "duration": 1.35}, {"text": "I am prepared to argue it Mr. Justice Frankfurter but I did not want to get into the point of upsetting what normally is procedural is -- as procedural device for appealing to this Court.", "start": 2458.108, "stop": 2477.017, "duration": 18.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But if this Court as you urge has power to vacate that stay --", "start": 2477.017, "stop": 2481.912, "duration": 4.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "It does have that power.", "start": 2481.912, "stop": 2482.716, "duration": 0.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- then no procedural entanglements of a Court of Appeals are relevant to that power.", "start": 2482.716, "stop": 2489.89, "duration": 7.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that's -- I am sure that's correct sir, but Mr. Justice Frankfurter I still go back to my other question --", "start": 2489.89, "stop": 2498.938, "duration": 9.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 2498.938, "stop": 2499.63, "duration": 0.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- that whether you consider the vacation of the stay of the Eighth Circuit or whether you consider a stay of Judge Lemley's order, the merits are so entwined that this is one of the type of cases where it -- it points to the need for it.", "start": 2499.63, "stop": 2523.725, "duration": 24.09}, {"text": "The --", "start": 2523.725, "stop": 2523.854, "duration": 0.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What you are saying is that if as a matter of authorized Congressional action, a petition for certiorari can be brought here by the school board, that such a petition would raise claims so frivolous that there was no justification for staying the reversal by the Court of Appeals?", "start": 2523.854, "stop": 2545.53, "duration": 21.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "We take that position and we've tried to develop it.", "start": 2545.53, "stop": 2548.572, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "It's just without merit, but in the posture of this case it seems to me the easiest way would be to doing both.", "start": 2548.572, "stop": 2556.114, "duration": 7.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right.", "start": 2556.114, "stop": 2557.953, "duration": 1.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was the proprietary of this stay argued in the Court of Appeals fully?", "start": 2557.953, "stop": 2562.681, "duration": 4.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, as a matter of fact the application for stay and the ruling on the application were both the same day and we got our copies the next day.", "start": 2562.681, "stop": 2575.72, "duration": 13.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was the argument displayed?", "start": 2575.72, "stop": 2577.437, "duration": 1.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just, they just filed a motion of stay and when it was received it was granted and --", "start": 2577.437, "stop": 2583.696, "duration": 6.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible), is it not?", "start": 2583.696, "stop": 2586.618, "duration": 2.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir we filed a motion that it be issued forthwith.", "start": 2586.618, "stop": 2589.937, "duration": 3.32}, {"text": "We filed that ahead of it, we filed it the very next day after the opinion came down.", "start": 2589.937, "stop": 2595.052, "duration": 5.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "And they filed theirs?", "start": 2595.052, "stop": 2596.316, "duration": 1.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then they filed their motion to stay and on the day it arrived in the Court of Appeals, it was decided and it is also along that line which was pointed out in the Virginian case which is cited in our brief where the court took notice of the fact that the stay was given without reasons.", "start": 2596.316, "stop": 2618.236, "duration": 21.92}, {"text": "The stay in this case was really given on to the procedural statute which says that a stay can be granted for the purpose of petition in the Supreme Court, but nothing at all on the merits and I presume the merits weren't considered.", "start": 2618.236, "stop": 2631.668, "duration": 13.43}, {"text": "And so that at this -- at this stage of the litigation is the first time that the merits, and I use merits merely as to the merits as to whether or not an order is entitled to be stayed, that for the first time the merits of that are being considered for the first time.", "start": 2631.668, "stop": 2649.558, "duration": 17.89}, {"text": "And we take the position that when you balance these rights of these kids involved plus what this, this Court said in the Brown case, the public interest, meaning the public interest of the United States over against a school board's position that there are some people that don't want to let this thing go through then certainly the equities involved lean toward the protection of those constitutional rights rather than the postponement of them.", "start": 2649.558, "stop": 2681.357, "duration": 31.8}, {"text": "And I believe that I have to recognize that is an issue in this case and is expressed by the Court of Appeals, they said there is no problem about it.", "start": 2681.357, "stop": 2690.627, "duration": 9.27}, {"text": "They just cannot be surrender -- and they mentioned the case that I said before the Strutwear Knit case which is famous for the expression about handling bank robbers you, you don't close the banks you put the bank robbers in jail.", "start": 2690.627, "stop": 2705.353, "duration": 14.73}, {"text": "And therefore it seems to me and I don't want to prolong the argument that we are entitled to both, at the same time it seems to me that the real justice of the case would not be required by going into either, but that either on our petition for cert originally filed or by some other procedural device that this Court be given an opportunity to pass on the merits.", "start": 2705.353, "stop": 2743.368, "duration": 38.01}, {"text": "As I said before petitioners are perfectly willing to argue the case on the merits even though we were successful insofar as opinion of the lower court was concerned.", "start": 2743.368, "stop": 2755.654, "duration": 12.29}, {"text": "The law I think of reading of the three briefs, our brief, the school board's brief and the government's brief, demonstrates that there is really no serious conflict of the law as to the authority of this Court to act.", "start": 2755.654, "stop": 2777.259, "duration": 21.61}, {"text": "There is a conflict between the school board as to whether this Court should act, and on that we think that the equities on the side of school children are such that the only relief that can be granted that will be effective will be for the decision on the merits.", "start": 2777.259, "stop": 2797.585, "duration": 20.33}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Marshall.", "start": 2797.585, "stop": 2798.516, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 2798.516, "stop": 2798.637, "duration": 0.12}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think I am clear about this statute which I understand postpones the school opening until September 15th.", "start": 2798.637, "stop": 2808.597, "duration": 9.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "That in the state legislature or Arkansas, I don't know whether it passed or not but it's there pending I understand.", "start": 2808.597, "stop": 2817.162, "duration": 8.56}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So presently --", "start": 2817.162, "stop": 2818.656, "duration": 1.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "September 8th.", "start": 2818.656, "stop": 2819.425, "duration": 0.77}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "September 8th is --", "start": 2819.425, "stop": 2820.467, "duration": 1.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "September 8th is the deadline and I think if I can think ahead about when the 20 days for the mandate of the Court of Appeals, that would be up on the 7th, but the stay gave them 30 days from the date of judgment.", "start": 2820.467, "stop": 2835.613, "duration": 15.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2835.613, "stop": 2838.966, "duration": 3.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, at least I haven't received a copy of it.", "start": 2838.966, "stop": 2842.864, "duration": 3.9}, {"text": "No sir.", "start": 2842.864, "stop": 2844.228, "duration": 1.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "The time expired for constitution for rehearing?", "start": 2844.228, "stop": 2851.135, "duration": 6.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Ten day I think it is.", "start": 2851.135, "stop": 2852.207, "duration": 1.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2852.207, "stop": 2857.869, "duration": 5.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "On the 19th, was it, 18th, no sir, no sir it was 18th yes sir.", "start": 2857.869, "stop": 2861.831, "duration": 3.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2861.831, "stop": 2862.822, "duration": 0.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 2862.822, "stop": 2865.856, "duration": 3.03}, {"text": "If there are no further questions if Your Honor please we will reserve the time for not necessarily that we will use it, but if we may reserve it in case if we need.", "start": 2865.856, "stop": 2875.448, "duration": 9.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is the Court of Appeals record before us?", "start": 2875.448, "stop": 2878.3, "duration": 2.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "The copy of the record, no sir.", "start": 2878.3, "stop": 2879.737, "duration": 1.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You have a record.", "start": 2879.737, "stop": 2880.744, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, I can do this Mr. Justice Black.", "start": 2880.744, "stop": 2884.898, "duration": 4.15}, {"text": "We have a copy of the transcript of testimony and the pleading files, we don't have that with us but we --", "start": 2884.898, "stop": 2893.715, "duration": 8.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was the decision by Judge Lemley entirely on oral testimony or was there affidavit?", "start": 2893.715, "stop": 2900.108, "duration": 6.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well no affidavits it was all testimony and exhibits, a whole basket full of newspapers.", "start": 2900.108, "stop": 2907.404, "duration": 7.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "How many days was the proceeding?", "start": 2907.404, "stop": 2908.954, "duration": 1.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Three, practically three days, not five and the testimony was mostly from the school board people showing what a difficult problem they had from the Chief of Police, the Chairman of the School Board and the only testimony produced by the plaintiffs in this case petitioners here with two expert witnesses as to how to run a – how a school system could be run.", "start": 2908.954, "stop": 2935.177, "duration": 26.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did I understand you are required to Judge, Justice Black that -- indicate that you have a copy --", "start": 2935.177, "stop": 2941.396, "duration": 6.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Of the transcript.", "start": 2941.396, "stop": 2942.038, "duration": 0.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- you and/or Mr. Butler, each have copy of the proceeding.", "start": 2942.038, "stop": 2946.386, "duration": 4.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "We each have a copy of the transcript and I would be very glad to deposit the transcript copy with the clerk.", "start": 2946.386, "stop": 2953.729, "duration": 7.34}, {"text": "I would be very happy to do and will so do.", "start": 2953.729, "stop": 2956.243, "duration": 2.51}, {"text": "The --", "start": 2956.243, "stop": 2956.352, "duration": 0.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was it printed or merely typewritten?", "start": 2956.352, "stop": 2957.962, "duration": 1.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was typewritten.", "start": 2957.962, "stop": 2959.338, "duration": 1.38}, {"text": "We were permitted to go up on the original record from the Court of Appeals, including the type transcript and the argument was based on the typed transcript or the testimony.", "start": 2959.338, "stop": 2972.42, "duration": 13.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "To accelerate the disposition?", "start": 2972.42, "stop": 2973.804, "duration": 1.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 2973.804, "stop": 2974.696, "duration": 0.89}, {"text": "They were holding a special term and they gave us that permission.", "start": 2974.696, "stop": 2977.456, "duration": 2.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "How many copies?", "start": 2977.456, "stop": 2979.636, "duration": 2.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "How many copies do we have?", "start": 2979.636, "stop": 2981.505, "duration": 1.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "How many copies were before the Court of Appeals?", "start": 2981.505, "stop": 2984.148, "duration": 2.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Two so far as I -- two so far as I know.", "start": 2984.148, "stop": 2988.813, "duration": 4.66}, {"text": "I think that's correct isn't it, that's all that I know of sir.", "start": 2988.813, "stop": 2992.829, "duration": 4.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What in addition to that transcript (Inaudible) to have entire record capable of being used on a petition for certiorari?", "start": 2992.829, "stop": 3003.726, "duration": 10.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Justice Black I don't think the pleadings would be necessary.", "start": 3003.726, "stop": 3007.465, "duration": 3.74}, {"text": "They are very brief and you would no trouble, they could be run off.", "start": 3007.465, "stop": 3011.045, "duration": 3.58}, {"text": "The exhibits consisted of a large batch of newspapers which could -- instead of being printed could be deposited with the Court, and so I don't think it would be necessary to put those in the record, and you wouldn't need -- so far as I can concede, you wouldn't need anything but the transcript and the pleadings, both of which we have and we're going to file the transcript and unless we file the pleadings too at the same time, copy of it.", "start": 3011.045, "stop": 3040.821, "duration": 29.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler, you may proceed.", "start": 3040.821, "stop": 3047.919, "duration": 7.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "May it please Your Honors?", "start": 3047.919, "stop": 3052.013, "duration": 4.09}, {"text": "To straighten out a few things that counsel for the NAACP may not have been aware of, your clerk called me several days ago, after taking with the clerk of the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals and finding that the record of that Court had been returned to Little Rock.", "start": 3052.013, "stop": 3076.071, "duration": 24.06}, {"text": "I located it, and mailed it here immediately and it is my information that the entire record from the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals is here in your clerk's office.", "start": 3076.071, "stop": 3090.285, "duration": 14.21}, {"text": "That has attached to it three such typewritten volumes that each of about this size, which shows all of the testimony that was given in before Judge Lemley in approximately three-day hearing in his Court, in June.", "start": 3090.285, "stop": 3116.277, "duration": 25.99}, {"text": "In addition to that, there was a large packet as counsel has referred to, of various exhibits.", "start": 3116.277, "stop": 3124.07, "duration": 7.79}, {"text": "They were not identified each separately but were introduced as a packet.", "start": 3124.07, "stop": 3130.877, "duration": 6.81}, {"text": "They were largely newspaper items which Judge Lemley took into consideration to show the confusion and turmoil and the position that this school board was put in.", "start": 3130.877, "stop": 3143.349, "duration": 12.47}, {"text": "I thought that might be helpful for the Court to know that.", "start": 3143.349, "stop": 3148.212, "duration": 4.86}, {"text": "One other thing that I would like to mention in passing at the beginning, which I think counsel was somewhat confused on or uninformed on.", "start": 3148.212, "stop": 3162.036, "duration": 13.82}, {"text": "At the time this School Board requested a temporary stay, purely temporary, before Judge Davies in September of 1957, the troops, National Guard had either been ordered out or it was known that they were to be ordered out.", "start": 3162.036, "stop": 3184.648, "duration": 22.61}, {"text": "And at that time there was an injunction that had been ordered by the local Chancery Court, directing this School Board to do exactly opposite from what had been planned and what Judge Miller had ordered in August of 1956.", "start": 3184.648, "stop": 3205.52, "duration": 20.87}, {"text": "Now that was the purpose behind the School Board going into Court at that time and asking merely for a temporary delay, they did that for several reasons.", "start": 3205.52, "stop": 3219.842, "duration": 14.32}, {"text": "In the first place they were caught in an untenable position.", "start": 3219.842, "stop": 3225.934, "duration": 6.09}, {"text": "As a matter of fact they have been there continuously since then up to this very day.", "start": 3225.934, "stop": 3233.378, "duration": 7.44}, {"text": "They also felt that under the circumstances with troops moving in and out of the city and perhaps strife and turmoil to follow, that the wise thing to do was for the Court to have an opportunity to tell it, the School Board, what it should do under those circumstances.", "start": 3233.378, "stop": 3257.718, "duration": 24.34}, {"text": "The School Board felt that a temporary, not the kind of delay that Judge Lemley had given over a long period of time, two-and-a-half years, but for that immediate situation, that it was necessary to get it clarified.", "start": 3257.718, "stop": 3275.506, "duration": 17.79}, {"text": "A third reason for the School Board to go in at that particular time before Judge Davies, was that here they were ordered by two different courts, to do exactly opposite things, or at least partially opposite, and they felt on advice of counsel that it was advisable for them to show that there was no motive on their part of contempt of the federal court order.", "start": 3275.506, "stop": 3304.323, "duration": 28.82}, {"text": "Now, I think those are the reasons behind what has been referred to as the petition for delay of September 1957.", "start": 3304.323, "stop": 3315.796, "duration": 11.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler may I ask whether Mr. Marshall was correct, because I am – inferences I drew from Judge Devies' -- one of his judgements that there was two separate legal steps taken on behalf of the school board; one, a request for instructions and two, this motion for temporary injunction --", "start": 3315.796, "stop": 3338.173, "duration": 22.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Mr. Justice Frankfurter as I understand it and as I recall it rather, those were combined, yes.", "start": 3338.173, "stop": 3345.414, "duration": 7.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 3345.414, "stop": 3348.175, "duration": 2.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Think it had --", "start": 3348.175, "stop": 3348.387, "duration": 0.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or combined he dealt with them, as I read his judgment, he dealt with them in a combined disposition.", "start": 3348.387, "stop": 3353.88, "duration": 5.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that --", "start": 3353.88, "stop": 3354.02, "duration": 0.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I just want to be sure, maybe it's pedantic, whether those were two separate steps taken before and which he then combined into a single disposition, because he speaks separately of motion, his order of September 3rd and the Court having considered, having appeared (Inaudible), and that Court having considered the petition for instruction by sentencing.", "start": 3354.02, "stop": 3384.339, "duration": 30.32}, {"text": "It's not a matter of (Inaudible) to this case and it's certainly not, but I just in the interest of accuracy want to know what the board did, whether it asked for instructions and also at the same time asked Judge Davies to suspend this thing or stay this thing for a temporary time.", "start": 3384.339, "stop": 3399.778, "duration": 15.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor so many things have happened since then.", "start": 3399.778, "stop": 3402.003, "duration": 2.23}, {"text": "I would prefer to refer to the record itself rather than rely on my memory even though I was present.", "start": 3402.003, "stop": 3409.572, "duration": 7.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The reason for my asking, it is that the record doesn't set forth these two documents and Judge Davies' own statements leave me in doubt, all right?", "start": 3409.572, "stop": 3418.706, "duration": 9.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler may I ask you this question, in view of the opinion of the Court of Appeals overruling Judge Lemley, is the School Board acting under any compulsion to desegregate this school?", "start": 3418.706, "stop": 3439.182, "duration": 20.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir not at the moment, if I understand Your Honor's question.", "start": 3439.182, "stop": 3446.078, "duration": 6.9}, {"text": "They are not acting under any other compulsion.", "start": 3446.078, "stop": 3448.953, "duration": 2.88}, {"text": "Now there are acts one and that's one other thing that I wanted to mention, and that is there has been some statement of the delay of the School Board in opening the high schools in Little Rock or all of the schools, as a matter of fact.", "start": 3448.953, "stop": 3466.728, "duration": 17.78}, {"text": "The School Board on its own motion let us say, postponed it until September the 8th.", "start": 3466.728, "stop": 3476.766, "duration": 10.04}, {"text": "There is a statute which will be passed, I think it has already been passed, if not it will be passed today, postponing the opening of school until September the 15th, that is my information.", "start": 3476.766, "stop": 3494.681, "duration": 17.91}, {"text": "Now of course the School Board would have to obey the statute in regard to opening or closing school, because --", "start": 3494.681, "stop": 3505.823, "duration": 11.14}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is the time for registration?", "start": 3505.823, "stop": 3507.681, "duration": 1.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 3507.681, "stop": 3508.217, "duration": 0.54}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is the time for registration?", "start": 3508.217, "stop": 3509.785, "duration": 1.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Time for registration originally is about nine.", "start": 3509.785, "stop": 3515.524, "duration": 5.74}, {"text": "I have the President of the School Board here with me, he is the counsel and -- they have already had registration I'm informed Mr. Justice --", "start": 3515.524, "stop": 3531.236, "duration": 15.71}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And this bill for opening the -- delaying the opening of the school until the 15th, there is nothing to do with registration?", "start": 3531.236, "stop": 3540.747, "duration": 9.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't think it affects registration, no sir.", "start": 3540.747, "stop": 3544.51, "duration": 3.76}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "And these petitioners are registered?", "start": 3544.51, "stop": 3546.2, "duration": 1.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "These petitioners are registered under the order of Judge Lemley's delay, under his order, yes.", "start": 3546.2, "stop": 3556.737, "duration": 10.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there (Inaudible) some other schools?", "start": 3556.737, "stop": 3560.94, "duration": 4.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir that is my information, that they are already registered in the school that they originally were in.", "start": 3560.94, "stop": 3571.876, "duration": 10.94}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 3571.876, "stop": 3580.622, "duration": 8.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Perhaps, yes sir.", "start": 3580.622, "stop": 3582.037, "duration": 1.41}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is there a doubt about it?", "start": 3582.037, "stop": 3583.785, "duration": 1.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir there is some doubt about it.", "start": 3583.785, "stop": 3585.382, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible) by virtue of the postponement of Judge Lemley's second order, of Judge Lemley's order, that's the only intervening circumstance.", "start": 3585.382, "stop": 3595.448, "duration": 10.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes that was the intervening circumstance and the stay ordered by the Eighth Circuit, yes sir.", "start": 3595.448, "stop": 3601.661, "duration": 6.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "They are -- their names are physical, physically on the appropriate register of the class to which they were assigned –", "start": 3601.661, "stop": 3611.38, "duration": 9.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I must suggest –", "start": 3611.38, "stop": 3611.557, "duration": 0.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I am not talking about legal consequence.", "start": 3611.557, "stop": 3613.092, "duration": 1.54}, {"text": "I am not talking about legal consequence but to carry out Justice Harlan's question they, they were in that school for a year.", "start": 3613.092, "stop": 3620.548, "duration": 7.46}, {"text": "They must have been registered when they were admitted in, was it in '57?", "start": 3620.548, "stop": 3625.451, "duration": 4.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh yes, they oh yes they were registered.", "start": 3625.451, "stop": 3626.261, "duration": 0.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "They were physically on the books.", "start": 3626.261, "stop": 3628.526, "duration": 2.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh yes, yes sir.", "start": 3628.526, "stop": 3630.32, "duration": 1.79}, {"text": "Yes and in September of '57 perhaps I misunderstood your question.", "start": 3630.32, "stop": 3634.815, "duration": 4.49}, {"text": "In September of '57 they were registered in Central High School and remained there all during the school year both on registration and physical being there.", "start": 3634.815, "stop": 3649.308, "duration": 14.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And but for Judge Lemley's order they would have gone back whenever the school opened to their appropriate classes?", "start": 3649.308, "stop": 3657.705, "duration": 8.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Legally that is correct yes, yes.", "start": 3657.705, "stop": 3659.539, "duration": 1.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's what I am talking about.", "start": 3659.539, "stop": 3660.902, "duration": 1.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler may I ask one other question, has the school board determined what it will do toward desegregation or toward leaving the matter as it was last year in the event this Court declines to grant this stay?", "start": 3660.902, "stop": 3678.763, "duration": 17.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, it has not decided because it's almost compelled to see what statutes are passed by the general assembly now in session and various other things which it has no way of determining.", "start": 3678.763, "stop": 3695.65, "duration": 16.89}, {"text": "And this school, school board no doubt will have to meet those situations as they arise, as they have had to do all the past year.", "start": 3695.65, "stop": 3706.488, "duration": 10.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the plan which was put before Judge Miller that which he approved and which the Court of Appeals confirmed has never been revoked by the school board?", "start": 3706.488, "stop": 3715.907, "duration": 9.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir it has not, it has not been revoked, no sir.", "start": 3715.907, "stop": 3721.406, "duration": 5.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well as to these specific children, have they been assigned to any school?", "start": 3721.406, "stop": 3727.578, "duration": 6.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It is my affirmation Mr. Chief Justice that they have now --", "start": 3727.578, "stop": 3731.877, "duration": 4.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "They have not been.", "start": 3731.877, "stop": 3732.774, "duration": 0.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "They have not -- yes sir they have now been assigned to the all Negro school, the new high school there of Horace Mann.", "start": 3732.774, "stop": 3741.978, "duration": 9.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well isn't that, isn't that action towards segregating them again?", "start": 3741.978, "stop": 3748.068, "duration": 6.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh!", "start": 3748.068, "stop": 3748.31, "duration": 0.24}, {"text": "Yes sir it is.", "start": 3748.31, "stop": 3749.557, "duration": 1.25}, {"text": "It is, that and that was done, that was done under the order of Judge Lemley's decision.", "start": 3749.557, "stop": 3755.177, "duration": 5.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3755.177, "stop": 3755.672, "duration": 0.49}, {"text": "Well then my point is this.", "start": 3755.672, "stop": 3757.787, "duration": 2.11}, {"text": "If this Court does not stay the order of the Court of Appeals withholding its mandate then the school board will proceed to segregate these pupils who are plaintiffs in this case.", "start": 3757.787, "stop": 3775.861, "duration": 18.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 3775.861, "stop": 3776.583, "duration": 0.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3776.583, "stop": 3778.056, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did they transferred them --", "start": 3778.056, "stop": 3783.251, "duration": 5.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well now that the school board President informed me and of course he is correct hat that we don't know that they have actually been registered.", "start": 3783.251, "stop": 3793.81, "duration": 10.56}, {"text": "As a matter of fact that the point I was making a moment ago is that registration generally of most of the students in Little Rock has been accomplished within the last few days.", "start": 3793.81, "stop": 3805.48, "duration": 11.67}, {"text": "Now actually these students that are in question have been up here, they have been traveling around, I doubt that since even the school superintendent has been gone for the last couple of days whether he knows that these -- that all of these particular students have actually registered.", "start": 3805.48, "stop": 3825.454, "duration": 19.97}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What does registration involve?", "start": 3825.454, "stop": 3827.346, "duration": 1.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Registration simply involves the request by the student himself under general, under the general rules of the school board to indicate that he is planning to attend that particular school --", "start": 3827.346, "stop": 3847.825, "duration": 20.48}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well where does he register --", "start": 3847.825, "stop": 3849.254, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- that day.", "start": 3849.254, "stop": 3849.882, "duration": 0.63}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Does he go to the school itself --", "start": 3849.882, "stop": 3851.402, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "At the school yes sir.", "start": 3851.402, "stop": 3852.416, "duration": 1.01}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Where he has been assigned?", "start": 3852.416, "stop": 3853.52, "duration": 1.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Each school yes sir.", "start": 3853.52, "stop": 3854.693, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That applies both to segregated and the Central High school --", "start": 3854.693, "stop": 3857.644, "duration": 2.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh!", "start": 3857.644, "stop": 3857.809, "duration": 0.17}, {"text": "Yes all students must register, yes sir.", "start": 3857.809, "stop": 3861.395, "duration": 3.59}, {"text": "All students and that has been the customary practice for years.", "start": 3861.395, "stop": 3864.168, "duration": 2.77}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Beginning of each school year they must register.", "start": 3864.168, "stop": 3866.05, "duration": 1.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, oh yes they are registered so that the school authorities will know who is going to be where and how many they can expect.", "start": 3866.05, "stop": 3873.137, "duration": 7.09}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What I don't quite get is this, must register that is register up here at the very school to which the pupil has been assigned?", "start": 3873.137, "stop": 3883.828, "duration": 10.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, that's my understanding.", "start": 3883.828, "stop": 3884.508, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- these children have ever appeared at the all Negro high school?", "start": 3884.508, "stop": 3890.724, "duration": 6.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I do not know whether they have appeared there or anywhere else as a matter of fact.", "start": 3890.724, "stop": 3896.795, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "The point I was making a moment ago in answered one of other justice's question was that registration generally in Little Rock has already been accomplished and just within the past few days.", "start": 3896.795, "stop": 3910.001, "duration": 13.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But my only point was this Mr. Butler if this Court does not grant a stay to order of the Court of Appeals is it the purpose of the school board to assign these youngsters involved in this case to an all-Negro school?", "start": 3910.001, "stop": 3930.937, "duration": 20.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 3930.937, "stop": 3931.809, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's all.", "start": 3931.809, "stop": 3933.138, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you have a system of transfer in the middle of --?", "start": 3933.138, "stop": 3935.474, "duration": 2.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir we do.", "start": 3935.474, "stop": 3937.377, "duration": 1.9}, {"text": "Many transfers are made from time to time.", "start": 3937.377, "stop": 3940.594, "duration": 3.22}, {"text": "Each transfer is taken up on its own merits and ordinarily if the family moves from one geographical location to another or for various other reasons they are transferred during the school year that is not an uncustomary proceeding.", "start": 3940.594, "stop": 3955.671, "duration": 15.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But whites to white schools and Negroes to Negro schools?", "start": 3955.671, "stop": 3962.098, "duration": 6.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well no --", "start": 3962.098, "stop": 3963.553, "duration": 1.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Have you ever transferred -- do they ever transfer any Negroes in Little Rock to a White school or Whites to a Negro school by reason of moving a residence?", "start": 3963.553, "stop": 3974.162, "duration": 10.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice in Little Rock until this past year it was, and for the past 70 years ever since there has been a public school system in Little Rock, it has been segregated in the public school systems there.", "start": 3974.162, "stop": 3988.524, "duration": 14.36}, {"text": "So there has never theretofore been any transfer from Negro schools to White school or vice versa.", "start": 3988.524, "stop": 3997.604, "duration": 9.08}, {"text": "The transfer of pupils from one school to another whether it's White or Negro is a process that goes on every school year, not just at the beginning of the year, that's when they all register.", "start": 3997.604, "stop": 4016.759, "duration": 19.16}, {"text": "And ordinarily those students stay in that particular school, the balance of that year, but there are many exceptions to that and there are transfers during the course of the year.", "start": 4016.759, "stop": 4028.107, "duration": 11.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And am I right in understanding that under the plan, approved, submitted by the board and the approved by Judge Miller a state by stage carrying out the desegregation scheme that Central High School is the only school in Little Rock in which the plan became operative.", "start": 4028.107, "stop": 4049.41, "duration": 21.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "As a practical matter that was the only one, yes sir.", "start": 4049.41, "stop": 4052.176, "duration": 2.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't know what that means.", "start": 4052.176, "stop": 4052.969, "duration": 0.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "There were three -- there were three high schools, Central High School, Horace Mann High School and Hall High School.", "start": 4052.969, "stop": 4060.592, "duration": 7.62}, {"text": "Horace Mann High School is a new school so is Hall High School.", "start": 4060.592, "stop": 4065.239, "duration": 4.65}, {"text": "Central high school has been in its present physical plan for some 25 to 30 years.", "start": 4065.239, "stop": 4071.887, "duration": 6.65}, {"text": "The only applicants that were made for any racial mixing or integration to the best of my knowledge –", "start": 4071.887, "stop": 4084.549, "duration": 12.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Was at Central High School –", "start": 4084.549, "stop": 4085.037, "duration": 0.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- was at Central High School and some 17 first started out becoming eligible for that.", "start": 4085.037, "stop": 4092.553, "duration": 7.52}, {"text": "There were 70 some odd applied.", "start": 4092.553, "stop": 4095.705, "duration": 3.15}, {"text": "For various reasons they withdrew either voluntarily or otherwise and it finally came down to nine and ended up the school year with seven.", "start": 4095.705, "stop": 4105.714, "duration": 10.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler if you were to assume that the court had not issued a stay and that the (Inaudible) argument by an order came down approving a plan and requiring integration, would it be feasible or practical within the practice of the school board in keeping with the order of the court if such an order was entered and then transfer the students if is so ordered from whatever school they were in to an integrated school or would you have to wait a year as Mr. Justice --", "start": 4105.714, "stop": 4148.567, "duration": 42.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh!", "start": 4148.567, "stop": 4148.756, "duration": 0.19}, {"text": "No, no sir you wouldn't have to wait a year, they -- The point that I am making and I think Mr. Justice Clark what you are asking is the registration at the beginning of school is not necessarily held in (Inaudible) during the entire school year.", "start": 4148.756, "stop": 4164.712, "duration": 15.96}, {"text": "Now they try to just for the sake of continuity to keep as many children as possible in a particular school, but there are various circumstances as I understand that come up throughout the year whereby pupils are permitted to transfer from one school to another.", "start": 4164.712, "stop": 4186.768, "duration": 22.06}, {"text": "I trust I have answered your question --", "start": 4186.768, "stop": 4189.131, "duration": 2.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "We heard the case on the merits rather than passing on the stays, they would just say the court didn't pass on the stay at all, just referred the case on the merits in a later date and the judgment was against you, then there would be no reason that you knew of why the School Board could not at that time transfer the students from whatever school they were in to a integrated school.", "start": 4189.131, "stop": 4214.822, "duration": 25.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, I know of no reason why that couldn't be done.", "start": 4214.822, "stop": 4217.891, "duration": 3.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Wouldn't you, if it's a fair question, when do you contemplate filing petition here?", "start": 4217.891, "stop": 4223.647, "duration": 5.76}, {"text": "You have until the 20th I believe.", "start": 4223.647, "stop": 4227.153, "duration": 3.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor we were working on it when we had to drop that and file a response to the motion for vacating the stay, and we have simply not had time to pursue that.", "start": 4227.153, "stop": 4242.303, "duration": 15.15}, {"text": "It was our intention to proceed with that as promptly as we could.", "start": 4242.303, "stop": 4247.408, "duration": 5.11}, {"text": "We announced that we wanted to do it within a ten-day period if that were possible.", "start": 4247.408, "stop": 4251.919, "duration": 4.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "I take it you're not going to file a petition for rehearing in the Court of Appeals?", "start": 4251.919, "stop": 4255.515, "duration": 3.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir.", "start": 4255.515, "stop": 4257.074, "duration": 1.56}, {"text": "That's one other point I wanted to emphasize and clear up.", "start": 4257.074, "stop": 4263.91, "duration": 6.84}, {"text": "After the decision of the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals, the petitioners then filed for immediately sending down the mandate, either in the next mail or certainly by the next day.", "start": 4263.91, "stop": 4282.76, "duration": 18.85}, {"text": "We were preparing at the same time the other side was to present our motion for a stay.", "start": 4282.76, "stop": 4290.607, "duration": 7.85}, {"text": "I think it's correct that the petitioner's motion arrived there one day, ours arrived the next, so the issue there was traversed.", "start": 4290.607, "stop": 4299.478, "duration": 8.87}, {"text": "In other words each position was opposed to the other, them asking for immediate sending down of the mandate and our asking for the stay for a customary period of time and it is my information that the entire court, the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals granted that stay, that it was not done just by the Chief Judge or any justice there of.", "start": 4299.478, "stop": 4327.634, "duration": 28.16}, {"text": "It's my information that every justice agreed to the stay after the respective motions had been filed and that -- and the answer was the decision of the Court was announced the day after -- the later of the two motions was filed.", "start": 4327.634, "stop": 4346.241, "duration": 18.61}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler I think you told us, the record is here, do I understand that all now required to perfect your application for certiorari is the filing of your petition?", "start": 4346.241, "stop": 4360.161, "duration": 13.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir and filing a brief with it depending largely of course upon whether this Court weights rules of printing records.", "start": 4360.161, "stop": 4370.574, "duration": 10.41}, {"text": "There has been no printed record in this.", "start": 4370.574, "stop": 4373.699, "duration": 3.13}, {"text": "Actually it has moved so fast and courts have ordered us to do things both sides so quickly that there has been no time to print much of the thing that's customary to print.", "start": 4373.699, "stop": 4387.18, "duration": 13.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "If we permit it to be typewritten instead or printed, could you and would you accelerate your petition for certiorari?", "start": 4387.18, "stop": 4397.245, "duration": 10.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We would do it as quickly as we could which we had planned to do anyway Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 4397.245, "stop": 4403.525, "duration": 6.28}, {"text": "We have no disposition to delay legal proceedings, but we hope that we will be given time in that event as we should, to do it in an orderly fashion and get all of the things before -- all of the points before this Court that should be presented.", "start": 4403.525, "stop": 4419.854, "duration": 16.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 4419.854, "stop": 4421.208, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It has been my limited experience, that it is not an easy matter to present a petition for writ of certiorari.", "start": 4421.208, "stop": 4429.101, "duration": 7.89}, {"text": "There are certain things that must be done and we are not as familiar with that as lawyers who practice here in Washington.", "start": 4429.101, "stop": 4436.704, "duration": 7.6}, {"text": "We would deplore being rushed into it to the extent of not being -- having time adequately to prepare.", "start": 4436.704, "stop": 4446.821, "duration": 10.12}, {"text": "Now it seems that all the lawyers in this case are -- pretty well agreed and we won't dwell on that part of it, that this Court probably has the power to grant petitioners' motion.", "start": 4446.821, "stop": 4464.808, "duration": 17.99}, {"text": "Many instances can be cited both ways, not only of this Court but all appellate courts, of setting aside or upholding.", "start": 4464.808, "stop": 4472.823, "duration": 8.02}, {"text": "The customary thing of course is for the Court that heard the case to exercise its judicial discretion in granting the stay or not.", "start": 4472.823, "stop": 4487.802, "duration": 14.98}, {"text": "Now it would be in our opinion an unusual procedure, although not unprecedented for this Court to vacate the stay of the Circuit Court of Appeals.", "start": 4487.802, "stop": 4502.901, "duration": 15.1}, {"text": "I don't think it would serve any useful purpose to dwell on the various cases in the various circuits as well as in this Court.", "start": 4502.901, "stop": 4511.663, "duration": 8.76}, {"text": "I think we're all in accord that there is power in this Court to do either one.", "start": 4511.663, "stop": 4519.444, "duration": 7.78}, {"text": "Now unquestionably though the burden is on the petitioners that is at least my studied judgment.", "start": 4519.444, "stop": 4531.053, "duration": 11.61}, {"text": "I think the very nature of the legal proceedings dictate that when a stay is granted by a Court the burden is on the side seeking to set that aside, and we feel that they have not met any such burden up to this point.", "start": 4531.053, "stop": 4550.253, "duration": 19.2}, {"text": "As we see it each such case presents itself to every court, whether it's this Court or any other appellate court, with this rather simple but profound question, and that is should we as a court on motion pending on appeal or certiorari, summarily substitute our opinion for that of the lower court which heard the case and granted the stay.", "start": 4550.253, "stop": 4582.088, "duration": 31.84}, {"text": "With this Court sitting en banc, it may prove difficult for all the parties to eliminate arguing Judge Lemley's decision as against the point that is before this Court right now, the particular issue of setting aside the stay of the Eighth Circuit.", "start": 4582.088, "stop": 4601.634, "duration": 19.55}, {"text": "And I agree with counsel that he's just spoken that such argument necessarily overlaps one into the other.", "start": 4601.634, "stop": 4611.152, "duration": 9.52}, {"text": "It's difficult to distinguish between the two.", "start": 4611.152, "stop": 4616.796, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "However, we feel that even though such arguments become intertwined, that really the case, the issue before this Court as of now, insofar as these pleadings are concerned, is whether or not this Court is going to set aside the stay of the Eighth Circuit.", "start": 4616.796, "stop": 4641.214, "duration": 24.42}, {"text": "Now I set forth in our response, the trial court after hearing evidence for three days found that under the conditions now existing in Little Rock and these findings, not a single finding of Judge Lemley was disturbed or questioned by the Circuit Court of Appeals.", "start": 4641.214, "stop": 4661.553, "duration": 20.34}, {"text": "As a matter of fact the Circuit Court of Appeals found everyone of those itself and so set them out in the opinion.", "start": 4661.553, "stop": 4670.547, "duration": 8.99}, {"text": "But Judge Lemley found and also the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals found that it is impossible for the School Board of Little Rock to operate a school program for the 2,000 students at Central High School on an integrated basis at this time, and that unless the plan of desegregation is postponed for a reasonable length of time, that irreparable harm will be inflicted upon the students of both Negro and white race.", "start": 4670.547, "stop": 4704.09, "duration": 33.54}, {"text": "Now the broad issue of course in this case is simply this.", "start": 4704.09, "stop": 4709.592, "duration": 5.5}, {"text": "Can a court of equity postpone the enforcement of the plaintiffs' constitutional rights if the immediate enforcement thereof will deprive others, many others as a matter of fact, of their constitutional rights to an education in a free public school?", "start": 4709.592, "stop": 4735.116, "duration": 25.52}, {"text": "The Little Rock Public School Board is composed of outstanding citizens of our community.", "start": 4735.116, "stop": 4742.188, "duration": 7.07}, {"text": "There are two medical doctors on the Board.", "start": 4742.188, "stop": 4745.959, "duration": 3.77}, {"text": "There is a civil engineer, graduate civil engineer, one of the large manufacturing concerns in our state.", "start": 4745.959, "stop": 4754.826, "duration": 8.87}, {"text": "There is a certified public accountant.", "start": 4754.826, "stop": 4759.56, "duration": 4.73}, {"text": "There is a leading businessman of one of the large backing companies there, an official of that company, and the present President of the Little Rock School Board is a wise and experienced lawyer who has practiced there many years.", "start": 4759.56, "stop": 4777.671, "duration": 18.11}, {"text": "Those men are unpaid.", "start": 4777.671, "stop": 4780.201, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "They are public servants.", "start": 4780.201, "stop": 4782.205, "duration": 2}, {"text": "They have tried to do the best they could under as trying circumstances as any public servants have ever been faced with.", "start": 4782.205, "stop": 4793.569, "duration": 11.36}, {"text": "Now when other boards of education were refusing to recognize the basic change that the Supreme Court had made in the law in the Brown decision, this Board was studying and formulating ways and means of complying.", "start": 4793.569, "stop": 4811.426, "duration": 17.86}, {"text": "They knew it was not an easy task, but they were willing to do their best.", "start": 4811.426, "stop": 4817.893, "duration": 6.47}, {"text": "These are men of high standing as I have said in their community.", "start": 4817.893, "stop": 4825.24, "duration": 7.35}, {"text": "From bitter experience, however, they discovered that they could not operate a public school system under the existing climate in Little Rock as of this time.", "start": 4825.24, "stop": 4838.584, "duration": 13.34}, {"text": "Now they didn't anticipate all of the difficulty that has arisen and I dare say that many courts did not anticipate all of that difficulty.", "start": 4838.584, "stop": 4849.881, "duration": 11.3}, {"text": "But from bitter experience they discovered after some five or six months of operation, after troops had been in and out and still there, under different commanders that they could operate the school only with troops and yet they could not give an education with troops.", "start": 4849.881, "stop": 4870.721, "duration": 20.84}, {"text": "They came to that, studied and serious conclusion on or about the later part of or about the 20th of February after they have been operating a full completely semester with troops in the halls and around the school building.", "start": 4870.721, "stop": 4888.647, "duration": 17.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Am I right in understanding that it wasn't the school board that asked the troops?", "start": 4888.647, "stop": 4894.396, "duration": 5.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "The school board did not ask for troops, no sir.", "start": 4894.396, "stop": 4899.92, "duration": 5.52}, {"text": "This was not an impulsive search for relief from the courts that these men made, but after they had tried it for a long time.", "start": 4899.92, "stop": 4913.359, "duration": 13.44}, {"text": "Now many people in Little Rock and through out the line no doubt are sympathetic and try to be understanding of the school board's problem, but no one can put themselves in the place of this school board unless they have been there.", "start": 4913.359, "stop": 4933.87, "duration": 20.51}, {"text": "We find that even the press in many places, not just in the South land, has been understanding and as an example of that I would like to read a very brief editorial from the New York paper as late as August 20th.", "start": 4933.87, "stop": 4959.836, "duration": 25.97}, {"text": "It says among many trials of the people of Little Rock certainly not the least of them has been the way in the which the course of events has been suddenly reversed and reversed again by the various agencies of government and now they are to suffer more of it.", "start": 4959.836, "stop": 4981.695, "duration": 21.86}, {"text": "First there was the ruling of the Supreme Court that upset the old order in the school.", "start": 4981.695, "stop": 4987.198, "duration": 5.5}, {"text": "To this change the local authorities in Little Rock and most of its people tried to adjust, but then all of a sudden they were confronted with troops sent by their governor to block integration and troops sent by their President to enforce integration.", "start": 4987.198, "stop": 5005.968, "duration": 18.77}, {"text": "Next there was a ruling by a federal district judge denying a stay and ordering integration.", "start": 5005.968, "stop": 5011.611, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "This was followed by an order from another federal judge in the same district granting the people at times respite by postponing integration.", "start": 5011.611, "stop": 5020.839, "duration": 9.23}, {"text": "This week the federal circuit judge has once more reversed direction.", "start": 5020.839, "stop": 5025.005, "duration": 4.17}, {"text": "There is talk of another appeal to the Supreme Court of a special session of the legislature, all of which of course has come about in the last few days.", "start": 5025.005, "stop": 5034.028, "duration": 9.02}, {"text": "This surely is a terrible buffeting of one people by the laws and powers of office.", "start": 5034.028, "stop": 5042.315, "duration": 8.29}, {"text": "Each of these office holders may have had the right to act as he did.", "start": 5042.315, "stop": 5047.741, "duration": 5.43}, {"text": "But just the same the result has been that the people of Little Rock did not know from one day unto the next, under what order of society they must live, but found all change by which holder of what office wielded the moments power.", "start": 5047.741, "stop": 5067.745, "duration": 20}, {"text": "We cannot know what will happen next month in the schools of Little Rock.", "start": 5067.745, "stop": 5073.347, "duration": 5.6}, {"text": "It maybe too late now for the whole that somehow time and forbearance will be allowed to heal passions.", "start": 5073.347, "stop": 5083.384, "duration": 10.04}, {"text": "And yet it must be hope for any man can see what will happen if the issue of integration comes to devour the issue of education.", "start": 5083.384, "stop": 5097.403, "duration": 14.02}, {"text": "What kind of education can we give any children, White or Negro, in classrooms inflamed by animosities or if once more it comes to that echoing the triumph of soldiers.", "start": 5097.403, "stop": 5113.315, "duration": 15.91}, {"text": "That ends the editorial.", "start": 5113.315, "stop": 5114.669, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "What paper was it?", "start": 5114.669, "stop": 5115.717, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 5115.717, "stop": 5116.241, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "What paper was it?", "start": 5116.241, "stop": 5117.212, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is the Wall Street Journal of August 20, 1958.", "start": 5117.212, "stop": 5126.588, "duration": 9.38}, {"text": "Now the Supreme Court said that local courts should be the ones to decide the various questions which would arise, it may seem unnecessary and perhaps unduly academic to read to this Court, maybe even seem presumptuous to read to this Court what it has said, but I have gotten something out of the opinion every time I have read it and reread it, and reread it.", "start": 5126.588, "stop": 5160.84, "duration": 34.25}, {"text": "And apparently experienced judges give different ideas about what this Court means.", "start": 5160.84, "stop": 5169.057, "duration": 8.22}, {"text": "And perhaps even at the expense of reputation it is advisable to read portions of that opinion in the light of the events which have taken place in Little Rock.", "start": 5169.057, "stop": 5183.921, "duration": 14.86}, {"text": "This case -- this Court said in the Brown case that because these cases arose under different local conditions and their disposition will involve a variety of local problems, we requested further argument on the question of relief.", "start": 5183.921, "stop": 5203.733, "duration": 19.81}, {"text": "These presentations were informative and helpful and in its consideration of the complexities arising from the transition to a system public -- of public education free of racial discrimination, full implementation of these constitutional principles may require solution of varied local school problems, because of their proximity to local conditions and the need for further hearings the courts which originally heard these cases can best perform this judicial appraisal.", "start": 5203.733, "stop": 5242.472, "duration": 38.74}, {"text": "Accordingly, we believe it's appropriate to remand those cases to those courts.", "start": 5242.472, "stop": 5249.712, "duration": 7.24}, {"text": "In fashioning and effectuating the decrees the courts will be guided by equitable principles.", "start": 5249.712, "stop": 5258.528, "duration": 8.82}, {"text": "Traditionally equity has been characterized by a practical flexibility in shaping its remedies and by a facility for adjusting and reconciling public and private needs.", "start": 5258.528, "stop": 5273.443, "duration": 14.91}, {"text": "These cases call for the exercise of these traditional attributes of equity power.", "start": 5273.443, "stop": 5280.988, "duration": 7.55}, {"text": "By giving weight to these public and private considerations, the courts will require that the defendants make a prompt and reasonable start towards the compliance with our May 17th 1954 ruling.", "start": 5280.988, "stop": 5294.493, "duration": 13.51}, {"text": "Once such a start has been made the courts may find that additional time is necessary to carry out the ruling in an effective manner.", "start": 5294.493, "stop": 5309.07, "duration": 14.58}, {"text": "When we look at this entire problem, we recognize that two-and-a-half years, historically is a very short time or perhaps any other period of time and I know of no better way at least it was most impressive on Judge Lemley.", "start": 5309.07, "stop": 5341.673, "duration": 32.6}, {"text": "it was impressive on other people when Mr. Blossom, the School Board Superintendent, who has studied this thing and has been on his heart as well as the hearts of the school board members more than anyone else and has been his major responsibility in asking him in the lower court what he found, and this is in the record that is now before Your Honors.", "start": 5341.673, "stop": 5375.287, "duration": 33.61}, {"text": "He was asked the question whether he had read the Supreme Court decision, these men were earnestly trying to carry out the orders of the Federal Court as they saw it.", "start": 5375.287, "stop": 5387.294, "duration": 12.01}, {"text": "But their function was also to maintain a public education system in Little Rock, and I will say I think in all fairness to those men that that probably was their primary object and consideration and duty.", "start": 5387.294, "stop": 5407.952, "duration": 20.66}, {"text": "But Mr. Blossom testified in studying this problem just what did it mean, what did deliberate speed mean in one locality as against another, what did it mean in this particular serious problem that has confronted not just Little Rock but the entire nation and here in substance was his testimony that portion of it verbatim.", "start": 5407.952, "stop": 5437.43, "duration": 29.48}, {"text": "We ask him whether he had given consideration to this time element when they finally filed the petition before Judge Lemley for a two-and-a-half year delay and he said very definitely, we have given great consideration to it in this plan.", "start": 5437.43, "stop": 5456.538, "duration": 19.11}, {"text": "We are dealing with something that is very important and very dear to the hearts of many people on both sides of it.", "start": 5456.538, "stop": 5464.823, "duration": 8.29}, {"text": "We took into account the effect as far as time and other cultural pattern changes in our society were concerned.", "start": 5464.823, "stop": 5472.471, "duration": 7.65}, {"text": "We try to look into history to see what it would teach us.", "start": 5472.471, "stop": 5476.299, "duration": 3.83}, {"text": "We tried to analyze the situation of the Negro and his march to civil rights in this community.", "start": 5476.299, "stop": 5483.653, "duration": 7.35}, {"text": "Then he was asked the question as whether he considered the term delivery speeds.", "start": 5483.653, "stop": 5488.975, "duration": 5.32}, {"text": "His answer was, “Yes sir, very material.”", "start": 5488.975, "stop": 5492.673, "duration": 3.7}, {"text": "The Negro race as a race came to this country in 1619.", "start": 5492.673, "stop": 5497.735, "duration": 5.06}, {"text": "They came in chains as slaves.", "start": 5497.735, "stop": 5500.698, "duration": 2.96}, {"text": "They stayed in that and as far as I could study it, you would class that as the first period in the history of the United States and they stayed from 1619 until 1865, nearly two-and-three-quarter century and that is one period in their march for civil rights and their development.", "start": 5500.698, "stop": 5519.816, "duration": 19.12}, {"text": "The second period came in 1865 and they stayed in this second period until 1896, the decision of Plessy versus Ferguson.", "start": 5519.816, "stop": 5529.139, "duration": 9.32}, {"text": "That is 31 years.", "start": 5529.139, "stop": 5531.732, "duration": 2.59}, {"text": "Now in this period they had their freedom, they did not have the economic or political or any other type of positions to any extent.", "start": 5531.732, "stop": 5540.078, "duration": 8.35}, {"text": "Then coming out of that period into what I could call the third one from 1896 to 1954 and I would just label that separate but equal.", "start": 5540.078, "stop": 5550.9, "duration": 10.82}, {"text": "Now they stayed in that 58 years and then you look at the problem and the complexities in this thing and recognize that many separate but equally -- is in no way a reality.", "start": 5550.9, "stop": 5564.503, "duration": 13.6}, {"text": "In many places in the South land, but in Little Rock Arkansas they were.", "start": 5564.503, "stop": 5571.776, "duration": 7.27}, {"text": "“I am not arguing the separate but equal philosophy,” Mr. Blossom continued, “I am trying to state that history tells us in terms of two-and-a-half year request for delay that this is the third period and we account for the fact that there are three periods, one taking nearly three centuries, another 31 years and another 58 years and recognizing that there is one group that says we are going to have it all now and another that says we are never going to have it, you put the horns of the dilemma in the proper perspective with the school board right in the middle and it is a difficult thing.", "start": 5571.776, "stop": 5611.567, "duration": 39.79}, {"text": "And then you come to May 17 1954 and we look at it today that was June 4, '58 and you compare that period of time as compared to either of the three previous periods I have outlined and you wonder how fast in terms of history, can anyone expect a change in cultural pattern.”", "start": 5611.567, "stop": 5636.579, "duration": 25.01}, {"text": "Following that Mr. Blossom went into some detail and as did the President of the School board as to what could be done in two-and-a-half years and that is in the record and I respectfully disagree with the implication left by opposing counsel that nothing was to be done.", "start": 5636.579, "stop": 5659.522, "duration": 22.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Would you mind, would you mind either reading if isn't too long, that well expressed --", "start": 5659.522, "stop": 5665.611, "duration": 6.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It --", "start": 5665.611, "stop": 5665.905, "duration": 0.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Or would you summarize what Mr. Blossom testified as to why two-and-a-half and not one-and-a-half and now three-and-a-half were selected.", "start": 5665.905, "stop": 5676.153, "duration": 10.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'd like to start, yes.", "start": 5676.153, "stop": 5677.145, "duration": 0.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I know lines must be drawn in this world, but I just wonder what his testimony was?", "start": 5677.145, "stop": 5680.596, "duration": 3.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes his testimony in effect was this and I'd be glad to read it to you on Your Honor, but it is rather interspersed as well as Mr. Upton's in among a whole lot of other testimony.", "start": 5680.596, "stop": 5693.015, "duration": 12.42}, {"text": "It basically is simply this Your Honor.", "start": 5693.015, "stop": 5696.267, "duration": 3.25}, {"text": "In the first place they felt that starting at mid-semester after organization was completed during the first semester was wise.", "start": 5696.267, "stop": 5706.127, "duration": 9.86}, {"text": "That would put it at the middle of a term.", "start": 5706.127, "stop": 5709.371, "duration": 3.24}, {"text": "Their reasoning simply was this, that your PTA organizations perhaps other organizations were and the school itself was then in a better organized position than it was after a summer recess of three months.", "start": 5709.371, "stop": 5725.164, "duration": 15.79}, {"text": "The other thing was simply this and we are firmly convinced of this situation.", "start": 5725.164, "stop": 5732.587, "duration": 7.42}, {"text": "In Little Rock as well as throughout the south and in other places where problem has arisen, the great mass of people are not law violators as such.", "start": 5732.587, "stop": 5746.933, "duration": 14.35}, {"text": "They are not people who form mobs, they are not people who defy the law, but we submit in this school board determined that they were entitled to know what the law was and as long as editorialist, popular editorialist in our community were saying that this was not the law of the land and if there were ways to get around it and one court was saying one thing and another court was saying another, and there were laws on the state statute books of Arkansas as well as other states throughout the south, diametrically opposed as some people argued, some of them could be reconciled, some of them could not with the decision in the Brown case, but it left the people of our community as well as the people of many communities in actual doubt as to what the law was and on question to the people in our part of the country, wanted to believe that this thing could take a long time or be circumvented entirely.", "start": 5746.933, "stop": 5813.218, "duration": 66.28}, {"text": "They wanted to believe that, but it is our firm opinion and it is the opinion of this school board and that was the main consideration given when they finally decided on a two-and-a-half year request that in that period of time perhaps as we pointed in our response a national policy could definitely be established, that laws could be tested so that the people would know, the people who want to obey the final word.", "start": 5813.218, "stop": 5847.225, "duration": 34.01}, {"text": "Now that was the reason and very candidly Mr. Blossom ended up by testifying and I am sure this was the thinking of every member of the school board as well that we don't know that two-and-a-half years will do it.", "start": 5847.225, "stop": 5862.5, "duration": 15.27}, {"text": "You may be able to do it one year, you might do it in a year-and-a-half, maybe two-and-a-half is not enough.", "start": 5862.5, "stop": 5868.995, "duration": 6.49}, {"text": "He doesn't know but the courts have said that the first consideration of this problem shall be dealt with by the school boards, it is their primary function, as a matter of fact this Court I believe have said it just that way, if not certainly all the appellate courts.", "start": 5868.995, "stop": 5888.302, "duration": 19.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler why aren't the two decisions of this Court, which, the first one based on the constitutional requirement that this Court unanimously was held compelled the Constitution and the second opinion recognizing that this was a change of what had been supposedly the permission of the Constitution, recognizing that and the kind of light that have been built under the contrary conception said as equities is always say that you must make appropriate accommodation for the specific circumstances of the situation instead of having a procrustean bed where everybody makes the cut off or stretch to fit the length of the bed, and who is better to decide that than the local United States judges.", "start": 5888.302, "stop": 5943.104, "duration": 54.8}, {"text": "Why isn't that a national policy, and why hasn't that national policy, why wasn't that enforced in Little Rock, in the Little Rock district when the school board submitted a plan after mature consideration, after listing public support on its behalf submitted it to the court where it was contested and the court said, yes this satisfies the policy laid down the second in the Brown and Allen decisions.", "start": 5943.104, "stop": 5970.898, "duration": 27.79}, {"text": "Why isn't that deference to local situation in the enforcement of what was laid down a national policy, national policy doesn't mean the same thing must take place in Little Rock, Arkansas as in Fitchburg, Massachusetts, something yes, but not for this kind of thing.", "start": 5970.898, "stop": 5989.492, "duration": 18.59}, {"text": "And there was a national policy and the federal courts recognized it.", "start": 5989.492, "stop": 5993.196, "duration": 3.7}, {"text": "It was sustained by the District Court over the opposition of the parents or whoever acted on behalf of these children went before there Court of Appeals.", "start": 5993.196, "stop": 6002.055, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "And the Court of Appeals said, yes this is fair carrying out of that which the Supreme Court laid down.", "start": 6002.055, "stop": 6008.27, "duration": 6.22}, {"text": "I do not understand what is meant by saying lets wait till we get a national policy, if that isn't a national policy.", "start": 6008.27, "stop": 6014.752, "duration": 6.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well Your Honor in answer to that I simply say this, that it was certainly not anticipated at the time that plan was formulated that the governor of the State of Arkansas would call our troops to keep integration in the schools from taking place, nor was it --", "start": 6014.752, "stop": 6034.543, "duration": 19.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The governor is calling out troops, isn't the same thing as the uncertainty of what the law is.", "start": 6034.543, "stop": 6041.816, "duration": 7.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well --", "start": 6041.816, "stop": 6041.869, "duration": 0.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That has nothing to do with the uncertainty of the law.", "start": 6041.869, "stop": 6044.45, "duration": 2.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor this --", "start": 6044.45, "stop": 6044.775, "duration": 0.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "The action of the governor under what he thought was his refusal to abide by the law.", "start": 6044.775, "stop": 6050.555, "duration": 5.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well this School Board is simply faced with realities, and that is the possession that it's in.", "start": 6050.555, "stop": 6059.733, "duration": 9.18}, {"text": "It did not anticipate the extreme difficulties that it went into.", "start": 6059.733, "stop": 6065.734, "duration": 6}, {"text": "It knew that it did not have an easy task in this thing.", "start": 6065.734, "stop": 6068.961, "duration": 3.23}, {"text": "All school boards I think realize that.", "start": 6068.961, "stop": 6072.94, "duration": 3.98}, {"text": "They did not anticipate the events which actually did take place, neither did they anticipate the things which are right today destroying the public schools system there.", "start": 6072.94, "stop": 6084.223, "duration": 11.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler I did not mean to imply, I hope did not carry any such meaning of what is said.", "start": 6084.223, "stop": 6090.86, "duration": 6.64}, {"text": "I did not remotely mean to imply the criticism of the school board.", "start": 6090.86, "stop": 6095.508, "duration": 4.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 6095.508, "stop": 6095.711, "duration": 0.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler as you were relating the reasons why the School Board continued this for two-and-a-half years, the question crossed my mind, suppose every other school district in the south would do the same thing and say we will carry on segregation for a number of years until the law is clarified, how would it ever be clarified?", "start": 6095.711, "stop": 6122.294, "duration": 26.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well Your Honor, I think the only answer to that is that many districts do not have that problem, even in some parts of the south.", "start": 6122.294, "stop": 6133.307, "duration": 11.01}, {"text": "In our state university, Negro students have been there for some years, and there has been no great problem about it.", "start": 6133.307, "stop": 6149.646, "duration": 16.34}, {"text": "Our other districts where the problems are greater as this Court pointed out that you have a variety of local problems.", "start": 6149.646, "stop": 6159.316, "duration": 9.67}, {"text": "Now in Arkansas there are some -- a number of districts, as well as in Texas and other states, where the people of that community have done it largely for economic reasons, various other reasons, but in any event it has worked successfully.", "start": 6159.316, "stop": 6177.273, "duration": 17.96}, {"text": "And I simply say again that this School Board in Little Rock, Arkansas was not faced with theories, it was faced with actualities which are undermining and which are going to destroy the public school system in Little Rock and when its destroyed it will be destroyed not just for white students, it will be destroyed all the way up and down the line unless they're given an opportunity to work this thing out in a climate of calm rather than in a climate of hysteria.", "start": 6177.273, "stop": 6212.207, "duration": 34.93}, {"text": "Now we urgently feel that way and the School Board feels that way about it.", "start": 6212.207, "stop": 6217.186, "duration": 4.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "My recollection is that in one of those opinions, either the Brown or the Alan case we did say that mere public opposition to the policy and to the program would not be a cause either for denying integration or for extending it?", "start": 6217.186, "stop": 6236.392, "duration": 19.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We understand that and of course Your Honor is correct, if the word I think non acceptance or some such or opposition.", "start": 6236.392, "stop": 6243.861, "duration": 7.47}, {"text": "Now, the courts have certainly held and we find no fault with the basic statement, the bald statement, the just mental reservations about this, or mental opposition to it, but when a school board is confronted with facts which of themselves will force it, will force the destruction of the public school system, then this Board feels and Judge Lamley felt that time should be given for cooler heads, calmer atmosphere to come to the front in order to work out these problems or at least to give an atmosphere that is conducive to working those out.", "start": 6243.861, "stop": 6297.473, "duration": 53.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well Mr. Butler I think there is no member of this Court who fails to recognize the very great problem which your school board has, but can we defer a program of this kind merely because there are those elements in the community that will commit violence to prevent it from going into effect?", "start": 6297.473, "stop": 6326.366, "duration": 28.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice I think so, but not directed to the people who form mobs, not directed to the people who are law deifiers, we're not standing up here taking -- trying to argue for their side of it.", "start": 6326.366, "stop": 6343.708, "duration": 17.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "I know you're not.", "start": 6343.708, "stop": 6344.41, "duration": 0.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We are arguing for the great mass of people throughout the south who I say again and will say again and again, are not law deifiers.", "start": 6344.41, "stop": 6355.915, "duration": 11.51}, {"text": "They want to follow the law but they as of this moment without certain state statutes having been tested in court do not know just exactly what the law is in a particular given circumstance.", "start": 6355.915, "stop": 6373.475, "duration": 17.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But is that the state law that concerns you or is it the threat and violence that concerns you?", "start": 6373.475, "stop": 6379.716, "duration": 6.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Both, I would say --", "start": 6379.716, "stop": 6382.851, "duration": 3.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "So as long as the state laws conflict with the federal laws you would think that there should not be any integration?", "start": 6382.851, "stop": 6391.623, "duration": 8.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir.", "start": 6391.623, "stop": 6392.055, "duration": 0.43}, {"text": "I don't feel that way about it.", "start": 6392.055, "stop": 6392.575, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "How much time would you --", "start": 6392.575, "stop": 6393.642, "duration": 1.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "But there are certain laws such as pupil assignment laws and laws of that kind and incidentally the pupil assignment law has just been recently upheld by a three-judge federal court in Alabama, I believe it was in May of this year, its reported in the June Race Relations Report, and upheld the constitutionality of that.", "start": 6393.642, "stop": 6417.249, "duration": 23.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "That isn't the question here, is it?", "start": 6417.249, "stop": 6419.448, "duration": 2.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir I think -- well not specifically here, I think it's intertwined in this entire problem.", "start": 6419.448, "stop": 6426.837, "duration": 7.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's in the same area, but it's a no sense controlling in this case is it?", "start": 6426.837, "stop": 6433.091, "duration": 6.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "The pupil assignment --", "start": 6433.091, "stop": 6433.44, "duration": 0.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "The assignment?", "start": 6433.44, "stop": 6434.333, "duration": 0.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 6434.333, "stop": 6434.898, "duration": 0.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "The pupil assignment.", "start": 6434.898, "stop": 6437.679, "duration": 2.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It is not -- that statute as such is not before this Court at that time no sir, the point I'm making is Mr. Chief Justice that laws such as that, I use that as an illustration, laws such as that are being advanced.", "start": 6437.679, "stop": 6454.413, "duration": 16.73}, {"text": "Some of them have been on the books for many years.", "start": 6454.413, "stop": 6456.789, "duration": 2.38}, {"text": "Some of them have -- many of them have not been determined whether their constitutional or not, and the great mass of people are in our opinion entitled to know and have those laws tested in court.", "start": 6456.789, "stop": 6473.148, "duration": 16.36}, {"text": "Now --", "start": 6473.148, "stop": 6473.617, "duration": 0.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Suppose the pupil assignment law contains one position that pupils can be assigned and must be assigned on account of their race or color?", "start": 6473.617, "stop": 6485.769, "duration": 12.15}, {"text": "Would you say that has been decided?", "start": 6485.769, "stop": 6489.006, "duration": 3.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir I would say that has been decided Mr. Justice Black and Arkansas statute does not contain any such provision, as a matter of fact it contains directly the contrary, but it does set out some other things which school boards generally have taken into consideration throughout the year, such as psychological adjustment, various other things, health and many things.", "start": 6489.006, "stop": 6512.353, "duration": 23.35}, {"text": "Now, some of the school assignment law, pupil assignment laws, I understand have been held by federal courts to be unconstitutional on their face.", "start": 6512.353, "stop": 6521.188, "duration": 8.84}, {"text": "The most recent one with which I am familiar with, and to which I refer, the three-judge federal court in Alabama; held at that, that state law was not unconstitutional on its face and they upheld it.", "start": 6521.188, "stop": 6534.855, "duration": 13.67}, {"text": "I don't know just where it is now but it's -- it was upheld by a three-judge federal court.", "start": 6534.855, "stop": 6540.403, "duration": 5.55}, {"text": "Excuse me sir.", "start": 6540.403, "stop": 6540.77, "duration": 0.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did you say to Justice Black a minute ago that the Arkansas law is just the opposite of the --", "start": 6540.77, "stop": 6545.836, "duration": 5.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Arkansas -- yes sir the Arkansas --", "start": 6545.836, "stop": 6547.339, "duration": 1.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You must pass things (Inaudible)", "start": 6547.339, "stop": 6551.651, "duration": 4.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 6551.651, "stop": 6552.199, "duration": 0.55}, {"text": "It was passed in 1957, yes sir.", "start": 6552.199, "stop": 6554.63, "duration": 2.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you say that, that has --", "start": 6554.63, "stop": 6556.842, "duration": 2.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "1955 or 1957,", "start": 6556.842, "stop": 6558.51, "duration": 1.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That has explicitly a prohibition against pupil assignment on the basis of race?", "start": 6558.51, "stop": 6564.598, "duration": 6.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "On the basis of race, yes sir, but it sets out some 12 or 15 other things that school boards may consider.", "start": 6564.598, "stop": 6573.94, "duration": 9.34}, {"text": "Now admittedly of course courts cannot make decision based on popularity polls, but the fact is and I think it's interesting to note in passing that a respected poll taken very recently across this entire nation shows, and it was not taken just in the south, it was throughout the entire United States, that 54% of the people favored Judge Lemley's decision and felt that it was the only way to solve this particular problem.", "start": 6573.94, "stop": 6604.888, "duration": 30.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I sometimes wonder why we have elections and not turn it all over to polls.", "start": 6604.888, "stop": 6609.462, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 6609.462, "stop": 6617.308, "duration": 7.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now to show the seriousness of this problem Your Honors, Your Chief Judge, Judge Gardner wrote this short dissent, and to me it is so appropriate, so realistic, so proper under the decision, the words themselves of the Brown decision that I'd like to read at least parts of it.", "start": 6617.308, "stop": 6652.483, "duration": 35.18}, {"text": "It's the entire dissent is limited to one page, but he says it is conceded that the school authorities have acted in good faith, both in formulating a plan or integrating and in attempting to implement the plan.", "start": 6652.483, "stop": 6673.556, "duration": 21.07}, {"text": "Their efforts in this regard were met with unprecedented and unforeseen opposition and resistance as set out and enumerated in the majority opinion.", "start": 6673.556, "stop": 6686.286, "duration": 12.73}, {"text": "This opposition included acts of violence to such an unprecedented extent that the armed forces of the United States were stationed in about the school building.", "start": 6686.286, "stop": 6698.308, "duration": 12.02}, {"text": "The events pertinent to the attempts of the school authorities during the school year to implement its plan for integration are set forth in the majority opinion.", "start": 6698.308, "stop": 6708.393, "duration": 10.09}, {"text": "The normal conduct of the school was continuously disrupted and the state of mind both within and without the school was to a greater or a lesser extent in a state of hysteria.", "start": 6708.393, "stop": 6722.197, "duration": 13.8}, {"text": "Under such circumstances and conditions set out in Judge Lemley's opinion, the school authorities made application for an extension of time so as to permit a cooling off or breathing space, so that both pupils, parents, teachers and the public might to some extent become reconciled to the inevitable necessity for public school integration.", "start": 6722.197, "stop": 6748.385, "duration": 26.19}, {"text": "Having in mind that the school officials and the teaching staff acted in good faith and if the school officials presented their petition for an extension of time in good faith it was the duty of this Court and he quotes, “To consider whether the action of school authorities constitutes good faith implementation of the governing constitutional principle” and he cites the Brown case of course.", "start": 6748.385, "stop": 6776.017, "duration": 27.63}, {"text": "In this situation the action of Judge Lemley in extending the time as requested by the school official was the exercise of his judicial discretion.", "start": 6776.017, "stop": 6788.324, "duration": 12.31}, {"text": "The background is well set forth in Judge Lemley's opinion.", "start": 6788.324, "stop": 6791.912, "duration": 3.59}, {"text": "For centuries there had been no intermittent social relations between white and colored races in the section referred to as the South.", "start": 6791.912, "stop": 6799.847, "duration": 7.93}, {"text": "There had been no integration in the schools and that practice had the sanction and a decision of the Supreme Court of the United States as constitutionally legal.", "start": 6799.847, "stop": 6810.259, "duration": 10.41}, {"text": "It had become a way of life in that section of the country and it is not strange that this long established, cherished practice could not suddenly be changed without resistance.", "start": 6810.259, "stop": 6823.228, "duration": 12.97}, {"text": "Such changes, if successful, are usually accomplished by evolution rather than revolution and time, patience, forbearance are important elements in effecting all radical changes.", "start": 6823.228, "stop": 6841.068, "duration": 17.84}, {"text": "The action of Judge Lemley was based on realities and on conditions rather than theories.", "start": 6841.068, "stop": 6848.691, "duration": 7.62}, {"text": "The exercise of his discretion should not, I think, be set aside as it seems to me it was not an abuse of discretion, but rather a discretion wisely exercised under all the conditions.", "start": 6848.691, "stop": 6864.843, "duration": 16.15}, {"text": "We should not substitute our judgment for that of the trial court.", "start": 6864.843, "stop": 6871.153, "duration": 6.31}, {"text": "That ends Judge Gardner's decision.", "start": 6871.153, "stop": 6877.451, "duration": 6.3}, {"text": "All we are asking at this moment is for this Court to continue in effect the stay of the Circuit Court until our petition for a writ of certiorari can be filed and considered and the matter heard in an orderly fashion.", "start": 6877.451, "stop": 6894.394, "duration": 16.94}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm just wondering Mr. Butler whether your argument in that event would be any different from the one you've just given us?", "start": 6894.394, "stop": 6901.499, "duration": 7.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It would probably be somewhat longer Your Honor but that would be the basis of it.", "start": 6901.499, "stop": 6906.241, "duration": 4.74}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Same vein I take it?", "start": 6906.241, "stop": 6909.554, "duration": 3.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think in the short space that Judge Gardner took I think he said it about as concisely as it could be said.", "start": 6909.554, "stop": 6919.22, "duration": 9.67}, {"text": "I think there are other things to be said in connection with it.", "start": 6919.22, "stop": 6923.72, "duration": 4.5}, {"text": "He practiced his dissent, that under the time element he could not go into in great detail, but that it was a hurried opinion but his firm opinion.", "start": 6923.72, "stop": 6941.45, "duration": 17.73}, {"text": "But we are here now for that purpose and as I understand it for that purpose alone, to ask that the normal procedure be followed in this important case and that this Court not disturb the stay of the Eighth Circuit under the present circumstances.", "start": 6941.45, "stop": 6964.148, "duration": 22.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler?", "start": 6964.148, "stop": 6965.074, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 6965.074, "stop": 6965.672, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Under your view as to that aspect of the motion asking a stay on Judge Lemley's (Inaudible)", "start": 6965.672, "stop": 6981.248, "duration": 15.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well Your Honor of course our position is simply this, that Judge Lemley's decision although found to be in disagreement by the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals, nevertheless both obviously he and then the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals felt that it should be stayed, which is an indication to us Your Honor and to many other judges and lawyers throughout this land, that the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals had some question in its mind.", "start": 6981.248, "stop": 7013.417, "duration": 32.17}, {"text": "If it was absolutely certain that it had been correct, the chances are it would not have issued the stay.", "start": 7013.417, "stop": 7024.594, "duration": 11.18}, {"text": "It was in his -- it was within its power to deny a stay.", "start": 7024.594, "stop": 7031.187, "duration": 6.59}, {"text": "They were traversed and they had it before them and they had heard the whole case.", "start": 7031.187, "stop": 7036.414, "duration": 5.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 7036.414, "stop": 7052.003, "duration": 15.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, it is and it is the customary procedure if Your Honor please for this Court to recognize the judicial discretion of that Court in granting stays and ordinarily I would say does not upset them.", "start": 7052.003, "stop": 7068.317, "duration": 16.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Unless you understand it?", "start": 7068.317, "stop": 7069.727, "duration": 1.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 7069.727, "stop": 7070.197, "duration": 0.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, now (Inaudible) namely to stay the effect of Judge Lemley's order meanwhile so that the normal process is (Inaudible), you see?", "start": 7070.197, "stop": 7097.787, "duration": 27.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir and I --", "start": 7097.787, "stop": 7098.337, "duration": 0.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 7098.337, "stop": 7099.663, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well I think, Your Honor that is so wrapped up legally and practically that the practical effect of that, if I understand Your Honor's question would be that it would serve no useful purpose for what we are ultimately seeking and that is to give the people of that section an opportunity to think in a period of calm rather than in a period of hysteria.", "start": 7099.663, "stop": 7130.349, "duration": 30.69}, {"text": "Now if the Court puts it back in the status quo that it was before Judge Lemley it would serve this School Board as we see it no usual purpose.", "start": 7130.349, "stop": 7143.385, "duration": 13.04}, {"text": "There would be troops back in Little Rock to maintain law and order and –", "start": 7143.385, "stop": 7148.558, "duration": 5.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why do you say that?", "start": 7148.558, "stop": 7149.671, "duration": 1.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 7149.671, "stop": 7150.834, "duration": 1.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "I said why do you think that?", "start": 7150.834, "stop": 7152.551, "duration": 1.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well perhaps should not because that is my personal opinion.", "start": 7152.551, "stop": 7156.494, "duration": 3.94}, {"text": "I'm expressing the opinion of the School Board in its considered judgment the school board feels that that is what would happen and they have been in this untamable position.", "start": 7156.494, "stop": 7174.432, "duration": 17.94}, {"text": "They cannot operate a school without students apparently and they cannot have an educational system and program with them.", "start": 7174.432, "stop": 7189.604, "duration": 15.17}, {"text": "I see my time is up, I presume --", "start": 7189.604, "stop": 7192.735, "duration": 3.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your time is not up.", "start": 7192.735, "stop": 7194.508, "duration": 1.77}, {"text": "That's the call for luncheon, but so if you have more to say you may take it up after lunch.", "start": 7194.508, "stop": 7201.661, "duration": 7.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We have asked for a rebuttal time, we have completed this part of our argument.", "start": 7201.661, "stop": 7206.566, "duration": 4.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Rebuttal, your rebuttal time of the Solicitor General, do you, you must make your entire argument in response to Mr. --", "start": 7206.566, "stop": 7217.537, "duration": 10.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 7217.537, "stop": 7218.519, "duration": 0.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "At this time.", "start": 7218.519, "stop": 7219.655, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh at this time to Mr. Martin.", "start": 7219.655, "stop": 7221.371, "duration": 1.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 7221.371, "stop": 7223.516, "duration": 2.14}, {"text": "So you may proceed after lunch, if you so advise.", "start": 7223.516, "stop": 7225.66, "duration": 2.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 7225.66, "stop": 7230.214, "duration": 4.55}]}]}, {"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - August 28, 1958 (Part 2)", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/15580", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Your Honor.", "start": 0, "stop": 12.106, "duration": 12.11}, {"text": "Counsel for N.A.A.C.P. has made this statement that we have to weigh, the Court has to weigh, as it said in its lower -- in the Brown decision, previous decision, the irreparable harm on the one side as against on the other side.", "start": 12.106, "stop": 40.335, "duration": 28.23}, {"text": "Now, here are the facts, the record points it out.", "start": 40.335, "stop": 44.266, "duration": 3.93}, {"text": "I don't think anyone will dispute it.", "start": 44.266, "stop": 48.256, "duration": 3.99}, {"text": "Here we have 2000 students in one of the high schools and we have hundred of others in the other high schools.", "start": 48.256, "stop": 60.741, "duration": 12.49}, {"text": "These petitioners, although it's a class action of course, designated as such by the original plaintiffs.", "start": 60.741, "stop": 70.986, "duration": 10.25}, {"text": "But there are only seven who would not be deprived of anything tangible or any benefit that you can really point to of, anything like a tangible -- in a tangible measurement.", "start": 70.986, "stop": 90.922, "duration": 19.94}, {"text": "Now, as against that, if the public school system is at steak in Little Rock and this School Board earnestly believes that it is.", "start": 90.922, "stop": 104.733, "duration": 13.81}, {"text": "Then you are effecting from an equitable standpoint, maybe not just the remaining 2000 students in Central High School but perhaps throughout the school system in Little Rock.", "start": 104.733, "stop": 120.939, "duration": 16.21}, {"text": "Now, those are the balancing of the equities that, it seems to us, weigh heavily in favor of denying the vacating of this stay of the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals.", "start": 120.939, "stop": 138.34, "duration": 17.4}, {"text": "Now, I have tried as I said at the very beginning --", "start": 138.34, "stop": 142.508, "duration": 4.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler, really aren't -- aren't the rights of all the Negro children of Little Rock wrapped up in this case?", "start": 142.508, "stop": 150.428, "duration": 7.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 159.287, "stop": 150.428, "duration": -8.86}, {"text": "And their -- and their actual ability to get any kind of an education there in a public school system are wrapped up in it, Mr. Chief Justice, in our opinion.", "start": 150.428, "stop": 159.381, "duration": 8.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I mean wrapped up in the --", "start": 159.381, "stop": 160.519, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "And --", "start": 160.519, "stop": 160.786, "duration": 0.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- principle that we are litigating here.", "start": 160.786, "stop": 163.163, "duration": 2.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that's correct, Your Honor.", "start": 163.163, "stop": 164.777, "duration": 1.61}, {"text": "And -- and we feel that -- that unless we are granted this stay that the whole thing might be in a flood and be washed down stream where no one benefits.", "start": 164.777, "stop": 175.063, "duration": 10.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understand your (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 175.063, "stop": 176.139, "duration": 1.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "And then, of course, it would be an empty victory indeed for the Negro students.", "start": 176.139, "stop": 183.211, "duration": 7.07}, {"text": "Now, on that one point though, I think, theoretically at least opposing counsel and I can agree and that is that the balancing of these equities must be done, the irreparable harm that would be done to the students just in Central High School.", "start": 183.211, "stop": 206.774, "duration": 23.56}, {"text": "If they have to go to school with troops marching up and down the hall.", "start": 206.774, "stop": 212.403, "duration": 5.63}, {"text": "Now, as I start it out at the beginning, we don't -- we are not in a position to argue the case in chief.", "start": 212.403, "stop": 219.998, "duration": 7.59}, {"text": "I have attempted to refrain from arguing it.", "start": 219.998, "stop": 224.487, "duration": 4.49}, {"text": "We believe that there are many decisions which we should study and submit to this Court on the merits of the case and we have attempted to limit our argument on the pleadings that are now before this Court, but it is difficult, of course, to stay on that one limited issue when, of course, everyone is concerned about the entire issue, as it is shown in the entire case.", "start": 224.487, "stop": 257.798, "duration": 33.31}, {"text": "Now, one other point and perhaps I did not emphasize this enough.", "start": 257.798, "stop": 266.011, "duration": 8.21}, {"text": "Regardless, of whether or not the people of Arkansas should recognize the United States Supreme Court decisions as the law of the land.", "start": 266.011, "stop": 279.687, "duration": 13.68}, {"text": "The plain fact is that they have not and it is most difficult for them to do so, if not impossible when the Governor of the State says, that that is not the law of the land then only Congress can really say what the law of the land is.", "start": 279.687, "stop": 303.246, "duration": 23.56}, {"text": "Now, as lawyers we may take the position.", "start": 303.246, "stop": 306.852, "duration": 3.61}, {"text": "Well, they're not informed but that is a fact and as long as the United States Senator from a neighboring State of ours says, it's not the law of the land and as long as our Governor says, that it is not the law of the land, not the set of law of the land.", "start": 306.852, "stop": 332.213, "duration": 25.36}, {"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, you've been the Governor of a great state and if you --", "start": 332.213, "stop": 336.861, "duration": 4.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I never tried -- I never tried to resolve any legal problem with this kind as Governor of my State.", "start": 336.861, "stop": 344.525, "duration": 7.66}, {"text": "I thought that was a matter for the courts and I abided by the decision of the courts whether they were the courts of my State or in -- in their proper jurisdiction of the federal courts.", "start": 344.525, "stop": 354.809, "duration": 10.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We all realize that, sir.", "start": 354.809, "stop": 356.44, "duration": 1.63}, {"text": "The point I'm making is this.", "start": 356.44, "stop": 358.375, "duration": 1.94}, {"text": "That if the Governor of any State says, that a United State Supreme Court decision is not the law of the land, the people of that state until it is really resolved have a doubt in their mind and a right to have a doubt.", "start": 358.375, "stop": 375.998, "duration": 17.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I have never heard such an argument made in the Court of Justice before and I've tried many a case over many a years.", "start": 375.998, "stop": 384.253, "duration": 8.25}, {"text": "I never heard a lawyer say, that the statement of the Governor as to -- to what was legal or illegal should control the action of any court.", "start": 384.253, "stop": 394.797, "duration": 10.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not advocating that Mr. Chief Justice, and I -- I trust that these words will be weighed carefully.", "start": 394.797, "stop": 403.25, "duration": 8.45}, {"text": "What I'm saying is that the mass of people in a State wanting to believe a certain thing, if they are told by their chief executive that such and such is the law or is not the law, then if he is a popular and respected public official, they are inclined to believe him and what they want to hear.", "start": 403.25, "stop": 430.022, "duration": 26.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, a short answer to that is if they want to believe it, they'll believe it no matter who says it.", "start": 430.022, "stop": 437.416, "duration": 7.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, nevertheless, that is a fact and not a theory in Little Rock and that --", "start": 437.416, "stop": 445.25, "duration": 7.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have no doubt --", "start": 445.25, "stop": 446.44, "duration": 1.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "And -- and -- that is a fact and not a theory in many other localities other than in Arkansas, many --", "start": 446.44, "stop": 456.153, "duration": 9.71}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that (Inaudible) --", "start": 456.153, "stop": 457.997, "duration": 1.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 457.997, "stop": 458.789, "duration": 0.79}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- that argument.", "start": 458.789, "stop": 462.802, "duration": 4.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Your Honor we've gotten into a whole lot of things that maybe or not strictly directed towards the pleadings that are here before us, but we feel so earnestly about this.", "start": 462.802, "stop": 474.728, "duration": 11.93}, {"text": "We feel that many people, judges, lawyers, various others have taken exactly opposite stands throughout this land.", "start": 474.728, "stop": 489.656, "duration": 14.93}, {"text": "And it is my personal opinion and it's the opinion of many others, not just others that the people by and large and even judges and lawyers are not certain as to what deliberate speed means under certain circumstances.", "start": 489.656, "stop": 506.095, "duration": 16.44}, {"text": "They're not certain about what equitable principle should be applied and when.", "start": 506.095, "stop": 512.464, "duration": 6.37}, {"text": "They are not certain about laws that have not yet been tested for their constitutionality.", "start": 512.464, "stop": 519.586, "duration": 7.12}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "You're asking that the law would be clarified not that we follow their dictations.", "start": 519.586, "stop": 524.57, "duration": 4.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We're asking for a period for orderly manner of process, Your Honor and we think that the orderly processes should dictate the stay of the Circuit Court being in effect until we have gotten our petition for writ of certiorari filed and if it's granted that we be allowed to present briefs and arguments on.", "start": 524.57, "stop": 552.482, "duration": 27.91}, {"text": "That is as simply as I can state our position.", "start": 552.482, "stop": 556.017, "duration": 3.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "If your argument based on the premise of the Senate's in your opposition that the reasonable provides that the end of the (Inaudible) the national policy that has been established.", "start": 556.017, "stop": 572.868, "duration": 16.85}, {"text": "By then, state law supporting to override the Brown case that had been tested in the Court.", "start": 572.868, "stop": 580.434, "duration": 7.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 580.434, "stop": 580.706, "duration": 0.27}, {"text": "I think that's -- that's in our pleading.", "start": 580.706, "stop": 583.292, "duration": 2.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's the premise of your argument?", "start": 583.292, "stop": 585.92, "duration": 2.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 585.92, "stop": 590.202, "duration": 4.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you have any rebuttal Mr. Marshall?", "start": 590.202, "stop": 593.213, "duration": 3.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "Just one point, may it please the Court.", "start": 593.213, "stop": 595.064, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "That I want to --", "start": 595.064, "stop": 595.715, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes -- yes.", "start": 595.715, "stop": 596.393, "duration": 0.68}, {"text": "Go right ahead.", "start": 596.393, "stop": 597.082, "duration": 0.69}, {"text": "Take your time.", "start": 597.082, "stop": 597.709, "duration": 0.63}, {"text": "You have ample time.", "start": 597.709, "stop": 600.013, "duration": 2.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "There are two points.", "start": 600.013, "stop": 603.181, "duration": 3.17}, {"text": "One was this question of this empty victory.", "start": 603.181, "stop": 608.739, "duration": 5.56}, {"text": "We've had this argued in this case from beginning to end.", "start": 608.739, "stop": 612.926, "duration": 4.19}, {"text": "And I -- I think the Court will remember that the eminent attorney, the late John Davis in arguing this verdict, the Brown case stood here and argued, the story of the (Inaudible) the bone across the bridge and looking in and dropping the bone.", "start": 612.926, "stop": 631.927, "duration": 19}, {"text": "And I submit that that argument has been made to this Court, it's been disposed of in the Brown case.", "start": 631.927, "stop": 636.727, "duration": 4.8}, {"text": "It has no bearing.", "start": 636.727, "stop": 639.853, "duration": 3.13}, {"text": "On the question -- Mr. Justice Black's question about time to resolve these laws, I hope the Court realizes that as the School Board is making that argument that they must have time to get the courts to pass on the laws that were passed two years ago.", "start": 639.853, "stop": 659.287, "duration": 19.43}, {"text": "The legislature is now passing a dozen laws of solid days and I will assume that in short time they'll be back asking for time to have those laws construed and that would, it seems to me, result in perpetual delay insofar as this is concern.", "start": 659.287, "stop": 679.099, "duration": 19.81}, {"text": "The other question that Mr. Butler couldn't answer and I can't answer but I don't answer form newspapers that the three Negro children that did apply to the white schools were declined admission, that was in the newspapers by Superintendent Blossom and that he intended to maintain the policy of segregated schools come opening of this school term.", "start": 679.099, "stop": 704.945, "duration": 25.85}, {"text": "I don't know how that could get into the record it's -- it's a mere newspaper statement but the last thing, I like to call the Court's attention, as I construe Mr. Butler's argument, except for the fact that he wants time to prepare briefs.", "start": 704.945, "stop": 723.431, "duration": 18.49}, {"text": "He seems to be in complete agreement that the merits in this case have to be going into and I wish to restate that our opposition on that particular point.", "start": 723.431, "stop": 735.925, "duration": 12.49}, {"text": "I -- the -- the balance into these equities, it's not as easy as it's stated.", "start": 735.925, "stop": 743.657, "duration": 7.73}, {"text": "I realize the School Board has a difficult job but there's no solution there -- just three things that were mentioned in the Court of Appeals decision.", "start": 743.657, "stop": 754.114, "duration": 10.46}, {"text": "One was that the (Inaudible) of -- of locks over the lockers and instead of punishing the people that did it, they replaced the locks.", "start": 754.114, "stop": 765.088, "duration": 10.97}, {"text": "And I -- I hate to mention it in the court of law but the record shows in the Court of Appeals, opinion shows that the white children, the 20 or 25, a very small group start to practice of urinating on the radiators and instead of putting the children out, they put the radiators out.", "start": 765.088, "stop": 783.382, "duration": 18.29}, {"text": "And it seems to me that there's no solution to this problem that is recognizes a difficult problem as the only possible solution to put the Negro kids out of school.", "start": 783.382, "stop": 793.368, "duration": 9.99}, {"text": "I don't submit that that is the only solution.", "start": 793.368, "stop": 797.36, "duration": 3.99}, {"text": "The record in this case would bare that out and so it seems to me that whether or not this Court goes into the merits certainly, these Negro kids and the others that are involved in the class action are entitled to the most affirmative relief possible out of this Court, before school opens, even if it's a consideration of the petition for certiorari.", "start": 797.36, "stop": 834.995, "duration": 37.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor General.", "start": 834.995, "stop": 836.947, "duration": 1.95}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.", "start": 836.947, "stop": 843.944, "duration": 7}, {"text": "The government of the United States has a great interest in the maintenance and preservation of the public school system of this country.", "start": 843.944, "stop": 857.18, "duration": 13.24}, {"text": "And the Government that is the executive branch feels that this Court had that heavily on its mind when it passed on the Brown cases.", "start": 857.18, "stop": 870.402, "duration": 13.22}, {"text": "And the time that was given for the consideration over a period of four days asking for briefs especially from the Attorney General of the United States and any Attorney General of any State for segregation was either authorized or permitted.", "start": 870.402, "stop": 892.677, "duration": 22.27}, {"text": "And the care that this Court used in assigning the task of determining the plan and implementation of this opinion of the Court by the local courts that would no one understand the situations.", "start": 892.677, "stop": 913.701, "duration": 21.02}, {"text": "And then assigning to those courts, the duty and responsibility of recognizing in each case equitable principles of law in determining upon the method, procedure and timeliness of the action shows the consideration that this Court gave to the preservation of the public school system of this country.", "start": 913.701, "stop": 941.85, "duration": 28.15}, {"text": "And if you go back to the Brown decision and study as terms, you'll see that this Court with due regard for the almost un-estimated value of the public schools to the American people.", "start": 941.85, "stop": 968.12, "duration": 26.27}, {"text": "Used every care that it could conceive to try to protect that system provided the people who were trying to work in the public school system and as state officials had a duty also to preserve it in accordance with the Constitution of the United States said about the task to try to carry out the Brown decision in good faith in every step of the way.", "start": 968.12, "stop": 1005.787, "duration": 37.67}, {"text": "We all know as lawyers and the public knows it from its experience that the courts have had equitable principles that if it work -- that they have worked with over the According to Brown case centuries had worked -- that they have worked with over the centuries.", "start": 1005.787, "stop": 1020.599, "duration": 14.81}, {"text": "And according to Brown case in a note, refers to that fact, a decision of this Court in which that is set out.", "start": 1020.599, "stop": 1029.133, "duration": 8.53}, {"text": "And a court of equity does not ask people any time or any place to do things that are beyond their power, things that they cannot do but they have to try.", "start": 1029.133, "stop": 1043.935, "duration": 14.8}, {"text": "They can't say we are going to stop obeying the laws today, it's difficult.", "start": 1043.935, "stop": 1051.746, "duration": 7.81}, {"text": "I don't mean to infer in anyway a criticism of this School Board because they have it terrible time.", "start": 1051.746, "stop": 1062.55, "duration": 10.8}, {"text": "They have had imposed upon them, action by state officials who have duties exactly contrary to their actions that no School Board should have had to deal with, with this difficult problem.", "start": 1062.55, "stop": 1080.212, "duration": 17.66}, {"text": "And I'm sure that this Court in the decision of Brown case, a simple mentation did not want in any way to lose the public school system in obtaining and enforcing this principle of constitutional task.", "start": 1080.212, "stop": 1102.406, "duration": 22.19}, {"text": "Nor do I believe for one moment that the two were inconsistent, that it's impossible for all Americans to have their rights under the constitution and be treated equally under the law by the government in all its various aspects and have to destroy the institution in order to grant those rights.", "start": 1102.406, "stop": 1137.668, "duration": 35.26}, {"text": "There is ample provision in the Brown case, implementing the declaration about constitutional law -- for time, if it is actually needed in good faith to try to carry out this constitutional principle.", "start": 1137.668, "stop": 1158.449, "duration": 20.78}, {"text": "It is all there and no court of equity in this country would fail to recognize those needs if they are properly brought to its attention and if the action is in good faith and everybody according to basic principles of equitable law has done everything within his power up to that point, to accomplish the court's decree.", "start": 1158.449, "stop": 1191.443, "duration": 32.99}, {"text": "That's when an equity court comes in and acts to help out someone who has tried and done his level best in accordance with all the means of his command and then ask for some help.", "start": 1191.443, "stop": 1213.377, "duration": 21.93}, {"text": "At that point, when additional time is asked for, we think this Court has made it plain that there can't be anymore of this talk about what the law is, is it what the Governor says today or a sender says tomorrow or a Governor of neighboring State -- State says the following day?", "start": 1213.377, "stop": 1237.884, "duration": 24.51}, {"text": "The law is established, this country cannot exist without a recognition of the Supreme Court of the United States when it speaks on a legal matter, it's the law.", "start": 1237.884, "stop": 1254.03, "duration": 16.15}, {"text": "But there must be a start, there must be a recognition that it got to be, then there must some kind of a start and I believe and do regard and careful consideration of the manifold difficult problems that the south has in this whole area, that there isn't a place in the country if they have the will, can't make some kind of a start, even if it's the smallest kind for it solving this problem, granting these rights and working them out.", "start": 1254.03, "stop": 1296.792, "duration": 42.76}, {"text": "In some place, it didn't take time, longer time in and others and this Court recognized that and it has the wisdom to choose the method of the common law which doesn't say, “everyone has to follow one pattern, everybody has to do it this way” but it takes a case by case where you examine every fact, every factor in your community, every problem that the board has to deal with that is real and then works out the plan accordingly.", "start": 1296.792, "stop": 1340.529, "duration": 43.74}, {"text": "But you must have a start.", "start": 1340.529, "stop": 1342.742, "duration": 2.21}, {"text": "You can't say we're going to find out what the law is, and then subject to really find out what the law is, we'll start someday, maybe.", "start": 1342.742, "stop": 1353.306, "duration": 10.56}, {"text": "There's got to be a good faith continuous of -- of all -- and all reasonable means used, as the government believes to try to carry out the plan once you start.", "start": 1353.306, "stop": 1373.113, "duration": 19.81}, {"text": "And above all, no court of law in this land, state or federal can recognize that you can ever vow to force and violence in setting aside, faking or modifying a decree of the Court.", "start": 1373.113, "stop": 1394.941, "duration": 21.83}, {"text": "The moment you do that, you give up law and order.", "start": 1394.941, "stop": 1399.818, "duration": 4.88}, {"text": "This country can't afford any such price, no one can neither the southerner and westerner from my country, the far west to the east.", "start": 1399.818, "stop": 1414.645, "duration": 14.83}, {"text": "We have paid too great a price, not only as Americans but the human race come this far along the road of lawful action and a rule of law to give it up when someone, even the small group as in this case, only 25 in the school used force and violence to scare out the enforcement of a court order.", "start": 1414.645, "stop": 1451.888, "duration": 37.24}, {"text": "And then any change must provide active steps and progress during that modification.", "start": 1451.888, "stop": 1465.2, "duration": 13.31}, {"text": "Can't just hold it all in a base and say maybe the climate will change.", "start": 1465.2, "stop": 1471.252, "duration": 6.05}, {"text": "Maybe more people will agree, so we can see where the weight of opinion is whether it's with the courts or against them when we start to enforce the law.", "start": 1471.252, "stop": 1482.251, "duration": 11}, {"text": "As agreed in this case that this Court has the power to take the action as proposed and we think that you have to start back at the Lemley decision.", "start": 1482.251, "stop": 1496.846, "duration": 14.6}, {"text": "We think that's where the error occurred that there was a duty on the part of Judge Lemley to stay his order because he was changing the status quo.", "start": 1496.846, "stop": 1507.526, "duration": 10.68}, {"text": "The Negroes were in the school, they were under the plan at the time of his decision.", "start": 1507.526, "stop": 1515.409, "duration": 7.88}, {"text": "And so, at that point, when he was taking them out of the school, he was changing the status quo and that's where the error occurred.", "start": 1515.409, "stop": 1525.873, "duration": 10.46}, {"text": "Now, we think there's no reflection on the Eight Circuit in setting aside the stay of the Eight Circuit because we -- we -- that that court had in mind that in the ordinary procedure, this matter would reach this Court and that probably this issue should be decided at least by a denial of service by this Court in the final analysis.", "start": 1525.873, "stop": 1554.651, "duration": 28.78}, {"text": "And that it was -- with that in mind, but with this Court sitting as a complete Court, we think, that there could be no purpose in leading that order in effect because the Court could determine this matter properly whether there was a basis for certiorari and then proceed to Court.", "start": 1554.651, "stop": 1578.636, "duration": 23.98}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1578.636, "stop": 1585.422, "duration": 6.79}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes it would be a very unusual action.", "start": 1585.422, "stop": 1587.608, "duration": 2.19}, {"text": "And I hope I can argue to justify such an unusual action.", "start": 1587.608, "stop": 1593.141, "duration": 5.53}, {"text": "It is not on unprecedented as the clerk -- as counsel has conceded.", "start": 1593.141, "stop": 1599.309, "duration": 6.17}, {"text": "But it is very unusual for this Court and I want --", "start": 1599.309, "stop": 1603.18, "duration": 3.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Have we ever -- have we ever passed on a petition for certiorari that wasn't before us?", "start": 1603.18, "stop": 1610.865, "duration": 7.68}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, you have asked that it be filed during --", "start": 1610.865, "stop": 1614.8, "duration": 3.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's a very different thing.", "start": 1614.8, "stop": 1616.322, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "During argument and you have --", "start": 1616.322, "stop": 1617.453, "duration": 1.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's a very different thing.", "start": 1617.453, "stop": 1618.888, "duration": 1.43}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "You have passed upon the question of stay with the -- by passing upon the merits and losing it.", "start": 1618.888, "stop": 1625.229, "duration": 6.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's -- that's another difference.", "start": 1625.229, "stop": 1626.334, "duration": 1.11}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's right.", "start": 1626.334, "stop": 1628.521, "duration": 2.19}, {"text": "We have gone into the merits of this case with the belief that we felt that that was our duty to the Court because one of the -- the great elements or the important elements of the question of the stay is the probability of success on appeal.", "start": 1628.521, "stop": 1647.246, "duration": 18.73}, {"text": "And the courts have said that, this Court and others many times that if there is no reasonable probability of success on appeal, then the stay should not be granted.", "start": 1647.246, "stop": 1660.195, "duration": 12.95}, {"text": "So, we felt that we had to face up before the Court to the question of whether or not there was a reasonable basis for this Court to grant any relief on a petition of certiorari on the merits or we had to say to the Court, a stay is reasonable.", "start": 1660.195, "stop": 1680.991, "duration": 20.8}, {"text": "Even though in balancing the equities we might lean towards going back to reserve the status quo that existed when Judge Lemley started.", "start": 1680.991, "stop": 1693.669, "duration": 12.68}, {"text": "We would still have to say to the court that if there was something in the merits of this case that deserved it, that a stay might be reasonable and would have been entirely a different argument.", "start": 1693.669, "stop": 1706.431, "duration": 12.76}, {"text": "Though, we have addressed ourselves to the proposition that there is nothing to this case that would justify this Court ever granting certiorari or acting upon the merits of it.", "start": 1706.431, "stop": 1721.291, "duration": 14.86}, {"text": "And there is no probable success that could be obtained by the petitioners in -- in this action, because under the law, they are not entitled to relieve at the hands of this Court.", "start": 1721.291, "stop": 1742.579, "duration": 21.29}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 1742.579, "stop": 1745.123, "duration": 2.54}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is our position.", "start": 1745.123, "stop": 1747.339, "duration": 2.22}, {"text": "Now, the whole matter boils down as we see it to exactly what the Court of Appeals of the Eight Circuit said.", "start": 1747.339, "stop": 1756.957, "duration": 9.62}, {"text": "The Negroes did nothing to cause this situation.", "start": 1756.957, "stop": 1762.018, "duration": 5.06}, {"text": "All the difficulty that you have is force and violence that was developed by a relatively small group of people who were opposed to the implementation of this decree of the Court.", "start": 1762.018, "stop": 1777.389, "duration": 15.37}, {"text": "It appeared inside the school and outside of the school.", "start": 1777.389, "stop": 1782.445, "duration": 5.06}, {"text": "But that's all it was and the Court of Appeals are finding the facts as they were found by the lower court said that they could not accept the conclusions of that court.", "start": 1782.445, "stop": 1796.817, "duration": 14.37}, {"text": "They found -- the Court of Appeals found that the cause -- the cause and effect of that action throughout was opposition to this Court's decision and the implementation of it and with the use of force and violence.", "start": 1796.817, "stop": 1815.217, "duration": 18.4}, {"text": "Now, this Court has said that the case is referred to by counsel, that you cannot accept force and violence as a justification or modification of a decree that there is no basis in this whole situation except to that.", "start": 1815.217, "stop": 1836.658, "duration": 21.44}, {"text": "Now, there is a further fact and further claim that there was a deterioration of educational standards in this school because of the implementation of this decree.", "start": 1836.658, "stop": 1850.705, "duration": 14.05}, {"text": "And the Court of Appeals held that that deterioration was not due to the implementation of a decree or any act to these colored children but was due to these people using these unlawful acts of violence and force to try to defeat the decree, the decision of this Court and its implementation and that that could never be a ground for any kind of relief.", "start": 1850.705, "stop": 1882.472, "duration": 31.77}, {"text": "Of course this Court already anticipated that grounds, that the vitality of the decision could not be defeated by any -- any opposition on the part of the populace as it's been argued before this Court.", "start": 1882.472, "stop": 1904.07, "duration": 21.6}, {"text": "The Court went into -- in some detail, examples of various types of problems that anticipated the school districts might have, that could be considered not merely in the implementation of the original order or plan but for changes as time develop to show that those changes became necessary in the operatin of the plan.", "start": 1904.07, "stop": 1936.854, "duration": 32.78}, {"text": "But of course, nothing like force and violence or opposition to the decision itself was recognized.", "start": 1936.854, "stop": 1944.12, "duration": 7.27}, {"text": "In fact, the Court (Inaudible) would not recognize that.", "start": 1944.12, "stop": 1954.839, "duration": 10.72}, {"text": "I don't mean to, in these remarks, to criticize the School Board.", "start": 1954.839, "stop": 1961.356, "duration": 6.52}, {"text": "I do -- do not want it to be construed in that manner but I do think, the Government takes the position that the School Board did not exhaust all of the things that they could have done to try to solve the situation.", "start": 1961.356, "stop": 1980.602, "duration": 19.25}, {"text": "And I -- they probably could not be blamed or because of the harassment that they suffered but when you considered the matter in a court of equity, you have to recognize that as a crime first consideration have they exhausted, the various steps that they might take to carry out the court order before they ask for remedial relief against it.", "start": 1980.602, "stop": 2015.084, "duration": 34.48}, {"text": "There are two respects that the school district did not do what it might have.", "start": 2015.084, "stop": 2020.149, "duration": 5.06}, {"text": "They're referred to by the Court of Appeals.", "start": 2020.149, "stop": 2022.87, "duration": 2.72}, {"text": "One was to seek a Hoxie or Clinton type of injunction against the acts of people who are making all the trouble for them.", "start": 2022.87, "stop": 2035.341, "duration": 12.47}, {"text": "Now, it's clear in the record that they knew the names of the various people in the organizations who are engaged in the opposition and leading and participating as clear.", "start": 2035.341, "stop": 2049.17, "duration": 13.83}, {"text": "So, they have the ability and they can't regain say that they were officers of the State of Arkansas.", "start": 2049.17, "stop": 2059.722, "duration": 10.55}, {"text": "It was their official duty to do what they could and they should have resorted to the courts without such injunction and we believe that would have made a material difference.", "start": 2059.722, "stop": 2072.065, "duration": 12.34}, {"text": "If after such an injunction, there was a violation to such an extent that the lawful forces in the area would bear in mind, have the primary responsibility in this country to maintain law and order, could not maintain law and order.", "start": 2072.065, "stop": 2094.801, "duration": 22.74}, {"text": "And the other forces that might be called upon, the assistance of the federal government were unable, then we would have a different situation for an act of court to consider but they didn't do that.", "start": 2094.801, "stop": 2112.398, "duration": 17.6}, {"text": "And that is an important aid that they could have obtained for themselves before they appealed to the court.", "start": 2112.398, "stop": 2120.725, "duration": 8.33}, {"text": "There is no question of what there could have been, firmer discipline within the school itself and that it would have aided materially in maintaining the educational processes on a level these children both white and colored were entitled to.", "start": 2120.725, "stop": 2142.601, "duration": 21.88}, {"text": "But when you talk about a deterioration of the educational process in this school, it seems to me that one of the things that all educators, certain teachers would recognize is that part of the educational process, is the attitude and conduct of the teachers, the personnel of the school and the children themselves.", "start": 2142.601, "stop": 2177.456, "duration": 34.86}, {"text": "And part of their responsibility is to get across to those teachers and the teachers to get across to the children, and those that are in the educational process.", "start": 2177.456, "stop": 2193.503, "duration": 16.05}, {"text": "The responsibility to enforce the laws that we do live in a country where we seek to maintain law and order for the benefit of all the people that the Constitution and each of the rights that every citizen has under it is precious to everyone of us.", "start": 2193.503, "stop": 2219.71, "duration": 26.21}, {"text": "Not just the rights that I like and want for me or that you like and want for you but all of this, for every man and woman.", "start": 2219.71, "stop": 2235.886, "duration": 16.18}, {"text": "And that if you teach these children in Little Rock or any other place in the country, that as soon as you get some force and violence, the courts and law on this country are going to bow to it.", "start": 2235.886, "stop": 2252.558, "duration": 16.67}, {"text": "They have no power to deal with it.", "start": 2252.558, "stop": 2256.399, "duration": 3.84}, {"text": "They will give way to it.", "start": 2256.399, "stop": 2259.032, "duration": 2.63}, {"text": "We change everything to accommodate the (Inaudible).", "start": 2259.032, "stop": 2263.683, "duration": 4.65}, {"text": "I think that you destroyed the whole educational process then and there.", "start": 2263.683, "stop": 2273.588, "duration": 9.91}, {"text": "If out of this difficult and undesired situation, the people of Little Rock and these children who shouldn't be hurt by these problems, learn that constitutional rights in this country are precious that they have a duty to these Negro boys and girls in this community to help them get their constitutional right.", "start": 2273.588, "stop": 2310.092, "duration": 36.5}, {"text": "And this constitutional right happens to be the right to enter a school at any (Inaudible).", "start": 2310.092, "stop": 2317.43, "duration": 7.34}, {"text": "But someday they will want other constitutional rights and be able to exercise them, freedom of speech in the press and everything else that we consider, so wonderful in our form of government.", "start": 2317.43, "stop": 2334.081, "duration": 16.65}, {"text": "And you can't tear down part of those rights without losing others in the process.", "start": 2334.081, "stop": 2344.657, "duration": 10.58}, {"text": "And there isn't any part of this country that doesn't have a tremendous state in maintaining each and all of those rights for all of its people.", "start": 2344.657, "stop": 2363.809, "duration": 19.15}, {"text": "And I'm confident that as the years go by where people of the south, as a people will realize that they have a steak in each American citizen being a full citizen with full and complete rights like any other and they will be anxious to support and fight for that at every opportunity.", "start": 2363.809, "stop": 2401.141, "duration": 37.33}, {"text": "It seems to me that we are now at the crossroads in this important question.", "start": 2401.141, "stop": 2411.569, "duration": 10.43}, {"text": "The people of the country are entitled to a definitive state on this Court as to whether or not force and violence, opposition to the Court's decision aren't enough for not merely getting a modification to try to adapt the real problems after they have exhausted their remedy.", "start": 2411.569, "stop": 2439.983, "duration": 28.41}, {"text": "But to just hold everything up and goes back with as step taking everybody out that you tried to believe in.", "start": 2439.983, "stop": 2451.939, "duration": 11.96}, {"text": "And the basic question all there really is in the case is whether or not we stand as a Government of the United States and all of its power and strength, as well as its consideration of the difficulties and problems that are real, that people have in trying to carry out quarrels.", "start": 2451.939, "stop": 2491.618, "duration": 39.68}, {"text": "We insist that there must be a rule of law, that we will not abandon for a moment the heritage that has been delivered up to us by the efforts of man over centuries.", "start": 2491.618, "stop": 2513.285, "duration": 21.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Marshall, do you have anything to say in response to the Solicitor General?", "start": 2513.285, "stop": 2517.448, "duration": 4.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir, if Your Honor please.", "start": 2517.448, "stop": 2518.909, "duration": 1.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler, do you?", "start": 2518.909, "stop": 2521.394, "duration": 2.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2521.394, "stop": 2521.454, "duration": 0.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "You may proceed.", "start": 2521.454, "stop": 2523.926, "duration": 2.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "If the Court please.", "start": 2523.926, "stop": 2531.034, "duration": 7.11}, {"text": "We likewise do not ought to be critical of the Attorney General's office but we have some ideas about where it may have failed in a few instances.", "start": 2531.034, "stop": 2544.925, "duration": 13.89}, {"text": "In the Honorable, Mr. Rankin's summation, he says in one part of the argument that this Court should give a definitive statement and then he argue strongly that unquestionably, the writ of certiorari would be denied.", "start": 2544.925, "stop": 2564.329, "duration": 19.4}, {"text": "It seems to me that that is a rather inconsistent position to take because if the writ is denied, I think, customarily at least just two words.", "start": 2564.329, "stop": 2579.693, "duration": 15.36}, {"text": "Writ denied, come out.", "start": 2579.693, "stop": 2580.913, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "I don't see how a definitive action on the part of this Court or a definitive decision, an opinion could be rendered under those circumstances which Mr. Rankin advocated.", "start": 2580.913, "stop": 2595.61, "duration": 14.7}, {"text": "Now, I have some difficulty in following just exactly, the position that the Government is taking in this thing.", "start": 2595.61, "stop": 2606.067, "duration": 10.46}, {"text": "I don't get the same impression from a very hurried reading.", "start": 2606.067, "stop": 2609.457, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "It's true.", "start": 2609.457, "stop": 2610.554, "duration": 1.1}, {"text": "We only receive the Government's brief this morning.", "start": 2610.554, "stop": 2615.299, "duration": 4.74}, {"text": "We've only had a time to scan it but I don't quite get the consistency of the statements in the brief as against his admission that everyone has conceded that the Little Rock School Board has acted in good faith.", "start": 2615.299, "stop": 2638.192, "duration": 22.89}, {"text": "Now, he made the statement that there should be good faith.", "start": 2638.192, "stop": 2642.834, "duration": 4.64}, {"text": "The courts have found that the Little Rock School Board in all instances has acted in good faith.", "start": 2642.834, "stop": 2649.93, "duration": 7.1}, {"text": "It has found many other things which the Circuit Court of Appeals finds no fault with Judge Lemley's findings.", "start": 2649.93, "stop": 2657.548, "duration": 7.62}, {"text": "Among which is that this School Board cannot operate under the conditions which it faces as of this time unless troops are stationed in the building and outside the ground.", "start": 2657.548, "stop": 2675.095, "duration": 17.55}, {"text": "Now, he states that it is time to come in and ask for equitable relief when all has been done within the power of the School Board.", "start": 2675.095, "stop": 2687.257, "duration": 12.16}, {"text": "We submit that this record throughout and everything that the School Board has done has not only been in good faith, but they have gone to the point to try to carry out the United States Supreme Court orders and the orders of the law of federal courts, to the extent of being harassed and humiliated among their own people.", "start": 2687.257, "stop": 2712.85, "duration": 25.59}, {"text": "They have done that day-by-day.", "start": 2712.85, "stop": 2715.893, "duration": 3.04}, {"text": "They were faced with the situation in September of 1957, as we pointed out earlier of troops being ordered in by one commander and then troops being order in by somebody else.", "start": 2715.893, "stop": 2729.905, "duration": 14.01}, {"text": "And those troops remain and in spite of that, the Little Rock School Board after it got into really the school year of operating, hoping all along that maybe the situation would resolve itself, therefore troops would be unnecessary.", "start": 2729.905, "stop": 2748.748, "duration": 18.84}, {"text": "They went clear from the first part of September, clear to the latter part of February before going into the court of equity and asking for relief.", "start": 2748.748, "stop": 2760.316, "duration": 11.57}, {"text": "We submit that that is good faith.", "start": 2760.316, "stop": 2763.187, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "We submit that they were entitled to equitable relief under those circumstancess.", "start": 2763.187, "stop": 2767.504, "duration": 4.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler --", "start": 2767.504, "stop": 2768.037, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now --", "start": 2768.037, "stop": 2768.15, "duration": 0.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Isn't there a difference between good faith in the sense of sincere, honestly entertained conviction and good faith in throwing out your hand and say we can't don't anything against the Court.", "start": 2768.15, "stop": 2784.328, "duration": 16.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2784.328, "stop": 2784.71, "duration": 0.38}, {"text": "I think a different distinction could be made there, Your Honor, I do indeed.", "start": 2784.71, "stop": 2790.178, "duration": 5.47}, {"text": "Now, the fact --", "start": 2790.178, "stop": 2791.049, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "And may I -- may I -- do you think -- you conceive of that as being a charge merely that the School Board of Arkansas has denied an equal protection or a charge in the State of the Arkansas has denied equal protection?", "start": 2791.049, "stop": 2808.076, "duration": 17.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, of course, it's the School Board that takes the brand of it and the charge is that the School Board, some people have made the charges and I understand that from the Solicitor General.", "start": 2808.076, "stop": 2821.68, "duration": 13.6}, {"text": "That the School Board haven't done everything that it should have.", "start": 2821.68, "stop": 2825.748, "duration": 4.07}, {"text": "Now, the fact is, the realities of the situation are that the N.A.A.C.P. which has rather vast resources and certainly, able legal counsel had a perfect right to come in and ask for injunctive relief and it did not do so.", "start": 2825.748, "stop": 2843.416, "duration": 17.67}, {"text": "The Justice Department had every right to put forward any criminal actions that were in order and it did not do so.", "start": 2843.416, "stop": 2857.353, "duration": 13.94}, {"text": "And now, we have the President of the United States saying that the process should go slower if we are to read the newspapers accurately and if the newspapers reported it accurately.", "start": 2857.353, "stop": 2872.323, "duration": 14.97}, {"text": "Now, that's exactly the position that the Little Rock School Board is taking.", "start": 2872.323, "stop": 2877.412, "duration": 5.09}, {"text": "We're not arguing and I hope the Court does not misunderstand this.", "start": 2877.412, "stop": 2882.369, "duration": 4.96}, {"text": "The School Board has recognized from the beginning and still does.", "start": 2882.369, "stop": 2887.976, "duration": 5.61}, {"text": "First, that the ultimate decision of any question of this kind is a question of law and that the final decision of the United States Supreme Court must stay.", "start": 2887.976, "stop": 2900.007, "duration": 12.03}, {"text": "We have never argued otherwise.", "start": 2900.007, "stop": 2902.54, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "Furthermore, we say though that until such time and under the words of the decision itself, we should be given ample time within which to try to resolve these problems in -- in an atmosphere of calm rather than of his theory.", "start": 2902.54, "stop": 2923.435, "duration": 20.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could you correct me if I'm wrong, Mr. Butler, in concluding that the position of the School Board from the time of its original incubation of its plan and it's submission to the Court, et cetera, et cetera.", "start": 2923.435, "stop": 2937.538, "duration": 14.1}, {"text": "Has never taken the position that there's any reason for not carrying out a plan except the interposition of force, not of its own choosing, but obstructed the orderly process of what it had planned and its original program was, the obstruction of course.", "start": 2937.538, "stop": 2956.859, "duration": 19.32}, {"text": "Is that a fair summary of the situation?", "start": 2956.859, "stop": 2958.827, "duration": 1.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2958.827, "stop": 2959.194, "duration": 0.37}, {"text": "I don't think it is, Your Honor.", "start": 2959.194, "stop": 2960.727, "duration": 1.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 2960.727, "stop": 2960.854, "duration": 0.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "For this -- for this reason.", "start": 2960.854, "stop": 2962.636, "duration": 1.78}, {"text": "The plan itself was to have been somewhat flexible.", "start": 2962.636, "stop": 2967.23, "duration": 4.59}, {"text": "The School Board recognized that they could not set down hard and fast crew --", "start": 2967.23, "stop": 2971.629, "duration": 4.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Right.", "start": 2971.629, "stop": 2972.451, "duration": 0.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "They fail and they earnestly fail, that they could be upheld in showing the way, you might say, to the people there that the decision of the United State Supreme Court had to be carried out and their purpose was two folds, first, to maintain a public school system and second to carry out the orders of the federal court of any other court in some jurisdiction.", "start": 2972.451, "stop": 3001.592, "duration": 29.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And so they begun -- and so they begun with the high school.", "start": 3001.592, "stop": 3005.282, "duration": 3.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3005.282, "stop": 3005.668, "duration": 0.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And they were going to stagger it.", "start": 3005.668, "stop": 3008.093, "duration": 2.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 3008.093, "stop": 3008.288, "duration": 0.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "We're going to gain experience through the introduction of nondiscrimination in the high school.", "start": 3008.288, "stop": 3014.891, "duration": 6.6}, {"text": "But what I want to know is if that that plan was frustrated or obstructed, not planning education (Inaudible) or to the extent that there was educational experience, tension, etcetera.", "start": 3014.891, "stop": 3029.192, "duration": 14.3}, {"text": "The cause of this fact though, the real reason was not anything due to what the plan of the Board or the experience gained there under but what happened to outside forces.", "start": 3029.192, "stop": 3042.039, "duration": 12.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well --", "start": 3042.039, "stop": 3042.768, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is that correct?", "start": 3042.768, "stop": 3043.616, "duration": 0.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I don't know what was in the thinking of each School Board member.", "start": 3043.616, "stop": 3046.124, "duration": 2.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I'm not talking about the thinking.", "start": 3046.124, "stop": 3047.564, "duration": 1.44}, {"text": "But -- at no point, is there any document in which they say, “We have now had experience, educational experience, and the plan which we mature honestly, began to be operative in the school year of 1957.", "start": 3047.564, "stop": 3063.654, "duration": 16.09}, {"text": "The experience now shows us that educationally speaking, that is not a sound plan.", "start": 3063.654, "stop": 3071.347, "duration": 7.69}, {"text": "Is there anything to suggest that the thinking of the School Board has originally contrived and divide and formulated was changed because of educational experiences rather than because -- beginning with the Governor's intervention construes outside forces begun to frustrate and block, the carrying out of what the School Board had agreed upon.", "start": 3071.347, "stop": 3095.351, "duration": 24}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'd say, educational forces or processes, if you're going to use a broad term because the School Board was faced with certain realities.", "start": 3095.351, "stop": 3104.503, "duration": 9.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's because realities are attributable if you're going to trace them to their courses.It wasn't any educational experience.", "start": 3104.503, "stop": 3111.795, "duration": 7.29}, {"text": "It wasn't the feeling that you couldn't have colored children with white children educationally speaking but because of the intervention of outside force, forces were brought into play which obstructed that which they have so carefully planned.", "start": 3111.795, "stop": 3126.234, "duration": 14.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that's a difficult thing to answer because I say again, it's so intertwined.", "start": 3126.234, "stop": 3131.618, "duration": 5.38}, {"text": "They don't know why they failed.", "start": 3131.618, "stop": 3135.316, "duration": 3.7}, {"text": "They don't know exactly, they can't point to any one thing.", "start": 3135.316, "stop": 3138.58, "duration": 3.26}, {"text": "They know this though.", "start": 3138.58, "stop": 3139.941, "duration": 1.36}, {"text": "The School Board knows that they were faced not with theories but with realities such as armed troops parading the hall and the grounds of one of their schools.", "start": 3139.941, "stop": 3153.582, "duration": 13.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I accept that.", "start": 3153.582, "stop": 3154.389, "duration": 0.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now that to me then to answer your question that is an educational factor in the broad sense.", "start": 3154.389, "stop": 3163.183, "duration": 8.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I should say it's a consequence -- as a consequence of those conditions, educational results follow.", "start": 3163.183, "stop": 3169.173, "duration": 5.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well --", "start": 3169.173, "stop": 3169.562, "duration": 0.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "If you can't teach, if you're going to have troops in the classroom.", "start": 3169.562, "stop": 3173.493, "duration": 3.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "That was exactly the feeling of Judge Lemley and Judge Lemley found and there has been nothing to the contrary that that is likely what will happen again.", "start": 3173.493, "stop": 3184.335, "duration": 10.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But it wasn't the School Board that rejected the Armed Forces, was it?", "start": 3184.335, "stop": 3190.444, "duration": 6.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 3190.444, "stop": 3190.946, "duration": 0.5}, {"text": "The School Board didn't ask for them but there were times there when, I think, I'm correct in saying that they were glad that some force was there to protect order and keep people from being injured.", "start": 3190.946, "stop": 3205.191, "duration": 14.24}, {"text": "Now the -- the Solicitor General tries to compare Hoxie, Arkansas and Clinton, Tennessee.", "start": 3205.191, "stop": 3215.485, "duration": 10.29}, {"text": "There is absolutely no comparison and if anyone has been in those places, you can readily recognize that there is none.", "start": 3215.485, "stop": 3224.252, "duration": 8.77}, {"text": "In the first place, you have an entirely different number of people involved, you have a much smaller school, you have a School Board in that place -- in both of those places dealing directly with the people that they and everyone else could put their finger on as interfering with it.", "start": 3224.252, "stop": 3241.291, "duration": 17.04}, {"text": "That was not the case in Little Rock.", "start": 3241.291, "stop": 3243.257, "duration": 1.97}, {"text": "The School Board does not know the law was interfering with it.", "start": 3243.257, "stop": 3247.411, "duration": 4.15}, {"text": "And for counsel to say, that the record shows that there were only 25 students involved.", "start": 3247.411, "stop": 3256.012, "duration": 8.6}, {"text": "That is not an accurate statement for this reason.", "start": 3256.012, "stop": 3260.623, "duration": 4.61}, {"text": "There was some testimony that said that they felt there might have been as many as 25 ringleaders.", "start": 3260.623, "stop": 3266.758, "duration": 6.13}, {"text": "But if you replace those 25, there would be 25 more likely and the fact is and this, of course, is undisputed that there were 200 students that this School Board suspended because they walked out in opposition to this.", "start": 3266.758, "stop": 3286.104, "duration": 19.35}, {"text": "Now, we submit that the record shows that the School Board did use as firm measures as School Boards ordinarily can and should.", "start": 3286.104, "stop": 3297.155, "duration": 11.05}, {"text": "It had no police power, it had no troops.", "start": 3297.155, "stop": 3298.951, "duration": 1.8}, {"text": "It had no closed -- kind of plainclothesman.", "start": 3298.951, "stop": 3303.882, "duration": 4.93}, {"text": "It had no on like that.", "start": 3303.882, "stop": 3306.964, "duration": 3.08}, {"text": "It has absolutely no duty in our concept of the law to go out and preserve the public peace.", "start": 3306.964, "stop": 3315.62, "duration": 8.66}, {"text": "That is not its function, it is not equipped to do that, and I think there can be no successful argument that there ever should be.", "start": 3315.62, "stop": 3327.531, "duration": 11.91}, {"text": "The School Board should be equipped to maintain peace and order within a community.", "start": 3327.531, "stop": 3334.105, "duration": 6.57}, {"text": "Now, in effect, the School Board did do more in Little Rock to try to work this thing out than either the Justice Department or the petitioners themselves.", "start": 3334.105, "stop": 3369.386, "duration": 35.28}, {"text": "We say again and we emphasize, that we do not criticize them anymore than they criticize us for failing to do some of the things that other people might have agreed should be done, or people would argue now should be done from the standpoint of hindsight rather than foresight.", "start": 3369.386, "stop": 3392.369, "duration": 22.98}, {"text": "But the fact is that no one in the Government brought any criminal actions, there was constant consultation between the two, trying to work out problems but nothing was done.", "start": 3392.369, "stop": 3408.763, "duration": 16.39}, {"text": "The School Board did not advocate if they do anything, they didn't advocate because they're not law enforcement officers.", "start": 3408.763, "stop": 3418.814, "duration": 10.05}, {"text": "They were trying as best they could to operate the school system.", "start": 3418.814, "stop": 3425.367, "duration": 6.55}, {"text": "Now, we point out again that the School Board was left on the hands of a dilemma and the fact is, and it is never been disputed, that this School Board is in an untenable position.", "start": 3425.367, "stop": 3444.792, "duration": 19.42}, {"text": "And all we're asking -- all we're asking at this time is for time to try to do those things and work out these problems that may bring peace and harmony and do it in a period of calm, when they can be done and not in a period of turmoil and strife.", "start": 3444.792, "stop": 3466.888, "duration": 22.1}, {"text": "Even in cases and I don't want to argue the merits of this thing again but the -- it's -- it's a fact that even in cases where defendants are found to have violated antitrust law.", "start": 3466.888, "stop": 3482.25, "duration": 15.36}, {"text": "And in those cases someone's constitutional rights are always involved or their legal rights.As much as five years or more, in many cases, people are given time within which to dispose of holding.", "start": 3482.25, "stop": 3498.347, "duration": 16.1}, {"text": "And do it in an orderly fashion.", "start": 3498.347, "stop": 3501.203, "duration": 2.86}, {"text": "That's the whole purpose.", "start": 3501.203, "stop": 3503.356, "duration": 2.15}, {"text": "Now, shall the courts deny citizens in a community, a reasonable opportunity to reach these solutions in a period of calm and quiet rather than with troops present and in an atmosphere of strife and turmoil?", "start": 3503.356, "stop": 3520.252, "duration": 16.9}, {"text": "Shall the courts close the door on those who earnestly and conscientiously plead for an opportunity to seek answers in a climate of calm?", "start": 3520.252, "stop": 3530.277, "duration": 10.03}, {"text": "Shall the courts force private citizens and officials and general assemblies to make decisions when the area is charged with the motions?", "start": 3530.277, "stop": 3539.206, "duration": 8.93}, {"text": "Any such impatient attitude by courts would certainly not be in keeping with the decision in this case where it was stated that flexible principles of equity in adjusting and reconciling public needs should come in to being.", "start": 3539.206, "stop": 3555.413, "duration": 16.21}, {"text": "Can it be logically argued that the ruling of this Court can be carried out, as this Court said it should in an effective manner, when schools are closed or if operated at all with armed troops parading not only the ground with the halls and classrooms themselves?", "start": 3555.413, "stop": 3578.694, "duration": 23.28}, {"text": "Patients and forbearance for a short while might save our public school system in Little Rock which was once the pride of our community to vacate the stay order might as effectively destroy our public school -- school system under the present atmosphere and if not given time.", "start": 3578.694, "stop": 3601.743, "duration": 23.05}, {"text": "As if you planted a bomb under each integrated school building in the district and lighted the fuses one-by-one.", "start": 3601.743, "stop": 3610.82, "duration": 9.08}, {"text": "Only this Court has the answer.One answer leads to the immediate destruction, in our best judgment of our public school program in Little Rock, depriving white and Negro students alike of their search for an education.", "start": 3610.82, "stop": 3629.927, "duration": 19.11}, {"text": "The other answer, without depriving these petitioners of any tangible rights or benefits gives a recess from a turmoil and the hope of acceptable solutions.", "start": 3629.927, "stop": 3644.925, "duration": 15}, {"text": "This is the answer we perfectly see.", "start": 3644.925, "stop": 3651.811, "duration": 6.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Gentlemen, we all -- we all came together on rather short notice and I know the Court would have me thanked both Mr. Marshall and Mr. Butler for your able and helpful arguments made on such short notice.", "start": 3651.811, "stop": 3668.124, "duration": 16.31}, {"text": "Mr. Solicitor General the Court is indeed indebted to you for your cooperative and -- and able argument in this case.", "start": 3668.124, "stop": 3678.918, "duration": 10.79}, {"text": "Now, gentlemen we're going to take a recess for -- until 4:30 in this matter --", "start": 3678.918, "stop": 3686.029, "duration": 7.11}]}]}, {"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - September 11, 1958 (Part 1)", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13538", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Court has now reconvened in special term to consider an application by the petitioners for a writ of certiorari to the United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit in the case of William Cooper et al., versus John Aaron et al., Number One Miscellaneous and a motion for vacation of a stay of execution granted by the Court of Appeals for Eighth Circuit in that case.", "start": 0, "stop": 34.553, "duration": 34.55}, {"text": "The petition was filed on September 8, 1958 in accordance with the order of the Court of August 28, 1958.", "start": 34.553, "stop": 46.555, "duration": 12}, {"text": "The briefs of petitioners and respondents were timely filed on September 9th and 10th respectively.", "start": 46.555, "stop": 55.556, "duration": 9}, {"text": "In addition five motions have been received for leave to file briefs as amicus curiae.", "start": 55.556, "stop": 62.582, "duration": 7.03}, {"text": "Three of these were addressed to the proceeding instituted by the respondents here for the vacation of the order of the United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit staying the issuance of its mandate, and for a stay of the order of the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Arkansas of June 21, 1958 in Aaron et al., versus Cooper et al.", "start": 62.582, "stop": 86.455, "duration": 23.87}, {"text": "Two are addressed to the instant proceeding.", "start": 86.455, "stop": 89.992, "duration": 3.54}, {"text": "Treating them all as addressed to the interest -- the instant proceeding, all motions for leave to file amicus curiae briefs and to intervene and argue are denied.", "start": 89.992, "stop": 106.275, "duration": 16.28}, {"text": "The petition for a writ of certiorari is granted and we will now proceed to the argument of the case on the merits.", "start": 106.275, "stop": 114.638, "duration": 8.36}, {"text": "The order of augment will be first the petitioners, second the respondents, then the Solicitor General and thereafter either of the parties in rebuttal of the Solicitor General, the petitioners to speak last.", "start": 114.638, "stop": 130.371, "duration": 15.73}, {"text": "Counsel may wish to obtain the admission of associates for the purposes of this case, if this is desired the Court will entertain such motions now.", "start": 130.371, "stop": 140.89, "duration": 10.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice and I have with me as co-counsel, Mr. A. F. House of the Little Rock Bar.", "start": 140.89, "stop": 147.731, "duration": 6.84}, {"text": "He has been admitted to practice before this Court for many years.", "start": 147.731, "stop": 151.732, "duration": 4}, {"text": "We also have as co-counsel, Mr. John Haley of Little Rock who has not yet been admitted to practice before this Court, but who we hope will be given permission to appear on the briefs as his name does appear there in this title.", "start": 151.732, "stop": 168.937, "duration": 17.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "And you wish him admitted for the purposes of this case now Mr. Butler?", "start": 168.937, "stop": 173.074, "duration": 4.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "If you please sir, but not for the purpose of oral argument.", "start": 173.074, "stop": 175.712, "duration": 2.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, well he maybe so admitted and --", "start": 175.712, "stop": 178.325, "duration": 2.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 178.325, "stop": 178.62, "duration": 0.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- for such service he maybe to you.", "start": 178.62, "stop": 184.198, "duration": 5.58}, {"text": "We will now proceed with the argument of the case Mr. Butler.", "start": 184.198, "stop": 189.846, "duration": 5.65}, {"text": "And may I say before we start that the Court appreciates the cooperation that we've had from counsel on both sides of the case in facilitating the hearing for us today.", "start": 189.846, "stop": 204.445, "duration": 14.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you Your Honor, Mr. Chief Justice and justices of the Supreme Court.", "start": 204.445, "stop": 210.08, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "For the record and in view of the Court's ruling that amicus curiae briefs will not be permitted, we would like for the record to show, however, that it has been the position of these petitioners for this writ, not to withhold their consent for any amicus curiae brief to be filed by any proper person.", "start": 210.08, "stop": 238.488, "duration": 28.41}, {"text": "We have had them submitted to us.", "start": 238.488, "stop": 240.305, "duration": 1.82}, {"text": "I'm afraid that all of them have not come to our attention particularly, and we have perhaps not responded to those, but for this record we would like to state that we have no objection to any briefs amicus curiae being filed and being considered by this Court.", "start": 240.305, "stop": 262.665, "duration": 22.36}, {"text": "We have stated the issues as we see them in our brief.", "start": 262.665, "stop": 272.362, "duration": 9.7}, {"text": "We see no particular reason at this time to read those.", "start": 272.362, "stop": 277.756, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "We've tired to state them as succinctly and yet as fully as we believe this Court would have us do.", "start": 277.756, "stop": 290.144, "duration": 12.39}, {"text": "We believe that the manner and the methods employed by the United States Supreme Court in the two Brown decisions of 1954 and 1955 recognized the complexities of this problem as had previous courts in determining issues of a similar nature.", "start": 290.144, "stop": 315.542, "duration": 25.4}, {"text": "Both of the Brown decisions in our opinion reflect an understanding by this Court of the history of the Negro race and of the cultural patterns throughout this land.", "start": 315.542, "stop": 334.212, "duration": 18.67}, {"text": "As Mr. Blossom, the Superintendent of The Little Rock school board stated and we quoted him in the brief and we quoted him at the last hearing, he has set forth we think an accurate outline of the history of this minority group within this country.", "start": 334.212, "stop": 361.763, "duration": 27.55}, {"text": "And briefly it is this that from 1619 to 1865 history shows that there was slavery in this land.", "start": 361.763, "stop": 374.188, "duration": 12.43}, {"text": "That is a period of two-and-a-half centauries.", "start": 374.188, "stop": 378.485, "duration": 4.3}, {"text": "From 1865 to 1896, I believe the way he termed it and some historians termed it as enforced citizenship.", "start": 378.485, "stop": 390.335, "duration": 11.85}, {"text": "That was a period of 31 years, ending as he viewed it and as we view it, and as many historians view it, by the case of Plessy versus Ferguson which announced separate but equal doctrine insofar as educational processes in this country are concerned, public education.", "start": 390.335, "stop": 417.52, "duration": 27.19}, {"text": "The third period we --", "start": 417.52, "stop": 418.502, "duration": 0.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That isn't quite what the case did, did it?", "start": 418.502, "stop": 422.861, "duration": 4.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It announced the doctrine Mr. Justice Frankfurter.", "start": 422.861, "stop": 425.95, "duration": 3.09}, {"text": "It did not deal with public education of course.", "start": 425.95, "stop": 428.451, "duration": 2.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "All I'm saying is your qualification as applied to education could not be fairly said to be the decision --", "start": 428.451, "stop": 436.236, "duration": 7.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well of course we all recognize that the case itself dealt with public transportation.", "start": 436.236, "stop": 440.58, "duration": 4.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have no doubt you did, I have no doubt you did.", "start": 440.58, "stop": 443.633, "duration": 3.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the dictum in the case was the first that I'm aware of where the doctrine of separate but equal facilities was held to be constitutional.", "start": 443.633, "stop": 460.025, "duration": 16.39}, {"text": "Then from 1896 until 1954, of course this country operated under that doctrine.", "start": 460.025, "stop": 468.413, "duration": 8.39}, {"text": "That was a period of 58 years.", "start": 468.413, "stop": 472.028, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "From 1954 until now and into the future, there are question marks of course, as to the period of time that effective education can pass from the transition period, from the separate but equal doctrine into complete desegregation.", "start": 472.028, "stop": 500.781, "duration": 28.75}, {"text": "We believe that this Court recognized that time was required for certain cultural patterns to change, and that obviously this Court recognized the necessity or at least the desirability of referring those matters to the local district courts for innumerable problems which this Court recognized would arise and some of which were enumerated in the decision.", "start": 500.781, "stop": 539.422, "duration": 38.64}, {"text": "Deliberate speed as used by this Court is certainly not just a phrase coined on the spur of the moment or developed as a philosophy of opportunism to solve an immediate problem, but instead to us it was a carefully conceived philosophy of deliberation, which along for legal reasons for delay, as outlined by this Court in the second Brown decision, allows for the flexibility and the delay provided in the decision by District Judge Harry J. Lemley.", "start": 539.422, "stop": 577.02, "duration": 37.6}, {"text": "In effect it provides for a transition from one era to another or from one set of standards to another.", "start": 577.02, "stop": 594.167, "duration": 17.15}, {"text": "Now I invite the Court's attention to this quotation “and if you go back to the Brown decision and study its terms, you will see that this Court with due regard for the almost inestimable value of the public schools to the American people, used every care that it could conceive to try to protect that system provided that the people who were trying to work in the public school system and the state officials had a duty also to preserve it in accordance with the Constitution of the United States and set about the task to try to carry out the Brown decision in good faith at every step of the way.", "start": 594.167, "stop": 640.889, "duration": 46.72}, {"text": "We all know as lawyers and the public knows it from its experience that the courts have had equitable principles that they have worked with over the centuries and the Court in the Brown case in a note refers to that fact, the decision of this Court in which that is set out.", "start": 640.889, "stop": 663.454, "duration": 22.56}, {"text": "And a court of equity does not ask people any time or any place to do things that are beyond their power, things that they cannot do.”", "start": 663.454, "stop": 675.941, "duration": 12.49}, {"text": "That ends the quotation and those are not our words, but those are the words of the honorable Solicitor General at the last hearing on this case.", "start": 675.941, "stop": 689.262, "duration": 13.32}, {"text": "No one has ever questioned the good faith of the Little Rock school board.", "start": 689.262, "stop": 695.223, "duration": 5.96}, {"text": "It has been admitted from time to time by counsel for NAACP by the honorable Solicitor General by every court before which this board has appeared, and is implicit in some of the comments made by the justices at this last hearing.", "start": 695.223, "stop": 717.662, "duration": 22.44}, {"text": "Again we find in the words of the honorable Solicitor General and I am sure that this Court in the decision in the Brown case in its implementation did not want in any way to loose the public school system in obtaining and enforcing this principle of constitutional law.", "start": 717.662, "stop": 738.365, "duration": 20.7}, {"text": "There is ample provision in the Brown case implementing the declaration about constitutional law for time if it is actually needed in good faith to try to carry out this constitutional principle.", "start": 738.365, "stop": 754.521, "duration": 16.16}, {"text": "It is all there and no court of equity in this country would fail to recognize those needs if they are properly brought to its attention and if the action is in good faith and everybody according to basic principles of equitable law has done everything within his power up to that point to accomplish the court's decree.", "start": 754.521, "stop": 779.701, "duration": 25.18}, {"text": "That is when an equity court comes in and acts to help out someone who has tried and done his level best in accordance with all the means at his command and then ask for some help or relief.", "start": 779.701, "stop": 796.155, "duration": 16.45}, {"text": "Again I state that is a quotation from the honorable Solicitor General made before this Court two weeks ago.", "start": 796.155, "stop": 806.394, "duration": 10.24}, {"text": "Now as that -- with that as a background or as a statement which of course we are willing to accept, Judge Lemley, who heard the decision -- who heard the evidence before he rendered his decision after a trial of some three days and after briefs had been submitted, made these statements.", "start": 806.394, "stop": 831.203, "duration": 24.81}, {"text": "Now if Your Honors please, Judge Lemley's decision in our opinion is so important.", "start": 831.203, "stop": 838.306, "duration": 7.1}, {"text": "It so well considered.", "start": 838.306, "stop": 840.399, "duration": 2.09}, {"text": "It's so effectively gives the background of the trials and tribulations of the school board in operating a public school system.", "start": 840.399, "stop": 853.671, "duration": 13.27}, {"text": "And the evidence is so clear in that case and he outlines it, although he takes some 19 pages to write his opinion, we feel so strongly that that should be carefully considered by every individual member of this Court that by quoting only short portions of it in our oral argument we trust that the Court will not believe that we slight any particular portion of it.", "start": 853.671, "stop": 887.48, "duration": 33.81}, {"text": "The full decision of Judge Lemley as well as the full decision of the Circuit Court of Appeals is in the pleadings that have already been filed heretofore before this Court.", "start": 887.48, "stop": 900.761, "duration": 13.28}, {"text": "Now in the light of the Solicitor General's remarks, let's look at some of the things that judge Lemley said in his decision.", "start": 900.761, "stop": 910.431, "duration": 9.67}, {"text": "As has been said, there can be no question that the board made a prompt and reasonable start toward compliance with the principles laid down in the Brown cases.", "start": 910.431, "stop": 922.737, "duration": 12.31}, {"text": "Thereafter, it put its plan into operation and has adhered to it in good faith in the face of great difficulties.", "start": 922.737, "stop": 930.533, "duration": 7.8}, {"text": "Now it has come here seeking relief only after it has been confronted with what is from an educational standpoint an intolerable situation and it does not ask for an abandonment of its plan nor does it attempt to obtain indefinite postponement.", "start": 930.533, "stop": 947.307, "duration": 16.77}, {"text": "It is simply requesting a practical delay and we are convinced that in seeking this delay the board is still acting in good faith, and upon the showing that has been made, we are satisfied that the board needs more time to carry out its plan in an effective manner, that to grant the instant petition is in the public interest and is consistent with good faith compliance at the earliest practicable day with the principles above mentioned.", "start": 947.307, "stop": 979.034, "duration": 31.73}, {"text": "In reaching this conclusion, we are not unmindful of the admonition of the Supreme Court that the vitality of those principles cannot be allowed to yield simply because of disagreement with it.", "start": 979.034, "stop": 991.419, "duration": 12.38}, {"text": "Here, however, as pointed out by the board in its final brief, the opposition to integration in Little Rock is more than a mere mental attitude.", "start": 991.419, "stop": 1001.377, "duration": 9.96}, {"text": "It has manifested itself in overt acts which have actually damaged educational standards and which will continue to do so if relief is not granted.", "start": 1001.377, "stop": 1014.103, "duration": 12.73}, {"text": "We have seen that the Supreme Court said in the second Brown decision that the transition from a formerly segregated school to a school free from compulsory segregation should be carried out in an effective manner and that such a transition is in the public interest.", "start": 1014.103, "stop": 1034.818, "duration": 20.72}, {"text": "In our estimation a transition which impairs or disrupts educational programs and standards and which will continue to do so is not in the public interest, but on the other hand inflicts irreparable harm upon all of the students concerned regardless of race.", "start": 1034.818, "stop": 1056.285, "duration": 21.47}, {"text": "Whereas here such a transition is being undertaken under the compulsive effects of a Federal Court order, a refusal to modify such an order so as to ameliorate the situation would in our opinion under the circumstances here present be inequitable if not arbitrary as well.", "start": 1056.285, "stop": 1081.535, "duration": 25.25}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could I ask you a few questions.", "start": 1081.535, "stop": 1082.878, "duration": 1.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, Mr. Justice.", "start": 1082.878, "stop": 1084.411, "duration": 1.53}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Taking the complete good faith in the school board and I for one certainly accept it without reservation, how can you, from the point of view of judging this case, divorce the action of the state, which you very frankly in your brief say was an action designed to frustrate the good faith of the action of the school board, how can you divorce that in judging the issues in this case from the position of the school board?", "start": 1084.411, "stop": 1117.368, "duration": 32.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't believe Mr. Justice Harlan that we are attempting to divorce that.", "start": 1117.368, "stop": 1123.206, "duration": 5.84}, {"text": "That is the primary problem that this school board has in carrying out its plan of integration or its plan of desegregation which I think is more accurate.", "start": 1123.206, "stop": 1138.347, "duration": 15.14}, {"text": "When it as an arm of the state government is ordered to do one thing by one court and by its employer so to speak, the State of Arkansas obviously is ordered to do something else.", "start": 1138.347, "stop": 1155.423, "duration": 17.08}, {"text": "We have not in any sense so far as I am aware attempted to divorce that.", "start": 1155.423, "stop": 1159.915, "duration": 4.49}, {"text": "We wish we could but we cannot.", "start": 1159.915, "stop": 1164.728, "duration": 4.81}, {"text": "It is implicit and inherent and intertwined in this particular problem.", "start": 1164.728, "stop": 1170.83, "duration": 6.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Am I right in inferring from the testimony, both of Mr. Upton and Mr. Blossom, that indeed the position of the school board derives from the fact that there was this intervention by state authority or this interruption of what was an incipient peaceful process which gave rise to the difficulties, which you just rehearsed, the state (Inaudible)", "start": 1170.83, "stop": 1196.879, "duration": 26.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, we certainly have been faced with that Mr. Justice Frankfurter and that --", "start": 1196.879, "stop": 1203.059, "duration": 6.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now may I ask you --", "start": 1203.059, "stop": 1204.467, "duration": 1.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that in incipiency maybe was not aware to everyone at the time, but it was a latent problem that exploded and which was not anticipated by the school board and I say by the people in Little Rock generally and I dare say by the courts themselves.", "start": 1204.467, "stop": 1229.506, "duration": 25.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the process which was interrupted by the intervention of the militia, of state action was as conceded by the school board and the Superintendent, a peaceful process underway, is that correct?", "start": 1229.506, "stop": 1247.58, "duration": 18.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir they thought it was peaceful up until just a few weeks before the actual opening of schools for the 1957-1958 School Year in Little Rock.", "start": 1247.58, "stop": 1257.403, "duration": 9.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now then, suppose everything you say is so and we're not suggesting, as I personally do not suggest you believe in the inevitability in human affairs, but suppose the same circumstances are put to the Court of Equity and the District Court at the end of two-and-a-half years, the same exercise of discretion in regard for external fact would justify a similar (Inaudible) or physically (Inaudible), would it not?", "start": 1257.403, "stop": 1288.809, "duration": 31.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well Mr. Justice Frankfurter let me state as concisely as I can our position.", "start": 1288.809, "stop": 1294.112, "duration": 5.3}, {"text": "I believe I stated when we were here before, that we do not intend to tell this Court that we believe that all of the problems wrapped up in this distressing situation can be solved in two-and-a-half years or six months or ten years or any other particular length of time.", "start": 1294.112, "stop": 1321.406, "duration": 27.29}, {"text": "We do earnestly believe this that without a reasonable period of calm, that solutions, proper lasting solutions have no chance of success.", "start": 1321.406, "stop": 1336.064, "duration": 14.66}, {"text": "Now whether that period be six months, whether it be two-and-a-half years, whether it be ten years, not being clairvoyant we have no way of knowing, but in the combined judgment of the school board, with the experience that it had, it felt that it did not have a good chance of arriving at solutions in less than that, that approximate period of time.", "start": 1336.064, "stop": 1363.953, "duration": 27.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Would you think it was proper, appropriate, relevant for this Court to consider the conditions that followed the formulation, judicial approval, practical implementation of the plan adopted by the board?", "start": 1363.953, "stop": 1385.187, "duration": 21.23}, {"text": "Is it relevant for this Court to consider the forces that interferes with the peaceful evolution of the plan which they with great care formulated, for which they received judicial approval, for which at one period the community as I read the evidence was on the whole, if not enthusiastic about, at least acquiescence in accordance with it?", "start": 1385.187, "stop": 1412.258, "duration": 27.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Your Honor, I believe this that from a practical standpoint as far the problem facing this school board, it makes no difference why this particular plan has failed to be accepted at this time.", "start": 1412.258, "stop": 1432.347, "duration": 20.09}, {"text": "As we set out in our brief, we gave the illustration of a trucker or a (Inaudible) being ordered by a court let's say, going from point A to point B and there is a bridge across a chasm, and he attempts to carry out his assignment, and he gets to the bridge and for reasons completely beyond his control the bridge is no longer there.", "start": 1432.347, "stop": 1462.269, "duration": 29.92}, {"text": "We feel that the school board would be in the position if this Court or any other court directed it to cross that chasm without a bridge that it would be saying, you go over the brink to your fate.", "start": 1462.269, "stop": 1476.663, "duration": 14.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I suggest --", "start": 1476.663, "stop": 1477.392, "duration": 0.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "And --", "start": 1477.392, "stop": 1478.305, "duration": 0.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I beg your pardon.", "start": 1478.305, "stop": 1479.571, "duration": 1.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I just was going to conclude Mr. Justice Frankfurter this thought, that to that (Inaudible) it makes no difference why the bridge is not there.", "start": 1479.571, "stop": 1489.062, "duration": 9.49}, {"text": "Now, it maybe a proper function of some judicial body or even an executive body to determine whether or not that destruction of the bridge was malicious or whether it was as a result of an act of God or whatnot, but to the man who has the problem right then of getting across the chasm, as this school board has the responsibility, its main responsibility of providing for proper educational system in the City of Little Rock, it makes no difference to it why the bridge was destroyed.", "start": 1489.062, "stop": 1528.668, "duration": 39.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I suggest two things Mr. Butler?", "start": 1528.668, "stop": 1531.11, "duration": 2.44}, {"text": "In the first place I think it's dangerous to argue or fair to analogize, that argued from physical factors of this world to psychological factors, but in the second place a Court of Equity would not be beyond its power to require that the bridge to restored?", "start": 1531.11, "stop": 1553.949, "duration": 22.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler, doesn't this argument that you're making now, more or less assume that this is a personal issue between the school board and these school children who seek admission whereas as a matter of fact the real issue before this Court is not just whether the school board is frustrating the rights of these children, but whether the acts of any agency of the State of Arkansas are preventing them from exercising their constitutional rights and whether it's a school broad or whether it's a governor, whether it's a legislature, whether it's the militia, whatever agency of the state government, if it did frustrate the rights of these children is a violation the Constitution, isn't that the issue that we have before us?", "start": 1553.949, "stop": 1612.186, "duration": 58.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well to answer the first part of question Mr. Chief Justice, it has been very heartening to the lawyers in this case, that the school board members have refrained at any time from dealing in personalities whether they be Negro children, whether they be the Governor, whether they be the President of the United States or any other person.", "start": 1612.186, "stop": 1636.752, "duration": 24.57}, {"text": "They have looked on their major responsibility as continuing an acceptable educational system within the City of Little Rock and they have refrained, although they have been taunted and prompted at times to deal in personalities, fortunately they have resisted that temptation insofar as I am personally aware.", "start": 1636.752, "stop": 1662.058, "duration": 25.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, but conceding absolute good faith to the board, is this Court not concerned with whether the state action of the state of Arkansas, whether that action emanated from the school board or from other authority, has frustrated the constitutional rights of these children", "start": 1662.058, "stop": 1687.124, "duration": 25.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well Mr. Chief Justice, this Court maybe concerned with a whole lot of things.", "start": 1687.124, "stop": 1692.436, "duration": 5.31}, {"text": "The thing that we are pleading for is and we have tried our best to keep it on this particular basis.", "start": 1692.436, "stop": 1700.819, "duration": 8.38}, {"text": "We feel very earnestly that the Little Rock school board is entitled to be heard before this tribunal as well as others, on its own record and for its own purposes.", "start": 1700.819, "stop": 1715.01, "duration": 14.19}, {"text": "Now we are not unmindful of course of the problems of a similar nature in other sections of the country and in other states, but we have done the best we could to try to keep out any foreign issues and to request the local court, the Court of Appeals and this Court to look at our problems in Little Rock.", "start": 1715.01, "stop": 1739.662, "duration": 24.65}, {"text": "We are not here to plead, because we are not familiar with situations in other states, and their particular problems, and it seems to us that, that is the very basic wisdom when the United States Supreme Court did abandon the doctrine of separate, but equal and change, that when it gave to the local district courts that power to determine the local problems as they might arise, that we are entitled as a school board of Little Rock to have our local judge on the evidence presented, determine that case for that particular case and no other.", "start": 1739.662, "stop": 1786.449, "duration": 46.79}, {"text": "Now, the results of that decision may by either side or both sides be pointed out for their own purposes in other areas of the country.", "start": 1786.449, "stop": 1799.291, "duration": 12.84}, {"text": "But we, and although it is not accurate to say we are not concerned about it, because every citizen of the United States is concerned about this problem, but it is not our obligation or duty to be unduly concerned about what precedent maybe set or what effect it may have in other sections of the country.", "start": 1799.291, "stop": 1824.041, "duration": 24.75}, {"text": "We have enough problems in Little Rock if we stick to this particular problem there.", "start": 1824.041, "stop": 1830.171, "duration": 6.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But Mr. Butler --", "start": 1830.171, "stop": 1831.242, "duration": 1.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Without giving undue consideration to what might happen somewhere else.", "start": 1831.242, "stop": 1835.198, "duration": 3.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, well just sticking to your own particular case, is it your position that if this Court recognizes that the school board has acted faithfully in this manner that it has no jurisdiction to relieve the distress of these children if other state action has deprived them of their constitutional rights?", "start": 1835.198, "stop": 1863.799, "duration": 28.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well Mr. Chief Justice I think that gets at one -- at the heart of this issue and I -- if I may suggest I get into that a little farther in my argument, if I may?", "start": 1863.799, "stop": 1873.804, "duration": 10.01}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, yes, take your own time, do it in your own way.", "start": 1873.804, "stop": 1877.166, "duration": 3.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "There is one thing that I would like – I'd like to answer a little further the grave question of Mr. Justice Frankfurter about wouldn't it be proper to construct the bridge and I thoroughly agree with that Your Honor, but I do think that in the construction of a bridge, it does take deliberate speed at least and one very eminent jurist on this Court some twelve years ago made this comment in an opinion.", "start": 1877.166, "stop": 1913.625, "duration": 36.46}, {"text": "“In any event mere speed is a test of justice, deliberate speed is.", "start": 1913.625, "stop": 1920.2, "duration": 6.58}, {"text": "Deliberate speed takes time but it is time well spent.”", "start": 1920.2, "stop": 1925.126, "duration": 4.93}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Assuming that, Mr. Butler assuming that the state authorities gave you unequivocal assurance that the school board will be backed up by the state authorities in implementing this plan, would the board still be asking for a go ahead?", "start": 1925.126, "stop": 1941.013, "duration": 15.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "If it were backed up by a state authority?", "start": 1941.013, "stop": 1942.769, "duration": 1.76}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, state or Federal authority?", "start": 1942.769, "stop": 1946.939, "duration": 4.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Oh –-", "start": 1946.939, "stop": 1947.373, "duration": 0.43}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "Will you be asking of delay?", "start": 1947.373, "stop": 1949.218, "duration": 1.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, I think not, if the various laws in the state and the various executives which have supervisory power including the general assembly of State of Arkansas had taken the position that some other states have taken in the north, New York and various other states, this school board wouldn't have any problem and there it would be no, no purpose or reason for it to ask for a delay.", "start": 1949.218, "stop": 1975.153, "duration": 25.93}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "So the essence --", "start": 1975.153, "stop": 1976.103, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I can't at this moment as history has unfolded itself in the last months anticipate that any such situation could be reversed and take place in the State of Arkansas at this time or for that matter any other South --", "start": 1976.103, "stop": 1995.318, "duration": 19.21}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "The essence of your position is that the school board finds itself in a position it does because of the break down of the enforcement activity --", "start": 1995.318, "stop": 2005.604, "duration": 10.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because --", "start": 2005.604, "stop": 2006.747, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- in Arkansas.", "start": 2006.747, "stop": 2008.082, "duration": 1.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Because Mr. Justice Harlan of various factors that are completely beyond its control, including the total opposition of the people and the state government of Arkansas.", "start": 2008.082, "stop": 2023.902, "duration": 15.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the opposition of the people as I read the testimony, which to me is very illuminated, the opposition of the people was engendered by action of officials, isn't that a fair statement?", "start": 2023.902, "stop": 2039.644, "duration": 15.74}, {"text": "I am not suggesting --", "start": 2039.644, "stop": 2040.916, "duration": 1.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is --", "start": 2040.916, "stop": 2040.997, "duration": 0.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I am not suggesting it wasn't – it wasn't an inflammable material there but -- but the ignition came not from the people rising up but from their incitement to action by officials, am I overstating the case?", "start": 2040.997, "stop": 2057.087, "duration": 16.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is such a matter of personal and individual opinion that I would prefer not to express my own on that point.", "start": 2057.087, "stop": 2064.987, "duration": 7.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well I thought that's what I read in Mr. Upton's testimony.", "start": 2064.987, "stop": 2069.165, "duration": 4.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible) trying to affect the program.", "start": 2069.165, "stop": 2080.193, "duration": 11.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well Mr. Justice Clark this board has tried to take the problems as they arose one at a time.", "start": 2080.193, "stop": 2088.786, "duration": 8.59}, {"text": "It has not made any particular plans for specific action or decisions within the next two-and-a-half years because it has not known whether it was going to have two-and-a-half years or not.", "start": 2088.786, "stop": 2106.407, "duration": 17.62}, {"text": "Now if that is determined then it does have tentative plans of things that it feels might help toward an ultimate and sound solution of these problems.", "start": 2106.407, "stop": 2120.892, "duration": 14.48}, {"text": "They are tentative and we try to take first things first and we think the first thing is for the Court to draft the time that Judge Lemley gave us feeling that you cannot reach sound conclusions in a state of chaos and hysteria.", "start": 2120.892, "stop": 2141.723, "duration": 20.83}, {"text": "And I dare say that if this board is given the two-and-a-half year delay that it would be wise although this is my personal opinion to let things kind of simmer down for at least a few weeks or few months before any further plans were actually promulgated, but that as properly as could be, solutions would be sought and attempts made to reconcile the differences that exist in this conflict.", "start": 2141.723, "stop": 2173.72, "duration": 32}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your position is that the school board promptly proceeded to carry out in good faith, it's (Inaudible) the decisions of this Court, it not only planned but it took action upon its plan.", "start": 2173.72, "stop": 2191.689, "duration": 17.97}, {"text": "Its purposes confirmed by judicial action were crushed in through forces outside of its own making or outside of its own control, and you want maneuvering time, you want time within which the school board independently considered acting on its own, as it were, can have a situation in which the former piece of (Inaudible)", "start": 2191.689, "stop": 2219.866, "duration": 28.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, that I think that states our position very clearly Mr. Justice Frankfurter, I do indeed.", "start": 2219.866, "stop": 2226.117, "duration": 6.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But then it's just watchful waiting?", "start": 2226.117, "stop": 2231.151, "duration": 5.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, we don't look at it that way Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 2231.151, "stop": 2234.843, "duration": 3.69}, {"text": "We don't feel that it is.", "start": 2234.843, "stop": 2236.24, "duration": 1.4}, {"text": "We have the hope that solutions can be reached if given an opportunity in an atmosphere that is conducive to reaching solutions.", "start": 2236.24, "stop": 2253.665, "duration": 17.43}, {"text": "Now I say again that we do not know that that can be done in any stated length of time.", "start": 2253.665, "stop": 2263.026, "duration": 9.36}, {"text": "As a matter of fact, the first petition which was filed before Judge Lemley, requested an indefinite period to be determined by the court on the evidence as to how long.", "start": 2263.026, "stop": 2277.311, "duration": 14.29}, {"text": "And Judge Lemley made a statement to all parties concerned directing that the school board members collectively and individually be present in which he said the primary responsibility for the exercise of judgment is on the school board.", "start": 2277.311, "stop": 2295.284, "duration": 17.97}, {"text": "You determine and file an amendment to your petition as to whether or not you believe such and such a length of time should prevail or whether you want to change your plan in some manner and I think his reasoning on that was perfectly sound because the court itself has said that the primary responsibility is on the school boards.", "start": 2295.284, "stop": 2321.927, "duration": 26.64}, {"text": "Now we agree with that and we feel that the first exercise of judgment should be on the school board itself and then it should be under the supervision of the District Court to determine whether the school board acted in good faith and used good judgment, and if not then based on the evidence he could say so.", "start": 2321.927, "stop": 2345.713, "duration": 23.79}, {"text": "And Judge Lemley, using that judicial discretion, directed to him by this Court, did so and found that the school board was justified in asking for that delay.", "start": 2345.713, "stop": 2361.774, "duration": 16.06}, {"text": "The point I am making is simply this that the school board admitted from the very beginning that it was -- it could not foretell the future well enough to say that any exact period of time was necessary to solve the problem, but judgments had to be made and used and it used its judgment in suggesting to Judge Lemley this period of time which he apparently felt was necessary to carry out or have any possibility of a solution of these problems.", "start": 2361.774, "stop": 2398.997, "duration": 37.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Assume the court -- assume your school board at the end of the two years and a half felt that the climate of opinion was the same then as it is now, what would it be prepared to do?", "start": 2398.997, "stop": 2411.896, "duration": 12.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We think Mr. Chief Justice that, that is a matter for the local District Court to determine in his judicial discretion considering all the factors and all the evidence available and presented to him at that particular time.", "start": 2411.896, "stop": 2429.703, "duration": 17.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well I know, but if we may have a hypothetical case, you put some to us and you present this two-and-a-half year extension to us without any representation on the part of the board as to what it proposes to do in the meantime.", "start": 2429.703, "stop": 2447.259, "duration": 17.56}, {"text": "Now let us assume the end of the two years and a half, if you prevail, that the climate of opinion is as it is now, would you be in asking for another two years and a half or would you have a program to bring about desegregation?", "start": 2447.259, "stop": 2464.468, "duration": 17.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, again Mr. Chief Justice, I don't think it's entirely accurate to say that this school board has not -- does not have any plans to do anything.", "start": 2464.468, "stop": 2474.098, "duration": 9.63}, {"text": "In the first place one of the things that we have felt most strongly was that a reasonable period of time, whatever that maybe, would be for the purpose of testing certain laws, state laws which have not even been tested by the State Supreme Court.", "start": 2474.098, "stop": 2493.925, "duration": 19.83}, {"text": "Now in the opinion of many lawyers, the State Supreme Court of Arkansas will possibly hold unconstitutional many of the acts which the legislature has passed, and perhaps in its judgment fall in line with the United State Supreme Court in varying degrees and recognize the superiority of this Court in determining federal questions.", "start": 2493.925, "stop": 2525.551, "duration": 31.63}, {"text": "Now, in such an event, in such an event the people of the State of Arkansas and in the other states if I may suggest, will then have heard from judges that are close to them, that are closer to their own local scenes and have a better understanding of what their responsibilities as citizens may be.", "start": 2525.551, "stop": 2551.429, "duration": 25.88}, {"text": "Now that is one of the primary factors that we -- that the school board gave consideration to and some of those cases, some of those statutes are right now under consideration and moving toward our State Supreme Court and we think that such a period of time, through the normal processes in our state and I'm sure its true in other states takes about a year, year-and-a-half, two years to get that sort of question decided by the various State Supreme Courts.", "start": 2551.429, "stop": 2585.775, "duration": 34.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well granted that is true, and the legislature in the meantime passes other laws to frustrate the rights of these individuals, would you want to wait for that too?", "start": 2585.775, "stop": 2597.029, "duration": 11.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well that's --", "start": 2597.029, "stop": 2597.446, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could be determined by the courts?", "start": 2597.446, "stop": 2599.485, "duration": 2.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We don't know Mr. Chief Justice. That's one of the things we would have to determine if and when that time came.", "start": 2599.485, "stop": 2612.262, "duration": 12.78}, {"text": "We're very frank to admit, we don't have all of the answers, but we hope that whether, and after a decision by this Court in this particular case, that it will give us at least a framework which we earnestly feel could be done within the decision and opinion of the Brown decision to work out some of our problems.", "start": 2612.262, "stop": 2635.941, "duration": 23.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "You asked (Inaudible) you mentioned the fact that you have laws, new laws aren't -- the fact they are not laws you know --", "start": 2635.941, "stop": 2644.002, "duration": 8.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now, one of the laws that I referred to is an establishment of a so called sovereignty commission which -- that law was passed in 1957.", "start": 2644.002, "stop": 2654.943, "duration": 10.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "I mean this package that you mention in your brief?", "start": 2654.943, "stop": 2657.126, "duration": 2.18}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "The package of laws that we mentioned in our brief was a result of a special session of our General Assembly this past month.", "start": 2657.126, "stop": 2666.472, "duration": 9.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "That was after the (Inaudible)", "start": 2666.472, "stop": 2668.734, "duration": 2.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 2668.734, "stop": 2670.025, "duration": 1.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you intend to set those --", "start": 2670.025, "stop": 2671.502, "duration": 1.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It was about coincident with the time we were appearing here before.", "start": 2671.502, "stop": 2676.894, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "As matter of a fact I believe the legislature was in session two weeks ago to the best of my recollection.", "start": 2676.894, "stop": 2681.444, "duration": 4.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that was after Judge Lemley's orders.", "start": 2681.444, "stop": 2684.518, "duration": 3.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir that was after Judge Lemley's orders, yes.", "start": 2684.518, "stop": 2686.708, "duration": 2.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "But the time that you were considering the two-and-a-half years, you were thinking of laws then presently on the books.", "start": 2686.708, "stop": 2697.049, "duration": 10.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mainly, yes.", "start": 2697.049, "stop": 2699.277, "duration": 2.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is the Sovereignty Law and it's (Inaudible)", "start": 2699.277, "stop": 2703.124, "duration": 3.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Briefly Mr. Justice Black the Sovereignty Law established a Sovereignty Commission to pass on certain things among which are problems involving this issue of desegregation of schools, as well as other types of conflicts that may arise between the races, the white and the Negro races.", "start": 2703.124, "stop": 2734.495, "duration": 31.37}, {"text": "That law incidentally was -- a three-judge federal court was called to pass upon the constitutionality of it.", "start": 2734.495, "stop": 2743.004, "duration": 8.51}, {"text": "That Court deferred its action until it was passed upon by the State Supreme Court.", "start": 2743.004, "stop": 2750.902, "duration": 7.9}, {"text": "It has now been held constitutional by the local Chancery Court, which is not an unusual situation.", "start": 2750.902, "stop": 2758.598, "duration": 7.7}, {"text": "I mean out lower courts in our state ordinarily uphold the constitutionality of acts passed by the General Assembly and leave that function to be -- to the State Supreme Court, the appellate court where they think it belongs, and it is now in the process of being appealed to the Supreme Court.", "start": 2758.598, "stop": 2778.199, "duration": 19.6}, {"text": "Now that is only one example of the type of law that we have in mind.", "start": 2778.199, "stop": 2784.029, "duration": 5.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Does that law setup a plan to abide by the -- this Court's decree?", "start": 2784.029, "stop": 2795.089, "duration": 11.06}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't recall the specific wording of it.", "start": 2795.089, "stop": 2797.441, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "I don't think there is any particular reference, and I don't think the specific purpose was that limited Mr. Justice Black.", "start": 2797.441, "stop": 2806.073, "duration": 8.63}, {"text": "It's --", "start": 2806.073, "stop": 2806.435, "duration": 0.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did it have that purpose?", "start": 2806.435, "stop": 2808.886, "duration": 2.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's a commission that is setup to deal with and at least make recommendations and determinations on various problems which have been engendered by this particular conflict.", "start": 2808.886, "stop": 2821.257, "duration": 12.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Does it setup a plan at all at any time?", "start": 2821.257, "stop": 2824.026, "duration": 2.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not for schools as such.", "start": 2824.026, "stop": 2825.231, "duration": 1.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "By this Court's decree.", "start": 2825.231, "stop": 2827.084, "duration": 1.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not for schools as such as I recall, no sir.", "start": 2827.084, "stop": 2830.668, "duration": 3.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is that with effect to statute laws have, this package you spoke of, on the action of the Board, would they have power under the state law to do anything?", "start": 2830.668, "stop": 2841.457, "duration": 10.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well I have those acts.", "start": 2841.457, "stop": 2843.598, "duration": 2.14}, {"text": "They have been passed.", "start": 2843.598, "stop": 2845.431, "duration": 1.83}, {"text": "There were six acts that were sponsored by the present state administration.", "start": 2845.431, "stop": 2851.122, "duration": 5.69}, {"text": "Those were all passed.", "start": 2851.122, "stop": 2852.339, "duration": 1.22}, {"text": "There were some other suggested, some of which as I recall were defeated, others were passed primarily at the instance of the State Attorney General.", "start": 2852.339, "stop": 2862.818, "duration": 10.48}, {"text": "The statutes passed by the General Assembly sponsored by the government deal exclusively with educational problems, some of the others deal with other phases of the larger problem.", "start": 2862.818, "stop": 2877.934, "duration": 15.12}, {"text": "Now the present situation if I'm correctly informed as of this moment is that those laws have been passed by the General Assembly, but have not been signed by the government, and whether they will be or not, we have no way of knowing.", "start": 2877.934, "stop": 2897.24, "duration": 19.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Does any one of them provide for obedience to the Court's decree?", "start": 2897.24, "stop": 2903.934, "duration": 6.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not in that language.", "start": 2903.934, "stop": 2905.737, "duration": 1.8}, {"text": "[Laughter]", "start": 2905.737, "stop": 2907.882, "duration": 2.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Does it provide it in substance?", "start": 2907.882, "stop": 2913.546, "duration": 5.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, not one of those laws.", "start": 2913.546, "stop": 2918.599, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "We made mention I believe of the pupil assignment law of Arkansas and that statute specifically provides that in the determination of various factors, some ten or a dozen factors that school boards may properly consider in admitting particular students to school.", "start": 2918.599, "stop": 2940.671, "duration": 22.07}, {"text": "The provision in that statute obviously took into consideration the decisions of this Court and stated that race would not be a factor in determining the admission or non-admission of any student in any school in Arkansas.", "start": 2940.671, "stop": 2959.614, "duration": 18.94}, {"text": "Now that particular statute passed some two years ago, a year-and-a-half ago, did very definitely take into consideration the Brown decisions.", "start": 2959.614, "stop": 2973.386, "duration": 13.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Since we're taking with actuality, is it not fair to state, or rather I got the impression from your argument last time and partly today, that there is a body of enactment in Arkansas, which helped to create a state of public opinion that is hostile to carrying out the purpose of your original plan of the school board by way of implementing this Court's decision in desegregation -- for desegregation, and that your argument was that you do not know whether or not when those laws came under challenge before your local court, your state courts, they maybe declared unconstitutional and thereby affect public opinion in support of the board's plan rather in opposition to it, isn't that, wasn't part of your argument?", "start": 2973.386, "stop": 3029.741, "duration": 56.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well it was certainly an accurate statement that I intended to make that we have no way of knowing what our Supreme Court is going to say in any particular situation, but we have a good deal of confidence in the ability and integrity of our state Supreme Court and it will be surprising to many lawyers in Arkansas if all of those acts of the legislature are held to be constitutional by our Supreme Court.", "start": 3029.741, "stop": 3057.473, "duration": 27.73}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And by that very invalidation by your Supreme Court public opinion which is a fact to which you constantly appeal maybe seriously affected in favor of the original plan of the board or at least in favor of --", "start": 3057.473, "stop": 3070.226, "duration": 12.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It could --", "start": 3070.226, "stop": 3071.055, "duration": 0.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- obedience to this Court's decree.", "start": 3071.055, "stop": 3072.95, "duration": 1.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, we do think so.", "start": 3072.95, "stop": 3074.807, "duration": 1.86}, {"text": "We do indeed.", "start": 3074.807, "stop": 3077.252, "duration": 2.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "I was just going to say Mr. Butler to put this thing in the, in perspective, isn't it a fact that the State of Arkansas passed a constitutional amendment in defiance of the particular decision that that this Court granted, Brown versus Board of Education and that it dedicated the state to opposition by every available method the “unconstitutional decision of Brown versus Board of Education.”", "start": 3077.252, "stop": 3114.758, "duration": 37.51}, {"text": "That's from your Constitution now, isn't it?", "start": 3114.758, "stop": 3116.857, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It is certainly true Mr. Chief Justice that the State of Arkansas, the electors of that state by an overwhelming majority voted such a constitutional amendment to which you have referred in which they stated that every constitutional method should be examined and pursued and put into effect to avoid the mixing of the races in the public school systems in Arkansas, that is correct.", "start": 3116.857, "stop": 3155.797, "duration": 38.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well as I understood your brief here it commands the general assembly to oppose by every constitutional method the “unconstitutional decision of Brown versus Board of Education” that's in your Constitution, isn't it?", "start": 3155.797, "stop": 3170.663, "duration": 14.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "That is in that amendment yes sir.", "start": 3170.663, "stop": 3173.258, "duration": 2.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "In that language?", "start": 3173.258, "stop": 3174.083, "duration": 0.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "In that language.", "start": 3174.083, "stop": 3175.052, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Mr. Butler as I recall your argument last time, it's not the position of the board that the decisions in the Brown cases were unconstitutional.", "start": 3175.052, "stop": 3190.205, "duration": 15.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, Mr. Justice Brennan that has never been our position.", "start": 3190.205, "stop": 3193.6, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "We -- the school board from the very beginning and its attorneys have gone on the presumption, on the conclusion not just a presumption that the decision in the Brown cases was the law that must be followed and it was because of that or because of those decisions that the school board formulated this plan of desegregation and I think it is fair --", "start": 3193.6, "stop": 3226.824, "duration": 33.22}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's what as I understood it and that is --", "start": 3226.824, "stop": 3228.673, "duration": 1.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "And that is and that if you please sir is still the position of this school board.", "start": 3228.673, "stop": 3234.805, "duration": 6.13}, {"text": "Now I think it's fair to that point however to state that the school board and a vast majority of the people in the immediate locality of Little Rock are fundamentally, socially opposed to segregation of the races in the public schools.", "start": 3234.805, "stop": 3254.077, "duration": 19.27}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well I agree --", "start": 3254.077, "stop": 3254.444, "duration": 0.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "But in spite of that feeling, the school board formulated this plan in trying to carry on a school system and at the same time following the law, abiding by the law.", "start": 3254.444, "stop": 3270.159, "duration": 15.72}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "That leads me to my second question.", "start": 3270.159, "stop": 3272.321, "duration": 2.16}, {"text": "I know that you are familiar with Clause 3 of Article 6 of the Federal Constitution which requires every state legislator and every state official executive or judicial to take an oath when he enters upon his service to support the Federal Constitution, I think the actual language is to support this Constitution, you are familiar with that?", "start": 3272.321, "stop": 3303.48, "duration": 31.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, I am familiar with that.", "start": 3303.48, "stop": 3305.148, "duration": 1.67}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well that then brings me to this question since as I understand your answers and your colloquy particularly with Mr. Justice Harlan and Mr. Justice Frankfurter, that in large part the situation which prompted your petition to the District Court was a situation brought on by the active or by actions, affirmative actions of state legislature and its governor, I think, I think your brief also suggest something, actions on the part of your state judiciary, not on the side of enforcement of the constitution but opposed indeed in every way that the state can try to that enforcement.", "start": 3305.148, "stop": 3362.77, "duration": 57.62}, {"text": "Just how was this Court in a position to allow, or sanction, or approve a delay sought on the ground that the responsible state officials rather than be on the side of enforcement of these constitutional rights, have taken actions to frustrate their enforcement?", "start": 3362.77, "stop": 3392.268, "duration": 29.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well Mr. Justice Brennan I have that later on in my argument, but since you have brought it up now, let's see if we can dispose of it which in effect I was going to conclude with, but in view of your question I think we might as well answer it right now and that's simply this as we see it.", "start": 3392.268, "stop": 3416.695, "duration": 24.43}, {"text": "We have described here a situation where the school board which is a creature of the state, it's an arm of the state government, is placed between the millstones as Justice Sanborn of the Eighth Circuit said “between the upper and the nether millstone,” in a conflict between the state and federal government and the – and all of the agencies of each.", "start": 3416.695, "stop": 3444.601, "duration": 27.91}, {"text": "And it seems to us that we have pointed out the absurdity of the premise that a school district should keep the peace.", "start": 3444.601, "stop": 3452.563, "duration": 7.96}, {"text": "Now I have something to say about that when I get back on the principle argument, but here is what we are suggesting and which will be borne out by the balance of our argument, that the problem is not yet been grasped by Attorney General's office or the Solicitor General, and by the Eighth Circuit of appeals in a situation of this kind.", "start": 3452.563, "stop": 3479.811, "duration": 27.25}, {"text": "And we think that a plan of desegregation which has the planning along with it for the support of that plan in an effective manner is something that can be done by the agencies which are setup for those purposes by the federal and state the governments but certainly not by there school board.", "start": 3479.811, "stop": 3509.213, "duration": 29.4}, {"text": "Now some plan it seems to us adequate enforcement must come forward if you are going to have a conflict that runs head-on so to speak between your federal and your state governments.", "start": 3509.213, "stop": 3527.16, "duration": 17.95}, {"text": "Now, at that point, that is again the reason that we are asking for additional time for those conflicts which are completely beyond the realm of this school board to solve and be given an opportunity to be solved by the two sovereignties involved.", "start": 3527.16, "stop": 3555.498, "duration": 28.34}, {"text": "Now we think --", "start": 3555.498, "stop": 3556.543, "duration": 1.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible) federal government have federal legislation or --", "start": 3556.543, "stop": 3563.174, "duration": 6.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's one answer yes, and that has been seriously propounded by students of this problem that that the Congress should act in this field and that perhaps sometime it will.", "start": 3563.174, "stop": 3577.267, "duration": 14.09}, {"text": "It has struggled with the problem but to my knowledge it has not passed any legislation involving it.", "start": 3577.267, "stop": 3588.115, "duration": 10.85}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well of course the very section that I have referenced, referred to before, Section 3 of Article 6 puts the same obligation upon federal officers and Congressmen and is put upon state legislators and state officials, the obligation by oath to support this Constitution.", "start": 3588.115, "stop": 3614.116, "duration": 26}, {"text": "And what you're talking about I gather is that it is a default on the part of state officials and we ought to expect, or you ought to be able to except is that an assistance of the federal government?", "start": 3614.116, "stop": 3626.323, "duration": 12.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Mr. Justice Brennan there may have been times, and I'm no student of the history of the Supreme Court in its relationship with the legislative branch of this government, but at least to my limited knowledge, I don't recall anytime when the Congress even after a determination of the law by this Court has ever really felt compelled to pass any particular legislation because of a particular decision.", "start": 3626.323, "stop": 3658.606, "duration": 32.28}, {"text": "Now, there have been many instances I believe both in the federal government and in that state, where a certain Court decisions have prompted the legislative bodies of the national government or the state government to pass laws which would circumvent that particular court decision.", "start": 3658.606, "stop": 3679.651, "duration": 21.04}, {"text": "At least that has happened in our state many times, where the court did not express the will of the people as determined by the legislative body and I think that probably history will bear that out insofar as the National Congress is concerned.", "start": 3679.651, "stop": 3699.526, "duration": 19.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did the board ask the Congress to take any action?", "start": 3699.526, "stop": 3702.444, "duration": 2.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 3702.444, "stop": 3703.098, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did the board ask the Congress to take any action?", "start": 3703.098, "stop": 3705.575, "duration": 2.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "The Little Rock school board, no sir it has not.", "start": 3705.575, "stop": 3710.074, "duration": 4.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Another opinion, amicus brief which your Attorney General filed in 1955 and he suggested that, and I thought perhaps the board might have taken it up --", "start": 3710.074, "stop": 3718.388, "duration": 8.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir it -- to the best of my knowledge at least there has never been any suggestion formally made certainly on the part of this school board to request Congress to pass any law one way or the other.", "start": 3718.388, "stop": 3731.293, "duration": 12.91}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "Suppose that we don't follow and disagree with your argument in the affirmative Court of Appeals, what is the -- what action does the school board take then?", "start": 3731.293, "stop": 3742.742, "duration": 11.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think the action of the school board at that point, if we may project our thinking for a few moments to that period of time, would simply be to sit back and wait, for this reason.", "start": 3742.742, "stop": 3755.658, "duration": 12.92}, {"text": "There are some of the laws that have been passed by this General Assembly of the State of Arkansas recently, and which if signed by the Governor for all practical purposes insofar as desegregated schools are concerned within the district have been taken away from the authority of the school board and put under the direct control of the Governor.", "start": 3755.658, "stop": 3783.42, "duration": 27.76}, {"text": "So, the school board would have to wait to see what the Governor did because certainly the legislative assembly in the State of Arkansas has the ultimate control of the operation of the school system, that has been held by our Court many times, and this school board would be in a further untenable position of not having the power as we see it, even to proceed to the extent that it has it the past.", "start": 3783.42, "stop": 3822.166, "duration": 38.75}, {"text": "It would then if Your Honor please --", "start": 3822.166, "stop": 3824.574, "duration": 2.41}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Had that statute become law, the one that --", "start": 3824.574, "stop": 3826.473, "duration": 1.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, it has not, it's been passed by the General Assembly and may and will become law, all of those whichever ones are signed by the Chief Executive.", "start": 3826.473, "stop": 3838.638, "duration": 12.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler before you get to another point there, did I understand you are correctly to say a few moments ago that the majority of the people of Little Rock were opposed to segregation of the races in the schools?", "start": 3838.638, "stop": 3854.116, "duration": 15.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "If we can use a little hindsight I certainly think that's true, yes sir.", "start": 3854.116, "stop": 3857.237, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes well I just wanted to --", "start": 3857.237, "stop": 3859.549, "duration": 2.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, I don't think there is any question about there in looking back on it.", "start": 3859.549, "stop": 3863.036, "duration": 3.49}, {"text": "Now this school board said at the very beginning when it formulated this plan and did its best over a period of at least a year to explain to all responsible groups within that area, its plan it felt that it had let's say public sufferance at least if not active support.", "start": 3863.036, "stop": 3885.776, "duration": 22.74}, {"text": "The board never did feel that it had the active support or integration from any majority of the people of the community.", "start": 3885.776, "stop": 3895.968, "duration": 10.19}, {"text": "It felt and it did -- felt it was its duty and it did try to lead the thinking along that line, so that it could both carry out its function in operating an educational system and abide by the law, the federal law of this government.", "start": 3895.968, "stop": 3914.99, "duration": 19.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well Mr. Butler I think you -- we still misunderstand each other.", "start": 3914.99, "stop": 3920.378, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "My question to you was did I understand you correctly to say a few moments ago that a majority of the people of Little Rock are opposed to segregation of the races in the schools?", "start": 3920.378, "stop": 3939.283, "duration": 18.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, they are opposed to desegregation, there are opposed to integration.", "start": 3939.283, "stop": 3944.172, "duration": 4.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "I asked you that, you said yes that's correct but I wanted to be sure --", "start": 3944.172, "stop": 3946.746, "duration": 2.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I'm sorry sir --", "start": 3946.746, "stop": 3949.346, "duration": 2.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- and I think your self segregation opposed to segregation about --", "start": 3949.346, "stop": 3953.264, "duration": 3.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "There are opposed to integration.", "start": 3953.264, "stop": 3954.984, "duration": 1.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Integration yes.", "start": 3954.984, "stop": 3956.014, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 3956.014, "stop": 3957.103, "duration": 1.09}, {"text": "They are opposed to --", "start": 3957.103, "stop": 3957.779, "duration": 0.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "I just wanted you to tell you.", "start": 3957.779, "stop": 3959.89, "duration": 2.11}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think I used the term desegregation.", "start": 3959.89, "stop": 3963.017, "duration": 3.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler when you said the --", "start": 3963.017, "stop": 3964.642, "duration": 1.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "I just wanted to clear it up.", "start": 3964.642, "stop": 3965.761, "duration": 1.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 3965.761, "stop": 3965.948, "duration": 0.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's perfectly all right.", "start": 3965.948, "stop": 3966.354, "duration": 0.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "When you said the people of Little Rock were, what was your word, quiescent or acquiescent in what the school board did in the beginning?", "start": 3966.354, "stop": 3976.689, "duration": 10.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "At sufferance --", "start": 3976.689, "stop": 3977.638, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "At sufferance, they were not active supporters of the law you said, that was the phrase you used.", "start": 3977.638, "stop": 3984.739, "duration": 7.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "They were not active supporters Mr. Justice Frankfurter in anything that would lead to integration of the public school systems.", "start": 3984.739, "stop": 3995.605, "duration": 10.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "But there was a what --", "start": 3995.605, "stop": 3998.393, "duration": 2.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "There was a conclusion back in 1956 by the Little Rock school board, that this plan of desegregation was acceptable because it was the only plan that could be acceptable to that community.", "start": 3998.393, "stop": 4027.102, "duration": 28.71}, {"text": "It was not supportive by the people there.", "start": 4027.102, "stop": 4032.069, "duration": 4.97}, {"text": "It was more in our opinion as simply for the time being accepted as a possible solution and an adequate solution of a very serious problem.", "start": 4032.069, "stop": 4044.768, "duration": 12.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I suggest that on the whole realty of any law actively supported by the mass appeal, and the situation that is described in the evidence both by Mr. Upton and Superintendent Blossom, I think it's a fair description of what takes place when any new law is changed to which there is opposition, namely that the mass of people on the whole reflect or at least go along with what their leaders propose and urge, and that was as I read the testimony, you can correct me if I'm wrong, that the way I read the testimony of Mr. Upton and then of Blossom, as between the times that the board planned, it was confirmed by the Court and the later changes in September, what 1957?", "start": 4044.768, "stop": 4095.563, "duration": 50.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 4095.563, "stop": 4098.327, "duration": 2.76}, {"text": "I'm afraid, in all candor, Mr. Justice Frankfurter I will have to unqualifiedly agree with you, when you say that you feel that laws are not ordinarily acceptable to the people when they came --", "start": 4098.327, "stop": 4112.648, "duration": 14.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "I didn't say that, I said actively supporting --", "start": 4112.648, "stop": 4115.325, "duration": 2.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Actively supporting --", "start": 4115.325, "stop": 4115.997, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's a very different thing.", "start": 4115.997, "stop": 4117.38, "duration": 1.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, it comes to my mind an illustration such as this, when the Eighteen Amendment was passed and Volstead Act followed, it had in my opinion the active support of a majority of the people of the United States.", "start": 4117.38, "stop": 4134.569, "duration": 17.19}, {"text": "That change and they voted it out a constitutional amendment to that and repel of that Act.", "start": 4134.569, "stop": 4141.56, "duration": 6.99}, {"text": "Now to me that is a good example of the Congress following the majority of the thinking of the people in the United States and it seems to me that, that is generally the way most laws are passed if they are to be supported or even tolerated by a majority -- by the populace in general.", "start": 4141.56, "stop": 4171.185, "duration": 29.63}, {"text": "Now that's just a passing observation that I have but I --", "start": 4171.185, "stop": 4175.813, "duration": 4.63}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "You lived through --", "start": 4175.813, "stop": 4178.318, "duration": 2.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir I'm 48 years old and I have lived through most of that.", "start": 4178.318, "stop": 4183.89, "duration": 5.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler --", "start": 4183.89, "stop": 4184.649, "duration": 0.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Has it made the difference as it does here?", "start": 4184.649, "stop": 4188.024, "duration": 3.38}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It did, I'm sure it did.", "start": 4188.024, "stop": 4188.553, "duration": 0.53}, {"text": "I'm sure that the Eighteen Amendment and the Volstead Act were supported to varying degrees throughout this country, the little history I've read on it so indicates.", "start": 4188.553, "stop": 4200.045, "duration": 11.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Are you familiar with the progress if any of desegregation in other districts of Arkansas, other school districts?", "start": 4200.045, "stop": 4207.564, "duration": 7.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Only to this extent Mr. Justice Clark, that here is a desegregation program that has been going on successfully in the North Western part of our state at the site of our state university.", "start": 4207.564, "stop": 4223.289, "duration": 15.72}, {"text": "That is Fayetteville, Arkansas, it's in Washington County.", "start": 4223.289, "stop": 4228.773, "duration": 5.48}, {"text": "I say successfully, so far as I am informed there has been no particular problem or strife about it, and the people in that community several years ago accepted desegregation in their public schools.", "start": 4228.773, "stop": 4244.369, "duration": 15.6}, {"text": "Now in addition to that for many years there has been opportunity for Negro students on a graduate level at our state university, we've had some very fine graduate lawyers come out of our law school there and other graduate schools, not limited to the law school.", "start": 4244.369, "stop": 4264.366, "duration": 20}, {"text": "So I would say as a conclusion that in several communities in Arkansas, desegregation in the public school system has been effective and without turmoil.", "start": 4264.366, "stop": 4282.749, "duration": 18.38}, {"text": "Now if we may get back for a few moments to Judge Lemley?", "start": 4282.749, "stop": 4290.146, "duration": 7.4}, {"text": "He found of course that and as far as he could foretell the future, that these problems and obstacles before the school board were of such a nature that it was likely to require again for this school year the use of troops in order to protect life and property.", "start": 4290.146, "stop": 4315.791, "duration": 25.65}, {"text": "Now, at our previous hearing one of the justices aptly observed I should say as a consequence of those conditions educational results follows.", "start": 4315.791, "stop": 4328.521, "duration": 12.73}, {"text": "You can't teach if you are going to have troops in the classroom.", "start": 4328.521, "stop": 4333.233, "duration": 4.71}, {"text": "If that conclusion is correct, and that is certainly the opinion of the Little Rock school board, then the question which this Court must answer for the Little Rock school board in this particular case is this, is it better to defer certain intangible constitutional rights of a few students constituting less than 1% of the total enrollment of a school or to insist upon the immediate fulfillment of those rights even if it destroys the full educational opportunities of 2,000 students in that particular school to say nothing of some total 21,000 in the entire school system.", "start": 4333.233, "stop": 4379.744, "duration": 46.51}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "How many Negro children are there in Little Rock?", "start": 4379.744, "stop": 4387.384, "duration": 7.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "To best of my recollection it's about -- there are 21,000 students white and colored and I believe the ratio is about 60% or 65% white 35% to 40% colored.", "start": 4387.384, "stop": 4407.633, "duration": 20.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Then why do you say this only affects less than 1% of the pupils of that district?", "start": 4407.633, "stop": 4415.25, "duration": 7.62}, {"text": "Aren't the rights of all the children in that district involved here?", "start": 4415.25, "stop": 4418.801, "duration": 3.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm saying that the immediate enforcement of the rights at this particular time affects only seven Negro students, that the immediate insistence, the insistence of immediate fulfillment for them, because the plan did not contemplate anymore than that for this particular period.", "start": 4418.801, "stop": 4442.105, "duration": 23.3}, {"text": "Now the plan did if things had gone smoothly, they had intended to take in more to that school or possibly to other schools, but the plan itself Mr. Chief Justice was on the basis of starting at the high school level first in the three grades in the high school level.", "start": 4442.105, "stop": 4463.031, "duration": 20.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But if we stopped that program we are denying this same right to approximately 40% of the children of your community.", "start": 4463.031, "stop": 4472.011, "duration": 8.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We take the position that you are not denying the right, you are delaying the fulfillment of a constitutional right which you have said they have, but not the denial of the right as a class action which this is.", "start": 4472.011, "stop": 4488.464, "duration": 16.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well this decision, the Brown decision was in 1954, this is 1958, two years and a half will bring it up almost to 1961.", "start": 4488.464, "stop": 4504.618, "duration": 16.15}, {"text": "Now, if all those children are denied the right to go to the elementary schools aren't they being denied permanently and finally of a right to get equal protection under the laws during their primary grade years.", "start": 4504.618, "stop": 4524.109, "duration": 19.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "They would be deprived of the personal fulfillment of what we consider an intangible right expressed by this Court.", "start": 4524.109, "stop": 4534.386, "duration": 10.28}, {"text": "They would not be deprived --", "start": 4534.386, "stop": 4535.732, "duration": 1.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well then by that you don't accept the decision of the Supreme Court as to whether it's a violation of the constitution.", "start": 4535.732, "stop": 4544.775, "duration": 9.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, we do except it Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 4544.775, "stop": 4547.273, "duration": 2.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why do you call it intangible rights?", "start": 4547.273, "stop": 4551.425, "duration": 4.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well I was distinguishing that as against --", "start": 4551.425, "stop": 4554.892, "duration": 3.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "If somebody was to deprive you of life, liberty or property would that be an intangible right?", "start": 4554.892, "stop": 4560.426, "duration": 5.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I didn't have in mind that sense.", "start": 4560.426, "stop": 4562.376, "duration": 1.95}, {"text": "The point I'm making is simply this, that you have a conflict between two balances of equity so to speak and those balances must be weighed and as counsel for NAACP and others all of us recognize in this case and in all cases of a similar nature, Judge Lemley certainly recognized it, that there must be a balancing of equities.", "start": 4562.376, "stop": 4593.259, "duration": 30.88}, {"text": "That you must take into consideration the public interest and the individual and this Court has held in many instances that where public interest is involved as against specific gratification of personal rights, that if it's of sufficient importance, to the public interest that those gratification -- that the gratification of those rights maybe delayed and postponed and we think and that's what this Court said in the Brown decisions.", "start": 4593.259, "stop": 4625.095, "duration": 31.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Aren't you being questioned when you say that the denial of these rights to 40% of the children of your community is in the public interest?", "start": 4625.095, "stop": 4636.138, "duration": 11.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir as a matter of fact we have had a very fine educational system in the city of Little Rock.", "start": 4636.138, "stop": 4644.041, "duration": 7.9}, {"text": "It has actually been the pride of our community, up until the turmoil of this past year and I think it's important.", "start": 4644.041, "stop": 4652.439, "duration": 8.4}, {"text": "I don't think it can be overemphasized that these Negro children as well as all others in Little Rock have a new high school building with faculty, all facilities by all acceptable standards, the equal of Central High School.", "start": 4652.439, "stop": 4674.18, "duration": 21.74}, {"text": "Now, in assigning and weighing and balancing the equities in this case we feel that, that is important.", "start": 4674.18, "stop": 4683.121, "duration": 8.94}, {"text": "I state again that we are not in this lawsuit advocating, going back to the separate but equal doctrine, but we do think that in applying the flexible principles of equity which this Court said should be applied; that, that is a factor to take into consideration and certainly no Negro student will be deprived of an education in qualified schools, that is schools with adequate physical facilities and excellent faculties, if their constitutional rights under the Brown decision are merely postponed for a while.", "start": 4683.121, "stop": 4729.659, "duration": 46.54}]}, {"speakerName": "Harold Burton", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler in some other area if they decide to implement desegregation (Inaudible)", "start": 4729.659, "stop": 4741.877, "duration": 12.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "That has been considered not once but many times, and it's been the Board's observation that such a program in some instances has been workable, in others there -- I think they tried that in Nashville, Tennessee, the first grade and that resulted in the bombing of the school there.", "start": 4741.877, "stop": 4762.99, "duration": 21.11}, {"text": "This board came to the conclusion because of various geographical factors, the housing situation, the physical facilities of all the schools in the system, that it was better to attempt to start at the high school level than at the lower grades.", "start": 4762.99, "stop": 4780.438, "duration": 17.45}, {"text": "Now, I think that some of the school board members as well as some of the population of the area in looking back and having the advantage of observing the events which have taken place can argue without fear of serious contradiction that maybe we should have started at the other end.", "start": 4780.438, "stop": 4804.975, "duration": 24.54}, {"text": "Now that's hindsight.", "start": 4804.975, "stop": 4808.094, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "It was there --", "start": 4808.094, "stop": 4809.182, "duration": 1.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 4809.182, "stop": 4817.126, "duration": 7.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It might work better and it might not.", "start": 4817.126, "stop": 4819.149, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "There is quite a divided opinion on that Mr. Justice Clark, but this Board is -- it still feels that it's plan is given proper time and free of certain obstacles over which it has no control can be successful.", "start": 4819.149, "stop": 4841.564, "duration": 22.41}, {"text": "But many people argue and I can't say that they're wrong, that it might be better to start at the first grade.", "start": 4841.564, "stop": 4852.13, "duration": 10.57}, {"text": "There are some very good reasons why they did not do that.", "start": 4852.13, "stop": 4856.969, "duration": 4.84}, {"text": "At beginning as I say the location of the races within the city dictated and appeared at that time, it was better to start at the high school level.", "start": 4856.969, "stop": 4868.945, "duration": 11.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 4868.945, "stop": 4871.905, "duration": 2.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "There is a kindergarten provided as I understand it, but it is not a part of the free public education or system.", "start": 4871.905, "stop": 4881.26, "duration": 9.36}, {"text": "It's operated in a combination and in conjunction with the public school system, but I think operated by private individuals, if they so desire and they feel.", "start": 4881.26, "stop": 4894.999, "duration": 13.74}, {"text": "The public school system starts at the age of six for the children.", "start": 4894.999, "stop": 4900.587, "duration": 5.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "Who would ever (Inaudible) study the option plan and (Inaudible)", "start": 4900.587, "stop": 4910.724, "duration": 10.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, I think they've studied every possible plan that's ever been suggested to them.", "start": 4910.724, "stop": 4915.988, "duration": 5.26}, {"text": "I'm not sure that I personally know the terms of the plan you have in mind, but I know this school board has studied every possible solution that has been called to its attention.", "start": 4915.988, "stop": 4929.987, "duration": 14}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible) school itself?", "start": 4929.987, "stop": 4934.39, "duration": 4.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, as a matter of fact that has been suggested and one of the statutes passed recently incorporates that general quality into it, and many people in our area feel that, that has possibilities, and should be given an opportunity to be explored in a time free of turmoil.", "start": 4934.39, "stop": 4961.3, "duration": 26.91}, {"text": "That is a very definite possibility, and some very able citizens have suggested that approach to it, which maybe the ultimate solution.", "start": 4961.3, "stop": 4973.296, "duration": 12}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Did Judge Lemley make any finding as to whether it could be anticipated two-and-a-half years of the sentiments which you say is an action of the public petition, which you say frustrated the board, would change?", "start": 4973.296, "stop": 4990.416, "duration": 17.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, he did not make any such finding of fact as that.", "start": 4990.416, "stop": 4995.459, "duration": 5.04}, {"text": "The farthest he went was to say this, that insofar as he could determine that if the plan of integration were not postponed, at this semester beginning September 1958, that it would result in troops or I believe as he put it the equivalent of that, to be within the school and on the school grounds in order to maintain order and that it was his belief that if granted some delay such as asked for by the Board for a short period, that it would provide a period of calm relief from the excessive tension and turmoil, so that various other things can be considered and perhaps solutions worked out.", "start": 4995.459, "stop": 5056.936, "duration": 61.48}, {"text": "I think that was in effect what he said.", "start": 5056.936, "stop": 5060.33, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "I don't believe he made any determination of just what might be the result two-and-a-half years from now, but he did recognize that it was essential for some delay or postponement in order to preserve the educational system in Little Rock, and particularly at Central High School.", "start": 5060.33, "stop": 5082.124, "duration": 21.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "I gather from your brief and argument, I don't know whether I'm right or not, and it goes something like this, there is that you call it in your brief, a massive resistance to the constitutional principle that this Court announced, State of Arkansas, has been led by your Governor and other high public officials, that the Board is helpless to do anything, because of state opposition, and meaning by state opposition those who are charged with (Inaudible), you're asking for time on account of that massive resistance and hostility to the law?", "start": 5082.124, "stop": 5124.078, "duration": 41.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, that's in our brief and that is our position, yes.", "start": 5124.078, "stop": 5131.789, "duration": 7.71}]}, {"speakerName": "William J. Brennan, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "May I ask Mr. Butler where did the two-and-a-half year interval derived from, was that Board's suggestion or was that --", "start": 5131.789, "stop": 5140.961, "duration": 9.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, as I said a few moments ago Mr. Justice Brennan the first petition to Judge Lemley on February 20, 1958 set no specific time limit, except it was on this basis that at the present time and for the next school year, it appears that if this plan of desegregation of integration is carried forward, that we cannot as a board continue our public -- a school system in an effective manner at least.", "start": 5140.961, "stop": 5172.896, "duration": 31.93}, {"text": "And they suggested that the District Court considered all of the evidence and then determine, in his best judgment, when he felt that such a climate of acceptance might be foretold.", "start": 5172.896, "stop": 5188.116, "duration": 15.22}, {"text": "And Judge Lemley declined to assume that first responsibility, and in his statement to all of the parties, told the school board to go back and exercise its judgment, which he felt should be exercised as to what period of time was necessary within which to do that.", "start": 5188.116, "stop": 5211.633, "duration": 23.52}, {"text": "And that's when the school board considering the time required for various state statues and other things to get out of the way and to provide some reasonable period to let things simmer down, concluded that two-and-a-half years was the proper time.", "start": 5211.633, "stop": 5230.096, "duration": 18.46}, {"text": "Now the first consideration, that they came to or first conclusion was that it might work better and I believe we touched on that point at the last hearing, that it had a chance of working better at mid semester, that the school was better organized at that time and school officials were you might say in more complete charge of the situation.", "start": 5230.096, "stop": 5253.237, "duration": 23.14}, {"text": "It may also have been dictated by a feeling, well it certainly didn't work in September, maybe it'll work in some other month better, but they had a good reason for that.", "start": 5253.237, "stop": 5261.183, "duration": 7.95}, {"text": "Now that was the reason for the mid term, the two year, additional two years was for the other reasons which we had enumerated which -- yes sir.", "start": 5261.183, "stop": 5271.325, "duration": 10.14}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible) on page 29 of your brief you criticize the federal government for not giving -- having given the school board adequate protection, and then you go on and say no protection is to be expected, in two-and-a-half years it will be wise to suspend operations for that period.", "start": 5271.325, "stop": 5295.514, "duration": 24.19}, {"text": "Do I correctly infer from that, that what you're saying is that if adequate protection, adequate backing and enforcement is given to the school board, then you see no need for any different --", "start": 5295.514, "stop": 5312.552, "duration": 17.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, I don't think that is our conclusion Mr. Justice Harlan.", "start": 5312.552, "stop": 5318.737, "duration": 6.19}, {"text": "We don't feel that immediate forceful enforcement, and by that I mean by troops and things of that nature, is the answer at this time.", "start": 5318.737, "stop": 5334.944, "duration": 16.21}, {"text": "Now we do feel that somewhere down the line, there should be adequate enforcement by some power that is certainly in excess of any power that the school board has to maintain peace.", "start": 5334.944, "stop": 5351.594, "duration": 16.65}, {"text": "But in our best judgment, and in the judgment of the school board and of Judge Lemley, a necessary postponement was dictated even though you had military force or whatever, that some additional to that was desirable so that a period of calm, free of actual turmoil, a period if you please when people in the community were not forced into doing something immediately and precipitously, but to give them time to feel that they were acquiescing and helping to solve distressing problems which are on the minds and hearts of most of the people there.", "start": 5351.594, "stop": 5413.926, "duration": 62.33}, {"text": "The disturbing thing about -- one of the disturbing things about it is that throughout our community and this is probably true in many other communities, people are more and more at this point going into the extremes.", "start": 5413.926, "stop": 5430.775, "duration": 16.85}, {"text": "The moderate people and their thinking have been brushed aside for the moment.", "start": 5430.775, "stop": 5437.124, "duration": 6.35}, {"text": "The school board feels that with a reasonable period of time and postponement that perhaps that -- those extremes views on either side can be overcome by the calmer period people within -- and between those two extremes.", "start": 5437.124, "stop": 5458.674, "duration": 21.55}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well such change of public opinion doesn't spontaneously arise, such is not my experience or reading or reflection on that intangible thing called public opinion, mere passage of time, the mere passage of time wouldn't by itself change what you indicate is this hostile attitude what was once on sufferance is now hostility, merely letting time pass wouldn't make another change into the prior direction, would it?", "start": 5458.674, "stop": 5495.301, "duration": 36.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I agree with that Mr. Justice Frankfurter.", "start": 5495.301, "stop": 5497.256, "duration": 1.95}, {"text": "I don't think the mere passage of time will necessarily do it.", "start": 5497.256, "stop": 5502.544, "duration": 5.29}, {"text": "I think that it cannot succeed unless there is some reasonable length of time granted for it to have an opportunity by evolution rather than revolution to come into fulfillment.", "start": 5502.544, "stop": 5516.792, "duration": 14.25}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "That presupposes does it not Mr. Butler that the leadership in your state is going to take some affirmative step to relieve the public opinion in that direction.", "start": 5516.792, "stop": 5531.016, "duration": 14.22}, {"text": "You point out in your brief that one of the factors that school board is confronted has been because of the enactment of the state laws opposing integration that that has led people to believe and the support the governor has given to those movements, that all those have combined to lead people to believe that somehow rather despite the Constitution and everything else, there are valid ways the state can delay or defeat this integration.", "start": 5531.016, "stop": 5562.805, "duration": 31.79}, {"text": "Now if the federal courts themselves are going to take a step to delay on the premises that you have stated implementation of this decree, why isn't that delay going to lead and spell for more hope on the part of oppositionists to integration that maybe this thing can be ultimately defeated?", "start": 5562.805, "stop": 5583.27, "duration": 20.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Mr. Justice Harlan, that's a matter of opinion and we certainly don't say that that's going to solve all of the problems and I thoroughly agree with you, I think you are saying about same thing that mere delay may not be the answer but we cannot see any sound –-", "start": 5583.27, "stop": 5603.55, "duration": 20.28}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "And all you are suggesting is a delay in your argument?", "start": 5603.55, "stop": 5609.51, "duration": 5.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We just say this that the first thing that must be done is for the people in that community and I dare say in other communities to have an opportunity free of things such as troops and any kind of military show of force that that is the primary thing that must be done at this time to postpone it, to give those other forces a chance.", "start": 5609.51, "stop": 5641.202, "duration": 31.69}, {"text": "Now we don't say necessarily that all problems are going to be dispelled into thin air two-and-a-half years from now, that has never been our position, but we say that solutions cannot be arrived there, proper solutions that will be acceptable by enough people to make it supportable unless such a delay is granted and we have hope just as everyone has hoped that these distressing problems can at least partially be solved if a reasonable postponement is given.", "start": 5641.202, "stop": 5682.69, "duration": 41.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler, would you care to comment on the suggestions conveyed in the letters of the Attorney General and from the City management, the school board which is now before the Court?", "start": 5682.69, "stop": 5693.677, "duration": 10.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I hadn't planned to but if Your Honor requests it, I'll be glad.", "start": 5693.677, "stop": 5697.723, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "I have some comments that I have no hesitancy in making.", "start": 5697.723, "stop": 5700.483, "duration": 2.76}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible) Solicitor General thought they are relevant and he submitted it.", "start": 5700.483, "stop": 5704.254, "duration": 3.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir, he did and here is his letter, and I think it has been given wide publicity --", "start": 5704.254, "stop": 5716.081, "duration": 11.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "And before the Court that's why (Inaudible)", "start": 5716.081, "stop": 5718.363, "duration": 2.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I might -- yes sir and I might suggest reading the answer which so far as I am aware has not been given any publicity by the president of the school board.", "start": 5718.363, "stop": 5732.037, "duration": 13.67}, {"text": "Mr. Wayne Upton received the letter from the Attorney General I believe on September the 9th and answered it the same day, and sent me a copy of it in which he says, “Dear Mr. Rogers, this will acknowledge your receipt on September 9 of your airmail letter of September 7th relating to the problem of the Little Rock School Board in the event that immediate integration at Central High School is ordered by the Supreme Court of United States.", "start": 5732.037, "stop": 5760.797, "duration": 28.76}, {"text": "We are indeed grateful for the attitude of your office as expressed in your September 7 letter and you maybe assured that the school board will give this matter its careful consideration at the earliest practicable moment.", "start": 5760.797, "stop": 5773.71, "duration": 12.91}, {"text": "I cannot speak for the board being only one of six members, but the thinking of board during the school year of 1957-58 was that criminal prosecutions would have been more helpful in solving the board's problems than injunctive relief.", "start": 5773.71, "stop": 5789.901, "duration": 16.19}, {"text": "Since ours is a considerably larger community than either Hoxie or Clinton it occurred to us that in an injunctive order directed to specific individuals would not necessarily have been affective.", "start": 5789.901, "stop": 5802.191, "duration": 12.29}, {"text": "There were so many people in this community actively opposed to integration that we had – that had we obtained orders of injunction against the known leaders, others would have been there to take their places.", "start": 5802.191, "stop": 5814.454, "duration": 12.26}, {"text": "It seems to us that we could have very well been involved in an almost endless effort to obtain injunction.", "start": 5814.454, "stop": 5824.167, "duration": 9.71}, {"text": "Moreover for a great portion of the time there was no federal judge available and such by the way is the situation at the present time.", "start": 5824.167, "stop": 5832.067, "duration": 7.9}, {"text": "Nevertheless our board shares with you the interest and desire to arrive at a peaceable solution of the problems facing us.", "start": 5832.067, "stop": 5839.845, "duration": 7.78}, {"text": "We will at all times be available for consultation with you or other officers of the Department of Justice.”", "start": 5839.845, "stop": 5845.928, "duration": 6.08}, {"text": "Now you have asked for my observation about that and in all candor I will tell is this.", "start": 5845.928, "stop": 5855.466, "duration": 9.54}, {"text": "We feel that the offer from the Attorney General comes at least a year late.", "start": 5855.466, "stop": 5861.491, "duration": 6.02}, {"text": "Our second observation is what Mr. Upton pointed out that the school board should not be put in the position of seeking injunctions against people when it was not the motivating force which caused the United States Supreme Court to make these decisions in the Brown cases.", "start": 5861.491, "stop": 5888.832, "duration": 27.34}, {"text": "In other words it was willing to comply with the law and it did what it could within its limited power to do that, but it has been the feeling of that board that if injunctive relief is the answer, which it questioned, then such injunctive relief should come through the cooperation of the NAACP which is adequately financed and certainly ably styled and the Attorney General's office and not from injunctive relief at the institution of the school board itself.", "start": 5888.832, "stop": 5928.35, "duration": 39.52}, {"text": "Now that is partially my observation but I think it pretty generally expresses the basic feeling of this board.", "start": 5928.35, "stop": 5938.315, "duration": 9.96}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well may I say this, what you -- your answer is it were historical comment on what, on what might happen, but the Attorney General's letter, in answer to my question and you said military force, the Attorney General's letter suggest facilities for enforcement other than military forces.", "start": 5938.315, "stop": 5962.376, "duration": 24.06}, {"text": "I was wondering if prospectively and not by way of historic comment of what might have been done or should have been done, pursued, do you think -- you have any comment to make on that?", "start": 5962.376, "stop": 5974.804, "duration": 12.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well I'd like to make this comment if Your Honor please that for at least the last three months this school board has been so involved in litigation it has hardly had time and certainly not sufficient energy to give careful consideration to any of these possible solutions including that just received from the Attorney General's office.", "start": 5974.804, "stop": 6005.518, "duration": 30.71}, {"text": "Again we think that that dictates the necessity of a period within which those things can be explored, that and other problems.", "start": 6005.518, "stop": 6021.156, "duration": 15.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 6021.156, "stop": 6026.877, "duration": 5.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well I think Mr. Justice Clark first thing you have to get there would be an injunction that's the problem.", "start": 6026.877, "stop": 6033.199, "duration": 6.32}, {"text": "You have an injunction then you have a citation for contempt as a result of that injunction and the point that Mr. Upton was making I believe was that you'd have to either at the same time or at different stages obtain injunctions against a large segment of the community and you don't know just where that would extend to.", "start": 6033.199, "stop": 6062.766, "duration": 29.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 6062.766, "stop": 6067.517, "duration": 4.75}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir.", "start": 6067.517, "stop": 6068.672, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 6068.672, "stop": 6076.133, "duration": 7.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's certainly subject to a citation for contempt if you can find the precise persons who are interfering and have evidence to show that they did interfere and of course –-", "start": 6076.133, "stop": 6088.26, "duration": 12.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Tom C. Clark", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's (Inaudible) an injunction?", "start": 6088.26, "stop": 6089.934, "duration": 1.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "And of course that is one of the problems of presenting evidence.", "start": 6089.934, "stop": 6093.304, "duration": 3.37}, {"text": "And I'd like to say at this point, I believe Mr. Justice Harlan raised the question, we -- we have not been critical of the attitude of the Justice Department.", "start": 6093.304, "stop": 6105.547, "duration": 12.24}, {"text": "We feel that that everybody connected with this has a problem and I might say that it's singular to me that there has been as little criticism of the forces involved who are actually concerned with this.", "start": 6105.547, "stop": 6122.681, "duration": 17.13}, {"text": "We have no criticism of their position.", "start": 6122.681, "stop": 6125.096, "duration": 2.41}, {"text": "We have an understanding of it.", "start": 6125.096, "stop": 6127.813, "duration": 2.72}, {"text": "As a matter of fact, one of the problems has been that and I think it's no secret so expressed by various persons within the Attorney General's office that members of the staff of the Attorney General feel that there are not adequate federal laws with which they can deal with this problem.", "start": 6127.813, "stop": 6154.341, "duration": 26.53}, {"text": "Now we think that that's what prompted the Attorney General about a year ago after a complete FBI report which we have never seen to say that in print that no person who would interfered with the integration plan in Little Rock would be prosecuted by the Office of the Department of Justice in that community.", "start": 6154.341, "stop": 6180.905, "duration": 26.56}, {"text": "Now I hope I am not misunderstood and we don't want to be appearing in a position of being critical of their attitude.", "start": 6180.905, "stop": 6189.959, "duration": 9.05}, {"text": "We are understanding of it.", "start": 6189.959, "stop": 6191.818, "duration": 1.86}, {"text": "We are sympathetic and we feel very earnestly that they are sympathetic with our position and our problems, but we still say that for things such as the Attorney General is now suggesting, which we received on the 9th that some delay must be given to implement that suggestion and to get ready for it and to try to prepare for it and solve the problems that are presented there.", "start": 6191.818, "stop": 6238.487, "duration": 46.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler in the hearing before Judge Lemley did the school board or anyone else introduce any evidence to show that there were any forces at work or any processes in motion to relieve your community of this feeling and action that is prompting your board to take its present position contrary to what it took before?", "start": 6238.487, "stop": 6271.405, "duration": 32.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir.", "start": 6271.405, "stop": 6272.549, "duration": 1.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why wasn't that done?", "start": 6272.549, "stop": 6274.067, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Not specifically Mr. Chief Justice, we -- the board came to this rather simple conclusion that it could not carry on an educational process effectively under those circumstances.", "start": 6274.067, "stop": 6286.683, "duration": 12.62}, {"text": "It felt that in order to give any kind of solution a chance that it must have a delay and largely that evidence which was presented to Judge Lemley over a period of some three days was to give him a history so that he could exercise his judicial discretion as to what to do and the evidence that was presented there simply showed the breakdown as a result of obstacles which were completely beyond the control of that school board, that were destroying the educational system.", "start": 6286.683, "stop": 6325.546, "duration": 38.86}, {"text": "Now that's what -- and the school board felt and obviously Judge Lemley felt that, that under the Brown decision was within his sphere of exercising his judicial discretion in giving what the Board asked for.", "start": 6325.546, "stop": 6341.072, "duration": 15.53}, {"text": "Now we didn't get into that lawsuit as to all of the possible suggestions as to what might be done.", "start": 6341.072, "stop": 6348.37, "duration": 7.3}, {"text": "We felt that the period of time to be granted by the trial judge; that, that was the time after feelings simmered down some, to explore these various things and to get ready, whatever course might take, so that adequate preparation would be forthcoming.", "start": 6348.37, "stop": 6368.679, "duration": 20.31}, {"text": "And not have to make decisions --", "start": 6368.679, "stop": 6369.35, "duration": 0.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler, you said you to refer to the --", "start": 6369.35, "stop": 6371.048, "duration": 1.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 6371.048, "stop": 6371.646, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You continue to refer to delays and I'm wondering if your position (Inaudible) I have.", "start": 6371.646, "stop": 6383.991, "duration": 12.35}, {"text": "As I understand your basic premise is that in a state where the government -- all that -- with great majority of public officials charged with enforcement of law, creating and most of the people are told in carrying out the Court's decree, the matter should be delayed in their state, that it comes down that.", "start": 6383.991, "stop": 6413.639, "duration": 29.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Let me state it this way Mr. Justice Black, here is the position we take.", "start": 6413.639, "stop": 6418.068, "duration": 4.43}, {"text": "This conflict has resolved itself as we see it as a school board into a head on collision between the federal and state governments.", "start": 6418.068, "stop": 6433.34, "duration": 15.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But there is any doubt as to what the Constitution says about that, is it?", "start": 6433.34, "stop": 6436.954, "duration": 3.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No sir, but that conflict insofar as the executives of those two sovereignties is concerned, must be resolved and this school board can't resolve it.", "start": 6436.954, "stop": 6450.7, "duration": 13.75}, {"text": "Now, the school board feels that until that conflict is resolved that it is helpless to carry on an effective educational system, and they are asking for time for that conflict in all of its ramifications to be resolved so that they can then, whatever the resolutions maybe on what might be termed an upper level, they can be guided by the resolution of those conflicts and formulate plans within the framework of those solutions.", "start": 6450.7, "stop": 6492.968, "duration": 42.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could it be -- you would (Inaudible) stating whether or not you believe, but you're not, of the situation in the Senate, at least in the State of Arkansas, that you could predict that with any time in the foreseeable future, this conflict on this issue would be resolved unless a court order was put in effect.", "start": 6492.968, "stop": 6522.196, "duration": 29.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes sir I think it's possible that this conflict could be resolved without --", "start": 6522.196, "stop": 6527.091, "duration": 4.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You think they said --", "start": 6527.091, "stop": 6527.956, "duration": 0.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Without an immediate court order requiring the school board to proceed forthwith, yes sir I think there is hope of that.", "start": 6527.956, "stop": 6538.358, "duration": 10.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "You're of the opinion, would not continue to be a majority of the people, majority of the officials who opposed hearing out the Court's decree?", "start": 6538.358, "stop": 6550.697, "duration": 12.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "You're not going to change the opposition of the majority of the people of Arkansas who are opposed to integration of the races in the public schools in two-and-a-half years in my opinion, but I think it is entirely likely that within such a period of time, the people of the State of Arkansas will no longer, or any large segment of, any uncontrollable segment of them, be put in -- justifiably be put in the category of law defiers and mob formers and people of that category.", "start": 6550.697, "stop": 6595.349, "duration": 44.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "In your argument before as I recall it, you stated that one of the forceful arguments that was made before us, that there were statute passed by various states that were intended to nullify, you may not of used the word nullify, to nullify this Court's order and people were not sure it would remain the law.", "start": 6595.349, "stop": 6618.456, "duration": 23.11}, {"text": "As I understood it you urge that the Court's opinion be made clear now for its position?", "start": 6618.456, "stop": 6634.265, "duration": 15.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well the first part of that certainly is accurate and I think it's implicit in us being here that we feel that this is a problem which this Court must deal with and again I say though that the conclusion of our school board and of our local district judge was that of that the problems in Little Rock Arkansas as distinguished from other related problems or dissimilar problems in other states, that a time for a cooling off period was in order and it was the only hope of arriving at suitable solutions that would be acceptable both to courts and to the majority of the people in that area and in areas similarly situated with similar problems.", "start": 6634.265, "stop": 6694.199, "duration": 59.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler, your answer to Justice Black a minute ago to the question preceding which you've just answered, your answer is if I may say so is about as important thing as has been said by you in the course of your argument, and therefore I would like to ask you whether I rightly infer the full significance of what you said.", "start": 6694.199, "stop": 6716.393, "duration": 22.19}, {"text": "Am I right to infer that you suggest that the mass of people in Arkansas, are law abiding, are not mobsters, they do not like desegregation, but they maybe one, two respect for the Constitution is pronounced by the organ charged with the duty of declaring it and therefore adjusting themselves to it, although they may not like it, is that the significance to what you said?", "start": 6716.393, "stop": 6744.185, "duration": 27.79}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Your Honor, you have said it so much better and so much more accurately and so much more concisely that I could adopt it wholeheartedly and that is exactly my personal feeling and I believe it is the feeling of the school board as an organization.", "start": 6744.185, "stop": 6764.168, "duration": 19.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well Mr. Butler do you then believe that if this Court should in deciding this case clarify the things that you think are now obscure in the minds of the involved people in Arkansas; that, that will take the place of the delay or do you seek delay in preference to clarification?", "start": 6764.168, "stop": 6794.982, "duration": 30.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We seek clarification, but we say to make that clarification effective and to keep our public school system intact, we must also have a delay to do it.", "start": 6794.982, "stop": 6809.534, "duration": 14.55}, {"text": "If I may use a homely illustration, it occurs to me that it's just about like this.", "start": 6809.534, "stop": 6816.456, "duration": 6.92}, {"text": "Some man comes up with a gun in your back, and he orders you to do something that maybe you ought to do, but as long as he has that gun in your back, he's going to try to find someway to turn around quickly and take that gun away and is going to amount in the long run to a particular conflict between those two people.", "start": 6816.456, "stop": 6836.513, "duration": 20.06}, {"text": "Whereas if you remove the gun and tempers have a chance to simmer down, the man at whose back the gun is being pointed may see the advisability of following the course which the man behind him had advocated all along, but in a spirit of conciliation, in a spirit of patriotism if you please, he will come nearer doing the thing without injury to either party, if he is given time within which to appraise it in a judicial manner, and in a slow manner, in a manner with deliberate speed if you please Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 6836.513, "stop": 6884.149, "duration": 47.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well that's gets a little involved for me, but may I put it this way?", "start": 6884.149, "stop": 6891.243, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "Would you say that no matter how clearly this Court might resolve the issues that are involved in this case, you still insist upon your delay of two-and-a-half years?", "start": 6891.243, "stop": 6908.915, "duration": 17.67}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "We insist upon any period of time which --", "start": 6908.915, "stop": 6911.621, "duration": 2.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well do you still insist upon delay?", "start": 6911.621, "stop": 6913.725, "duration": 2.1}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes a postponement of it, yes sir we do.", "start": 6913.725, "stop": 6918.432, "duration": 4.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "We'll take recess now.", "start": 6918.432, "stop": 6923.032, "duration": 4.6}]}]}, {"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - September 11, 1958 (Part 2)", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13495", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler, you may proceed.", "start": 0, "stop": 3.643, "duration": 3.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Your Honor.", "start": 3.643, "stop": 14.957, "duration": 11.31}, {"text": "If we are to read the newspaper reports accurately; it appears that the Government of Arkansas has stated that he would again call out the National Guard if he felt that it became necessary to maintain law and order.", "start": 14.957, "stop": 31.388, "duration": 16.43}, {"text": "The last time that he did that course under this stated purpose, he issued orders to keep the children out of the school.", "start": 31.388, "stop": 41.048, "duration": 9.66}, {"text": "If that is accurate, he says he will do that again and then the President of the United States if we are further to read the news reports accurately, he said that he would call the National Guard and then federalize it in order to prevent the Court orders from being nullified or ineffective or interfered with.", "start": 41.048, "stop": 67.039, "duration": 25.99}, {"text": "Now, these executives carry out their stated plans and obviously, Central High School will again have troops and if it's true that the education processes cannot effectively be carried on with troops patrolling the grounds and the buildings, then action of this Court if it affirms the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals, will by all logic and reason seriously impair, if not, virtually destroy the full potential of a high school education for those children at that time.", "start": 67.039, "stop": 99.558, "duration": 32.52}, {"text": "Now, in one of the briefs amicus curiae, this statement --", "start": 99.558, "stop": 109.531, "duration": 9.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "They're not before us, Mr. Butler.", "start": 109.531, "stop": 114.499, "duration": 4.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "All right, sir.", "start": 114.499, "stop": 115.208, "duration": 0.71}, {"text": "Well, if this -- this statement which I have pondered and I'm sure it presents a problem to this Court.", "start": 115.208, "stop": 123.25, "duration": 8.04}, {"text": "This statement is made that no court in history has attempted to enjoin 50 million people.", "start": 123.25, "stop": 133.552, "duration": 10.3}, {"text": "Now, the author of course, I presume was not referring to Arkansas alone of course, but approximately where there are some two million people.", "start": 133.552, "stop": 144.368, "duration": 10.82}, {"text": "But to that vast area which comprises some 12 states that's usually referred to the South.", "start": 144.368, "stop": 153.014, "duration": 8.65}, {"text": "The area, if you please, referred to by one of the justices as he amply observed that national policy might not be the same in Little Rock, Arkansas as it is in Pittsfield, Massachusetts.", "start": 153.014, "stop": 167.315, "duration": 14.3}, {"text": "The point that I get from -- form that comment that no court in history has ever attempted to enjoin 50 million people.", "start": 167.315, "stop": 177.861, "duration": 10.55}, {"text": "It points up simply the School Board's position that they are not in a position to go out with their very limited facilities and -- and seek injunctions against an entire province and if -- and it -- it's emphasized in this quotation that it's in our brief, Mr. Justice Holmes, some years ago in the case of Giles versus Harris, which we quote on page 33 of our brief.", "start": 177.861, "stop": 206.455, "duration": 28.59}, {"text": "The substance of it is simply this.", "start": 206.455, "stop": 208.651, "duration": 2.2}, {"text": "You will recall that the case involved the registration of Negro voters in the State of Alabama and Mr. Justice Holmes made this observation.", "start": 208.651, "stop": 221.577, "duration": 12.93}, {"text": "He's talking about the State not being a technical party to the sue, but he says, “And if we leave the State out of consideration, the Court has its little practical power to deal with the people of the State in abiding.”", "start": 221.577, "stop": 238.537, "duration": 16.96}, {"text": "In other words, he was saying even though the State isn't a party to it, if the people of the State which actually are the State, oppose something in mass as very little in a court of equity can do to remedy that particular situation, unless it is implemented in other ways.", "start": 238.537, "stop": 257.87, "duration": 19.33}, {"text": "And he goes on to say that if the conspiracy and intent exist.", "start": 257.87, "stop": 263.197, "duration": 5.33}, {"text": "The name on a piece of paper will not defeat them unless we are prepared to supervise the voting in that State by officers of this Court.", "start": 263.197, "stop": 271.31, "duration": 8.11}, {"text": "It seems to us that all that the plaintiff could get from equity would be an empty form.", "start": 271.31, "stop": 278.578, "duration": 7.27}, {"text": "And then, he ends up by this which we have supplied emphasis to in our brief, a part from damages to the individual, relief from a great political wrong, if done, as alleged by the people of the State and the State itself must be given by them or by the legislature and the political department of the Government of the United States.", "start": 278.578, "stop": 301.061, "duration": 22.48}, {"text": "He was just pointing out around the practical problems.", "start": 301.061, "stop": 306.674, "duration": 5.61}, {"text": "Now, if we see the issue in this and I -- even though this is repetition, I think it bears repeating that the issue as we see it and distinguished from the issue as set out in the opinion of the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals which we think is not the issue in this particular case.", "start": 306.674, "stop": 326.165, "duration": 19.49}, {"text": "Here's why we see the issue.Can a court of equity postpone the enforcement of the plaintiff's constitutional rights if the immediate enforcements thereof will deprive many others of their constitutional rights to an education in a free public school?", "start": 326.165, "stop": 344.365, "duration": 18.2}, {"text": "This Court as well as other courts dealing with this disturbing problem and in fact counsel for NAACP joins with courts in recognizing that in a situation such as faces this Court today, equities must be balanced.", "start": 344.365, "stop": 362.327, "duration": 17.96}, {"text": "And as counsel has said, “The irreparable harm on the one side as against the harm on the others,” and we submit that if the equities of the school children in Little Rock are the equities that are to be good -- to be given consideration or among those -- then we submit that the scales weighed down heavily in their favor and in favor of the relief which the District Court gave to the School Board.", "start": 362.327, "stop": 390.846, "duration": 28.52}, {"text": "I'd like to adopt also a statement which seems to me to be (Inaudible) from the brief which was submitted by the Honorable J.W.Fullbright, the distinguished Senator from Arkansas --", "start": 390.846, "stop": 401.424, "duration": 10.58}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler, I wish you wouldn't go into the briefs.", "start": 401.424, "stop": 403.857, "duration": 2.43}, {"text": "If you filed amicus curiae, you can (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 403.857, "stop": 406.911, "duration": 3.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, this is the --", "start": 406.911, "stop": 407.111, "duration": 0.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- pick any argument that you want but the briefs are not before us.", "start": 407.111, "stop": 410.253, "duration": 3.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, this is -- this, we adopt is part of our argument, Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 410.253, "stop": 412.526, "duration": 2.27}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "You can say anything you want, but it isn't a part of this record when you referred to it as a brief in this Court.", "start": 412.526, "stop": 418.182, "duration": 5.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, we have adopted this as part of our argument and it's a quotation.", "start": 418.182, "stop": 423.641, "duration": 5.46}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "You can make any arguments you wish, but not -- not as coming from the brief in -- on filing in this court because it isn't there.", "start": 423.641, "stop": 432.275, "duration": 8.63}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "This question seems to be appropriate to us.", "start": 432.275, "stop": 436.834, "duration": 4.56}, {"text": "Is it not the province of equity to which this Court was committed by the second Brown decision to adopt its statement of constitutional principles to the purposes, functions and abilities of the institutions to which those principles are certainly to apply.", "start": 436.834, "stop": 455.243, "duration": 18.41}, {"text": "That is the public school systems in the south and particularly in our case to Little Rock.", "start": 455.243, "stop": 461.581, "duration": 6.34}, {"text": "What indeed is the purpose of entrusting equitable jurisdiction to local Federal District Courts, if it is not to permit an appraisal of what can be done to comply with the orders of this Court in the light of good faith, efforts of local School Boards?", "start": 461.581, "stop": 483.086, "duration": 21.5}, {"text": "The Circuit Court of Appeals' majority seems to have been cognizant only of the violent and unlawful acts of individual citizens and groups and did not give proper way to the equitable nature of the proceeding.", "start": 483.086, "stop": 501.463, "duration": 18.38}, {"text": "It seems to us that it failed to recognize that there was involve not simply the violence of individual citizens, but the conflict of two sovereignties, the State and Federal Government.", "start": 501.463, "stop": 513.863, "duration": 12.4}, {"text": "This conflict poses problems which go far beyond in a quite different problem, the problems dealing with lawless mobs.", "start": 513.863, "stop": 522.722, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "They are problems which are not readily solved by federal injunctions in our opinion.", "start": 522.722, "stop": 529.098, "duration": 6.38}, {"text": "One of the essential issues is the refusal of a state government to accept the validity of a federal court decision as being a law.", "start": 529.098, "stop": 537.7, "duration": 8.6}, {"text": "The realities are that due to an unexpected and unprecedented development, this Court's original objective of procuring for Negro children, education on an integrated basis cannot be provided under existing circumstances, unless one subscribes to the theory that an educational process can be carried on effectively, while troops are the equivalent or in the -- on the school premises.", "start": 537.7, "stop": 565.483, "duration": 27.78}, {"text": "Time is desperately needed to enable us and enable persons in authority to find an adjustment of this distressing conflict.", "start": 565.483, "stop": 577.742, "duration": 12.26}, {"text": "No decision --", "start": 577.742, "stop": 578.668, "duration": 0.93}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understood from the findings of the District Court that the processes of -- of education in the classroom were not being interrupted here as if it was in the school grounds, the entrances and the halls.", "start": 578.668, "stop": 591.571, "duration": 12.9}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "And the corridors.", "start": 591.571, "stop": 592.36, "duration": 0.79}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "The corridors.", "start": 592.36, "stop": 593.266, "duration": 0.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "There was one bit of evidence.", "start": 593.266, "stop": 594.793, "duration": 1.53}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "We don't have any findings of a district judge that -- that you couldn't conduct a class or anything like that.", "start": 594.793, "stop": 600.262, "duration": 5.47}, {"text": "Classes were going ahead and the educational process currently was --", "start": 600.262, "stop": 604.14, "duration": 3.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think that was generally true, Mr. Justice Douglas, but there was one reference in -- in some witness, teacher's testimony and I believe Judge Lemley referred to it and that was that in patrolling the halls, there were glass doors and children in the classroom would see soldiers going up and down the corridors and that that was destructing influence and I think -- and -- and that's why I had reference to.", "start": 604.14, "stop": 627.01, "duration": 22.87}, {"text": "I know that that was in the evidence and I believe that it was mentioned in -- in Judge Lemley's opinion, although I cannot be certain of that.", "start": 627.01, "stop": 637.279, "duration": 10.27}, {"text": "No decision which this Court can make will assure the rights the Negro children more effectively than those decisions which are as heretofore rendered.", "start": 637.279, "stop": 645.868, "duration": 8.59}, {"text": "In spite of the full force of the executive power of the federal government, even the use of Armed Forces of the United States, children did not and cannot enjoy it better, we think not even as good an opportunity for education under conditions of turmoil which result from such extreme measures.", "start": 645.868, "stop": 665.178, "duration": 19.31}, {"text": "And of course, the education of all children, Negro and white suffer when such conditions exist.", "start": 665.178, "stop": 675.514, "duration": 10.34}, {"text": "We believe that the argument that to accept the decision of the District Court for two and a half year delay is an abandonment of the integration decision of this Court is without merits.", "start": 675.514, "stop": 687.905, "duration": 12.39}, {"text": "Such an argument takes no account of the difference between the annunciation of the constitutional doctrine and the application of that doctrine through the principals of equity.", "start": 687.905, "stop": 699.163, "duration": 11.26}, {"text": "More importantly, it takes no account of the obligation of the courts to adopt their powers to the purposes for which the institution or activity are affected by this powers exist.", "start": 699.163, "stop": 711.054, "duration": 11.89}, {"text": "This Court has stated that courts of equity may and frequently do go much farther, both to give or withhold relief in furtherance of the public interest than they are accustomed to go when only private rights are involved.", "start": 711.054, "stop": 726.276, "duration": 15.22}, {"text": "I believe we cite a case to that effect in our brief.", "start": 726.276, "stop": 729.428, "duration": 3.15}, {"text": "The processes of public education in this country offer the solution, if any is to be found whereby men of different races may learn to abide one another and in the full enjoyment of their rights.", "start": 729.428, "stop": 742.961, "duration": 13.53}, {"text": "If this is agreed, then the systems of education must be respected and preserved and social experimentation in there made tolerable to their purposes.", "start": 742.961, "stop": 756.311, "duration": 13.35}, {"text": "One other point that we feel that perhaps it's justified for this Court to take into consideration because after all it is the top court of equity and expects the lower courts and itself to do equity when equitable principles are involved and we simply pose this question.", "start": 756.311, "stop": 785.239, "duration": 28.93}, {"text": "It can be expected that the control of local school boards will fall into the hands of radicals and fanatics.", "start": 785.239, "stop": 795.198, "duration": 9.96}, {"text": "In which event, neither the processes of justice or education would be served, unless some reasonable delay is given in this case.", "start": 795.198, "stop": 806.208, "duration": 11.01}, {"text": "Now, we pose that as a question and we also believe that it has merit as argument.", "start": 806.208, "stop": 815.809, "duration": 9.6}, {"text": "Now, in the final analysis, this Court being a court of equity, of course it has the power to do whatever it feels, considering the entire record and all of the factors involved is the proper and right thing to do.", "start": 815.809, "stop": 838.057, "duration": 22.25}, {"text": "We again plead for the opportunity to preserve our public education system and that is our primary plea.", "start": 838.057, "stop": 849.044, "duration": 10.99}, {"text": "In the best judgment of the School Board, it has a chance of survival so as to give effective education to the children, only if some reasonable delay is given, whether that delay should be six months, whether it should be two weeks, whether it should be a year, whether it should be two years, it's certainly a matter of opinion and judgment.", "start": 849.044, "stop": 875.937, "duration": 26.89}, {"text": "I say again that it was the earnest belief, the well-considered judgment of the School Board that it had the best chance of arriving at solutions to these distressing problems if it were given the period of time within which to work those out and which time was approved by the federal district judge in his judicial discretion.", "start": 875.937, "stop": 904.689, "duration": 28.75}, {"text": "Now, we do not say that that is the only time.", "start": 904.689, "stop": 908.661, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "No one can say that that is the precise time when this can be solved.", "start": 908.661, "stop": 914.299, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "It maybe, that in this Court's judgment, six months maybe long enough.", "start": 914.299, "stop": 920.467, "duration": 6.17}, {"text": "It maybe a year will be long enough.", "start": 920.467, "stop": 923.86, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "That again is a matter of equity to determine, but the case is before you on the basis of what the School Board felt was the shortest period of time or the best period of time within which these solutions could be final.", "start": 923.86, "stop": 946.38, "duration": 22.52}, {"text": "We have described the situation where the School Board, a creature of the State is placed between the millstones and a conflict between the State and federal courts.", "start": 946.38, "stop": 958.885, "duration": 12.5}, {"text": "We believe that we have pointed out the absurdity of the premise that the School District should keep the peace.", "start": 958.885, "stop": 966.091, "duration": 7.21}, {"text": "We think that that is an incredible argument which does not deserve mush attention.", "start": 966.091, "stop": 972.159, "duration": 6.07}, {"text": "It is obvious that the School Board has no police powers as such.We say again that the problem which we feel has not yet been grasped by the respondents and the Solicitor General and by the Circuit Court of Appeals, that there are two elements which must be present in this situation.", "start": 972.159, "stop": 997.139, "duration": 24.98}, {"text": "First, that a plan of desegregation, that's the first plan.", "start": 997.139, "stop": 1002.546, "duration": 5.41}, {"text": "This Board has had that plan and this, the District formulated several years ago and tried in good faith to put into operation.", "start": 1002.546, "stop": 1016.127, "duration": 13.58}, {"text": "Second, that a plan of adequate enforcement in a word, there has been despite pleas to the Department of Justice by school officials and by the respondents.", "start": 1016.127, "stop": 1030.272, "duration": 14.14}, {"text": "Again, we say we're not being critical of that department, but they have not come forth until recently with the suggestion of this kind and their hands have been tied, we feel, to engage in criminal prosecutions where some were possibly indicated.", "start": 1030.272, "stop": 1051.398, "duration": 21.13}, {"text": "Since these dual plans are required and only one is in existence at this time, the least relief that the School District should have is a stay of the plan of desegregation until the District Court is satisfied that a plan of enforcement is in operation and is efficient to ensure an adequate educational program and an educational climate during the operation of the plan of desegregation.", "start": 1051.398, "stop": 1091.174, "duration": 39.78}, {"text": "This may take two weeks.", "start": 1091.174, "stop": 1093.25, "duration": 2.08}, {"text": "It may take two years, but until an adequate enforcement is an actuality, the plan of desegregation will be effective only to wreak havoc upon our school system.", "start": 1093.25, "stop": 1108.524, "duration": 15.27}, {"text": "And this Court, as a court of equity, we feel should remand the case to the District Court with instructions to tell that Court that when and if the conflict between the sovereignties is settled and when an effective plan of enforcement, so that the school system can function, is presented and appears to the District Court to have a reasonable chance of success, that until such time, the School Board should be given a postponement of its plan.", "start": 1108.524, "stop": 1153.217, "duration": 44.69}, {"text": "And we feel that this Court as a court of equity, of course has with in its power to do that.", "start": 1153.217, "stop": 1161.557, "duration": 8.34}, {"text": "Thank you.", "start": 1161.557, "stop": 1163.471, "duration": 1.91}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Marshall", "start": 1163.471, "stop": 1167.062, "duration": 3.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "May it please the Court.", "start": 1167.062, "stop": 1170.014, "duration": 2.95}, {"text": "There are one or two preliminary points and then I think, the argument for respondents can be rather briefed, because I think the issues are so clear.", "start": 1170.014, "stop": 1182.049, "duration": 12.04}, {"text": "The first one I -- I hate to start again in answering an argument, but I take the flat position that this quote, “battle between the sovereigns” was decided with the Constitution when it was adopted.", "start": 1182.049, "stop": 1195.77, "duration": 13.72}, {"text": "That was settled some years ago.", "start": 1195.77, "stop": 1199.111, "duration": 3.34}, {"text": "That leads into the second point which is I think it's one thing for a law politician in the State to argue or a political officer in a State to argue, that the disagreement with the Supreme Court of the United States or the doubt as to the power authority of the Supreme Court.", "start": 1199.111, "stop": 1228.086, "duration": 28.97}, {"text": "That makes another thing for a lawyer to stand in this Court and argue that there is any doubt about it.", "start": 1228.086, "stop": 1233.585, "duration": 5.5}, {"text": "And I think that's where we are in this case, for example, the reason to hold up this for this other lawyers.", "start": 1233.585, "stop": 1244.368, "duration": 10.78}, {"text": "Mr. Butler said he wasn't -- he wasn't too sure what was in it.", "start": 1244.368, "stop": 1251.013, "duration": 6.64}, {"text": "Well, here is one batch of laws passed by the legislature in Arkansas, the General Assembly, giving the Governor his authority and here's what has come about.", "start": 1251.013, "stop": 1266.928, "duration": 15.92}, {"text": "Since Judge Lemley's order, as a result of Judge Lemley's order, this is the action we can expect to be amplified for two and a half or more years.", "start": 1266.928, "stop": 1281.556, "duration": 14.63}, {"text": "This is S.B.No.2, Senate Bill Number 2 introduced by (Inaudible).", "start": 1281.556, "stop": 1291.081, "duration": 9.52}, {"text": "It says, it -- it has been found and it is hereby declared by the General Assembly that a large majority of the people of this State are opposed to the possible integration of, or mixing other races in the public schools of the State, that practically all of the people of the State are opposed to the use of federal troops in aide of such integration.", "start": 1291.081, "stop": 1317.759, "duration": 26.68}, {"text": "That the people of the State are opposed to the use of any federal power to enforce the integration of the races in the public schools, that it has now threatened that Negro children will be forcibly enrolled and permitted to attend some of the public schools of the State, formally attended only by white children.", "start": 1317.759, "stop": 1338.054, "duration": 20.3}, {"text": "That the President of United States has indicated that federal troops maybe used to enforce the orders of the District Court restricting enrollment in attendance of Negro pupils in schools, formally attended only by white children.", "start": 1338.054, "stop": 1352.607, "duration": 14.55}, {"text": "And that the possible operation of a public school in this State attended by both Negro and white children will inevitably result in violence in and about the schools and throughout the District, both endangering the safety of buildings and other property wise.", "start": 1352.607, "stop": 1368.632, "duration": 16.03}, {"text": "And that the state or feeling of the great majority of people of the State is such that a forcible mix in the races in public schools will seriously impair the operation in suitable efficient schools and on and on.", "start": 1368.632, "stop": 1381.12, "duration": 12.49}, {"text": "And that exact same section is quoted in everyone of this batch of bills which gives to the Governor the right to close the schools, take away the money, use it for private schools to give the state money to private schools, provided they have operated on the segregated basis, and other means of relief.", "start": 1381.12, "stop": 1406.431, "duration": 25.31}, {"text": "The other batch of bills are bills that are aimed at and I hope despite references have been made to counsel on this side and not to mention who this bill is directed to.", "start": 1406.431, "stop": 1419.979, "duration": 13.55}, {"text": "This is an Act entitled, an act to prohibit the fomenting and education and litigation that interferes with the orderly administration of public schools and institution of higher learning, and to prohibit the solicitation, receipt or donation of funds for the purpose of filing of prosecuting lawsuits to define maintenance, divide a penalty and therefore, statute closely like the one in Virginia, which a three-judge court with an opinion, exhausted opinion by Judge Soper, declared to be unconstitutional in which bills are now before this Court.", "start": 1419.979, "stop": 1460.884, "duration": 40.9}, {"text": "If time is given, it's obvious from this that in two and a half years, the law will be so crystalized in Little Rock, I mean in Arkansas that there will be no litigation, and they're protected by making sure that there'll be no lawyers to litigate.", "start": 1460.884, "stop": 1482.792, "duration": 21.91}, {"text": "And that is the reason that the plea is made for time, and whether or not the School Board believes as they do, time is time.", "start": 1482.792, "stop": 1494.937, "duration": 12.14}, {"text": "I don't believe, if it please the Court, that ever before has an effort been made to get a watering down of constitutional rights without any basis and although it was brought out in questioning.", "start": 1494.937, "stop": 1519.335, "duration": 24.4}, {"text": "As of right now, these petitioners in this case had given not the slightest idea of doing anything.", "start": 1519.335, "stop": 1529.304, "duration": 9.97}, {"text": "And that's what gets me to the point that they say that we agree that we should balance equities.", "start": 1529.304, "stop": 1534.193, "duration": 4.89}, {"text": "I never have agreed, as a lawyer that you can balance personal equities against constitutional rights, but even if you go into the so-called, what petitioners call equities, with all of the problems that the children went through in that school and the faculties.", "start": 1534.193, "stop": 1556.333, "duration": 22.14}, {"text": "Democracy has stopped.", "start": 1556.333, "stop": 1559.407, "duration": 3.07}, {"text": "There's always going to be a measure of difficulty and problems.", "start": 1559.407, "stop": 1565.225, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "The School Board is so worried because they get threat in telephone calls and letters.", "start": 1565.225, "stop": 1571.55, "duration": 6.33}, {"text": "I don't believe anybody ever in public office that is worth assaulted and make a decision one way or the other that didn't get telephone calls and letters.", "start": 1571.55, "stop": 1578.975, "duration": 7.42}, {"text": "That's a -- that's a part of service to democracy.", "start": 1578.975, "stop": 1582.91, "duration": 3.94}, {"text": "I don't welcome it, but I -- I recognize it.", "start": 1582.91, "stop": 1586.813, "duration": 3.9}, {"text": "But I think we have to think about these children and their parents.", "start": 1586.813, "stop": 1591.821, "duration": 5.01}, {"text": "These Negro children went through this everyday, and their parents has stayed at home, wondering what was happening to there children, listening to the radio about the bomb threats and all of that business.", "start": 1591.821, "stop": 1604.75, "duration": 12.93}, {"text": "I don't see how anybody under the sun could say that after those children, those families went through that for a year to tell them, “All you have done is gone.", "start": 1604.75, "stop": 1616.932, "duration": 12.18}, {"text": "You fought for what you consider to be democracy and you lost, and you go back to the segregated school from which you came.”", "start": 1616.932, "stop": 1625.446, "duration": 8.51}, {"text": "I just don't believe it and I don't believe you can balance those rights.", "start": 1625.446, "stop": 1630.316, "duration": 4.87}, {"text": "So, don't question here of the right of one group of children against another.", "start": 1630.316, "stop": 1636.833, "duration": 6.52}, {"text": "The other side constantly talks and indeed Judge Lemley taught about the injury to education.", "start": 1636.833, "stop": 1648.218, "duration": 11.38}, {"text": "It's according to what type of education we're talking about.", "start": 1648.218, "stop": 1652.27, "duration": 4.05}, {"text": "In our brief, I think it started around page 8.", "start": 1652.27, "stop": 1656.809, "duration": 4.54}, {"text": "We quoted from the decision in the Brown case and the West Virginia against Barnette and the argument of the Solicitor General two weeks ago, as to what education is.", "start": 1656.809, "stop": 1672.904, "duration": 16.1}, {"text": "Education is not the teaching of three hours.", "start": 1672.904, "stop": 1676.714, "duration": 3.81}, {"text": "Education is teaching of the overall citizenship, to learn, to leave together with fellow citizens and above all, to learn to obey the law.", "start": 1676.714, "stop": 1690.905, "duration": 14.19}, {"text": "Now, we talk about public education.", "start": 1690.905, "stop": 1694.009, "duration": 3.1}, {"text": "We think from those three quotations there is clear.", "start": 1694.009, "stop": 1696.843, "duration": 2.83}, {"text": "That's what we mean and the damage to the education in Arkansas in Little Rock and in Central High comes about to the order of Judge Lemley, which says that not only the School Board and the State came and ensured to submit to more violence and threats of more violence what did federal judiciary likewise should do so.", "start": 1696.843, "stop": 1724.205, "duration": 27.36}, {"text": "I don't know of anymore horrible destruction of principle of citizenship and to tell young children that those of you who withdrew rather than to go to the school with Negroes, those of you who are punished last year the three -- the few that the School Board did punish.", "start": 1724.205, "stop": 1746.799, "duration": 22.59}, {"text": "Come back, all is forgiven, you win.", "start": 1746.799, "stop": 1752.397, "duration": 5.6}, {"text": "And therefore, I'm not worried about the Negro children at this stage.", "start": 1752.397, "stop": 1757.128, "duration": 4.73}, {"text": "I don't believe they're in this case as such.", "start": 1757.128, "stop": 1761.278, "duration": 4.15}, {"text": "I worry about the white children in Little Rock who are told as young people that the way to get your rights is to violate the law and defy the lawful authorities.", "start": 1761.278, "stop": 1773.806, "duration": 12.53}, {"text": "I'm worried about their future.", "start": 1773.806, "stop": 1776.391, "duration": 2.59}, {"text": "I don't worry about the Negro kids' future.", "start": 1776.391, "stop": 1779.196, "duration": 2.8}, {"text": "They've been struggling with democracy long enough.", "start": 1779.196, "stop": 1781.192, "duration": 2}, {"text": "They know about it.", "start": 1781.192, "stop": 1783.076, "duration": 1.88}, {"text": "This is actually laid there.", "start": 1783.076, "stop": 1787.697, "duration": 4.62}, {"text": "The State of Arkansas with the Governor holding these Bills, refusing to sign them and say publicly that he holds them to see what this Court is going to do.", "start": 1787.697, "stop": 1803.797, "duration": 16.1}, {"text": "Maybe it's happened before, but I don't know of any others as where the Governor of a State has tried to hold something over this Court.", "start": 1803.797, "stop": 1813.627, "duration": 9.83}, {"text": "And I think that this Court has to recognize that, not to consider this case as counsel for the School Board would say, as to whether or not the children in Little Rock lost some education last year.", "start": 1813.627, "stop": 1830.117, "duration": 16.49}, {"text": "The evidence in the record is in complete conflict.", "start": 1830.117, "stop": 1834.396, "duration": 4.28}, {"text": "They say that the -- the great feeling of having troops in the school, for the record shows that the President is responsible for sending the troops to Little Rock, but the record shows and I think it's page 269, that they were put in the school at the request of Superintendent Blossom.", "start": 1834.396, "stop": 1855.56, "duration": 21.16}, {"text": "He's the one who put them inside of the school.", "start": 1855.56, "stop": 1858.425, "duration": 2.87}, {"text": "The president didn't and he's now complaining about it and to show this horrible effect in the record in this case about the effect of the troops being in the school.", "start": 1858.425, "stop": 1875.568, "duration": 17.14}, {"text": "There is also a witness who is a band director who has his band class and everything up on the fifth floor to round things up on top of the (Inaudible) so the sound goes up and disturb the -- there are no Negroes in the band class.", "start": 1875.568, "stop": 1891.015, "duration": 15.45}, {"text": "There are not even Negroes on that floor that he said he couldn't teach, because of the effect of Negroes being down on the first floor the fact that him teaching up on the fifth floor.", "start": 1891.015, "stop": 1901.633, "duration": 10.62}, {"text": "Well that's stretching a little in my imagination.", "start": 1901.633, "stop": 1904.128, "duration": 2.49}, {"text": "I mean, that's moving a little too far, and I think that that's the type of testimony in this record where -- where there's just no basis for it and I would not urge this Court make this effort to balance the harm -- to one of the harm to the other.", "start": 1904.128, "stop": 1922.79, "duration": 18.66}, {"text": "The next point I like to make is that in the Deep South today, there are three sets of School Boards.", "start": 1922.79, "stop": 1933.518, "duration": 10.73}, {"text": "There's one set that is working along and working it out either with or without court orders and working it out on a procedural basis and ranging over periods of years, varying with each School District.", "start": 1933.518, "stop": 1946.818, "duration": 13.3}, {"text": "In other School Boards, it says, “We just won't move at all.” And there's a third group that says, “The only way to move is over a very gradual period of years,” and in this case, we have that -- it's a gradual plan as you can find.", "start": 1946.818, "stop": 1967.746, "duration": 20.93}, {"text": "There was no ultimate time limit on it.", "start": 1967.746, "stop": 1969.99, "duration": 2.24}, {"text": "It would just go on and on, and it was approved by the District Court, affirmed by the Court of Appeals and not brought to this Court.", "start": 1969.99, "stop": 1977.563, "duration": 7.57}, {"text": "We went back down to see if it worked out.", "start": 1977.563, "stop": 1980.276, "duration": 2.71}, {"text": "And now, they say that this -- the most gradual of gradual plans can't work, then that group has joined the other group which says, “It just can't work anyhow.”", "start": 1980.276, "stop": 1994.233, "duration": 13.96}, {"text": "And so, the Brown decision means nothing, except in the areas where the people voluntarily accepted it.", "start": 1994.233, "stop": 2001.409, "duration": 7.18}, {"text": "And in their brief, they argue in -- in one particular place.", "start": 2001.409, "stop": 2007.119, "duration": 5.71}, {"text": "It's on page 29 of their brief.", "start": 2007.119, "stop": 2008.965, "duration": 1.85}, {"text": "They argue this after saying after two and one a half years.", "start": 2008.965, "stop": 2013.107, "duration": 4.14}, {"text": "They say, “If in the nature of things, there will never be any protection.", "start": 2013.107, "stop": 2016.379, "duration": 3.27}, {"text": "Operation should be suspended until such time as the people by processes of time are taught to respect court decisions and to be \\willing on patriotic grounds to subdue the passions which now control their thinking.”", "start": 2016.379, "stop": 2035.26, "duration": 18.88}, {"text": "If constitutional rights are to wait for that period, I submit you don't need the Constitution and you don't need this Court, if everybody was voluntarily do right, but it is interesting on this time element.", "start": 2035.26, "stop": 2051.014, "duration": 15.75}, {"text": "These two and a half years must be measured with three different groups of students, Negro.", "start": 2051.014, "stop": 2059.495, "duration": 8.48}, {"text": "The seven now in the record shows will be graduated at the -- within two and a half years, they'd be gone.", "start": 2059.495, "stop": 2068.092, "duration": 8.6}, {"text": "Now, when the argument is made that rights are not being destroyed, certainly the argument cannot be made that those children's rights on through.", "start": 2068.092, "stop": 2074.969, "duration": 6.88}, {"text": "They are out -- they are out of school.", "start": 2074.969, "stop": 2078.129, "duration": 3.16}, {"text": "The second group, are those that are eligible under the plan to come in this year and the third group or the others in the class which we furthered down the line from the high school going down to the elementary school.", "start": 2078.129, "stop": 2096.072, "duration": 17.94}, {"text": "And so, we took the position from the beginning of this era, that there where -- these three all fell into to one package and you couldn't strike one without striking the other.", "start": 2096.072, "stop": 2109.025, "duration": 12.95}, {"text": "And constantly, their argument is -- is understandably aimed and only the seven children and to me, that's the most dangerous argument that can be made.", "start": 2109.025, "stop": 2120.15, "duration": 11.13}, {"text": "It's one thing to say that we need time to put a plan into action.", "start": 2120.15, "stop": 2129.812, "duration": 9.66}, {"text": "It's another thing to say that a plan once in action, in -- once in performance should be suspended and stopped or halted.", "start": 2129.812, "stop": 2140.292, "duration": 10.48}, {"text": "We have argued in our brief and we've argued from the beginning of this that any application for time is based on the same principle as those who -- and as it was set out in the Brown decision that you ask for time originally.", "start": 2140.292, "stop": 2152.305, "duration": 12.01}, {"text": "There's no difference and certainly public opposition is not sufficient.", "start": 2152.305, "stop": 2159.568, "duration": 7.26}, {"text": "The most interesting argument I get from the State, I mean from the School Board is that two partners come in, in the case and say.”", "start": 2159.568, "stop": 2168.871, "duration": 9.3}, {"text": "I'm not responsible from non-performance because my partner stopped me from performing.”", "start": 2168.871, "stop": 2174.041, "duration": 5.17}, {"text": "I don't see a better difference.", "start": 2174.041, "stop": 2176.434, "duration": 2.39}, {"text": "The State is a unit.", "start": 2176.434, "stop": 2178.78, "duration": 2.35}, {"text": "The Fourteenth Amendment was aimed against the State, and all of this panoply of state action from the Governor on down is made against them and in that line, I have to comment on the continued resentment of the School Board at any suggestions that they seek to relieve in Hoxie or the Clinton, Tennessee relief.", "start": 2178.78, "stop": 2204.794, "duration": 26.01}, {"text": "And they say for example that it's not their job to go into court and get an injunction.", "start": 2204.794, "stop": 2211.369, "duration": 6.58}, {"text": "They don't have to go into court and get an injunction.", "start": 2211.369, "stop": 2214.86, "duration": 3.49}, {"text": "All they have to do is to go in the Court and say to the Court; I suggest that your adjunction in your degree is being violated.", "start": 2214.86, "stop": 2223.547, "duration": 8.69}, {"text": "We are prevented from -- that's all they have to do.", "start": 2223.547, "stop": 2225.422, "duration": 1.88}, {"text": "And in Clinton, the -- the judge called in the United States Department of Justice through the Attorney General's office, but there's no action yet.", "start": 2225.422, "stop": 2237.152, "duration": 11.73}, {"text": "They stood here this morning -- this afternoon and complained that they've been tied up in litigation in this case for three months.", "start": 2237.152, "stop": 2243.148, "duration": 6}, {"text": "They could very well have been tied up three months and seen what could be done there.", "start": 2243.148, "stop": 2246.726, "duration": 3.58}, {"text": "And indeed, Judge Lemley could have done so.", "start": 2246.726, "stop": 2250.407, "duration": 3.68}, {"text": "But from the beginning or the end of this case, the record will show that whenever there was a move against integration at Central High School, each step, the School Board made a move to get the Negro kids out of there, each step of the way and they are still at this late date arguing the same point against public violence.", "start": 2250.407, "stop": 2277.947, "duration": 27.54}, {"text": "And finally, if it please the Court, on the question of -- although we have respondents, the question of relief is important.", "start": 2277.947, "stop": 2287.833, "duration": 9.89}, {"text": "In our brief, we requested that the Court reverse -- I mean affirm the Court of Appeals, and that the Court set aside Judge Lemley's order and reinstate Judge Davis' orders and Judge Miller's order.", "start": 2287.833, "stop": 2308.498, "duration": 20.66}, {"text": "But after thinking about it, we would like with the permission of the Court to amend the -- the request of the Court that if the Court should decide to affirm the Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit that even to -- mandate to issue forthwith would not meet the realities of the situation because school opens on Monday, and this is a matter of the mandate issuing.", "start": 2308.498, "stop": 2336.62, "duration": 28.12}, {"text": "And we would respectfully suggest that if the Court does decide to affirm, that the Court ruled that Judge Lemley's order be set aside and these other orders reinstated as of the entry of the judgment in this Court.", "start": 2336.62, "stop": 2354.142, "duration": 17.52}, {"text": "We think that that would give the type of relief and on that, I understand that both sides of the counsel table are in agreement as to this Court clarifying the situation.", "start": 2354.142, "stop": 2365.921, "duration": 11.78}, {"text": "The only question is about time and I submit that the decision, the clarification cannot be made in time given at the same time.", "start": 2365.921, "stop": 2376.654, "duration": 10.73}, {"text": "And unless there are some -- one other point I forgot to mention, if it please the Court.", "start": 2376.654, "stop": 2383.071, "duration": 6.42}, {"text": "On the last appearance, the Court questioned about Judge Davis' original opinions and original orders.", "start": 2383.071, "stop": 2391.332, "duration": 8.26}, {"text": "We have with us certified copies of each of his two original orders.", "start": 2391.332, "stop": 2397.25, "duration": 5.92}, {"text": "With the permission of the Court, I would like to deposit it in the clerk's office in case any one would desire to see them and if there are no further questions, we would submit on the ground that the one single issue in this case where the case stripped down is the issue as to whether or not a federal District Court can delay an integration plan, desegregation plan already in progress, solely because of violence and threats of violence.", "start": 2397.25, "stop": 2434.725, "duration": 37.47}, {"text": "It's a narrow question and I believe it's the only question in this case and we therefore submit that the decision of the Court of Appeals is imminently correct that it should be affirmed or should be affirmed in such fashion as to make it clear even to the politicians in Arkansas, that Article VI of the Constitution means what it says.", "start": 2434.725, "stop": 2465.498, "duration": 30.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler, do you have anything in rebuttal?", "start": 2465.498, "stop": 2470.937, "duration": 5.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2470.937, "stop": 2471.664, "duration": 0.73}, {"text": "There are a few points that I would like to respond to, Mr. Chief Justice, in regard of what counsel for opponents has stated.", "start": 2471.664, "stop": 2484.555, "duration": 12.89}, {"text": "First, I would like to comment that there is not much doubt, although there maybe more than I suspect as to what lawyers as distinguished from the great mass of people think the law to be.", "start": 2484.555, "stop": 2503.406, "duration": 18.85}, {"text": "I think that virtually, every lawyer that has studied constitutional law in any manner recognizes as the School Board recognizes as -- and his counsel for the School Board recognizes that the federal law is supreme and if you do have a conflict between the two, then of course state law or constitutions must give way.", "start": 2503.406, "stop": 2529.877, "duration": 26.47}, {"text": "The point that we have made all along is that when you have responsible public officials, columnists and various other people in whom a populist has confidence telling them differences of opinion about it, it creates in the minds of those people some question as to what the law and not necessarily in the minds of lawyers, but in the minds of the great mass of people and in the minds of people who are I say again not basically law violators.", "start": 2529.877, "stop": 2566.241, "duration": 36.36}, {"text": "Now, counsel has commented on the equities in the situation and of course we feel that in the Brown decision, this Court disposed of that.", "start": 2566.241, "stop": 2581.24, "duration": 15}, {"text": "It recognized that there are equities in it that must be weighed, public and private rights.", "start": 2581.24, "stop": 2587.965, "duration": 6.73}, {"text": "When the Court said, because of their proximity to local conditions and the need for further hearings, the courts which originally heard these cases can best perform this judicial appraisal.", "start": 2587.965, "stop": 2601.703, "duration": 13.74}, {"text": "Accordingly, we believe it's appropriate to remand the cases to those courts in fashioning and effectuating the decrees.", "start": 2601.703, "stop": 2610.495, "duration": 8.79}, {"text": "The courts will be guided by equitable principles.", "start": 2610.495, "stop": 2614.695, "duration": 4.2}, {"text": "Traditionally, equity has been characterized by practical flexibility in shaping its remedies and by a facility for adjusting and reconciling public and private needs.", "start": 2614.695, "stop": 2629.494, "duration": 14.8}, {"text": "These cases call for the exercise of these traditional attributes of equity power.", "start": 2629.494, "stop": 2639.401, "duration": 9.91}, {"text": "Now, if the record is in conflict as counsel states, there was not much conflict about the evidence produced.", "start": 2639.401, "stop": 2650.512, "duration": 11.11}, {"text": "But whatever the conflict may have been, we believe that those are issues of fact that have been resolved by the trial court without any successful attack.", "start": 2650.512, "stop": 2663.086, "duration": 12.57}, {"text": "As a matter of fact, I didn't realize that there was any real dispute about the evidence, the basic evidence of the problems and obstacles that confronted the School Board.", "start": 2663.086, "stop": 2678.512, "duration": 15.43}, {"text": "We repeat again just posing the question for this Court that if you in effect drive the School Board out of office than other school boards with less moderate views with considerably less determination to follow the law will be replaced thereby.", "start": 2678.512, "stop": 2706.135, "duration": 27.62}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 2706.135, "stop": 2710.552, "duration": 4.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 2710.552, "stop": 2711.358, "duration": 0.81}]}, {"speakerName": "UNKNOWN", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible) resignation is in contemplation?", "start": 2711.358, "stop": 2714.253, "duration": 2.89}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2714.253, "stop": 2715.099, "duration": 0.85}, {"text": "So far as I know, resignation is not in contemplation.", "start": 2715.099, "stop": 2719.481, "duration": 4.38}, {"text": "Effective administration of the school system by the School Board is in jeopardy because the special session of the legislature of Arkansas has virtually turned that administration over to the Governor if he signs this.", "start": 2719.481, "stop": 2744.671, "duration": 25.19}, {"text": "Now, counsel again states that the School Board should do this or that.", "start": 2744.671, "stop": 2753.198, "duration": 8.53}, {"text": "They should ask the Court's assistance.", "start": 2753.198, "stop": 2756.771, "duration": 3.57}, {"text": "The School Board has always every major crisis that has come up, there had been many minor ones, but every major crisis, the School Board has gone to the Court and asked for instructions and tried to get instructions from the courts.", "start": 2756.771, "stop": 2776.353, "duration": 19.58}, {"text": "Now, it's had some practical problem there because as we pointed out, as Mr. (Inaudible) pointed out, there has not been a regularly sitting district judge there for quite some time.", "start": 2776.353, "stop": 2787.343, "duration": 10.99}, {"text": "That has posed a -- a very practical problem.", "start": 2787.343, "stop": 2790.906, "duration": 3.56}, {"text": "There's always been some court.", "start": 2790.906, "stop": 2792.463, "duration": 1.56}, {"text": "I don't mean to imply that you couldn't drive 200 miles or 100 miles or 150 miles and not find a judge, but to have one right there in Little Rock when these questions and problems come up quickly.", "start": 2792.463, "stop": 2805.224, "duration": 12.76}, {"text": "There has not been one available at times and we suggest what is to keep the NAACP, which is the organization that really sponsored the litigation before this Court which prompted this Court, urged this Court to change a doctrine of the law that had been in existence and recognized by this Court by some 58 years.", "start": 2805.224, "stop": 2831.881, "duration": 26.66}, {"text": "What is to keep that organization from going to the federal district judge?", "start": 2831.881, "stop": 2839.282, "duration": 7.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What about the law that was read to us?", "start": 2839.282, "stop": 2841.318, "duration": 2.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Sir?", "start": 2841.318, "stop": 2842.236, "duration": 0.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What about the state law that was read to us you have commented on?", "start": 2842.236, "stop": 2847.102, "duration": 4.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir, there are a whole lot of laws.", "start": 2847.102, "stop": 2848.41, "duration": 1.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that's the NAACP, the law that Mr. Marshall read to us.", "start": 2848.41, "stop": 2855.184, "duration": 6.77}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "That statute --", "start": 2855.184, "stop": 2856.543, "duration": 1.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes.", "start": 2856.543, "stop": 2856.96, "duration": 0.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, that -- as I recall, that was one of the acts that was not sponsored by the Governor.", "start": 2856.96, "stop": 2862.23, "duration": 5.27}, {"text": "I think that was written by the Attorney General.", "start": 2862.23, "stop": 2864.603, "duration": 2.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "I'm not -- because it would -- would it forbid them during what you say is needed to do?", "start": 2864.603, "stop": 2871.318, "duration": 6.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Justice Black, I'm -- I'm sorry, but I don't believe I followed your question, sir.", "start": 2871.318, "stop": 2875.64, "duration": 4.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understood you to say that the NAACP should file a proceeding down in Arkansas.", "start": 2875.64, "stop": 2882.524, "duration": 6.88}, {"text": "Now, I understood the statute to which Mr. Marshall referred that considerable obstacles have been thrown in the way of NAACP was referenced to litigation, is that correct?", "start": 2882.524, "stop": 2894.939, "duration": 12.41}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 2894.939, "stop": 2895.488, "duration": 0.55}, {"text": "That act that he has read does attempt to throw obstacles in the way.", "start": 2895.488, "stop": 2899.63, "duration": 4.14}, {"text": "Now, when I speak of the --", "start": 2899.63, "stop": 2900.786, "duration": 1.16}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why -- why is your argument then a proper one?", "start": 2900.786, "stop": 2903.778, "duration": 2.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, when I -- when I speak --", "start": 2903.778, "stop": 2906.113, "duration": 2.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- make it if you didn't think it was.", "start": 2906.113, "stop": 2907.421, "duration": 1.31}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "When I speak of the NAACP, I really incorporate within that group any individual litigants who claim that their rights are being -- that they're being deprived of those rights.", "start": 2907.421, "stop": 2920.023, "duration": 12.6}, {"text": "I don't mean as an organization necessarily, I mean -- I mean the legal staff which it has that is disposal, the legal staff of the individual litigants, whether they be prompted by the organization or as individual litigants.", "start": 2920.023, "stop": 2939.089, "duration": 19.07}, {"text": "They can go into Court.", "start": 2939.089, "stop": 2940.516, "duration": 1.43}, {"text": "They've been in the case at the same length of time that the School Board had because they sued the School Board to start out with.", "start": 2940.516, "stop": 2947.761, "duration": 7.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "But what's the object of this law?", "start": 2947.761, "stop": 2949.685, "duration": 1.92}, {"text": "I --I gathered from him.", "start": 2949.685, "stop": 2951.302, "duration": 1.62}, {"text": "I haven't seen it, but I gathered from him, it was to make it impossible for lawyers to do this.", "start": 2951.302, "stop": 2958.456, "duration": 7.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 2958.456, "stop": 2958.873, "duration": 0.42}, {"text": "I don't think the intent was to make it illegal for a lawyer representing an individual litigant to appear in Court.", "start": 2958.873, "stop": 2969.001, "duration": 10.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Hugo L. Black", "textObjs": [{"text": "What about representing the association?", "start": 2969.001, "stop": 2972.213, "duration": 3.21}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think it was directed to restrict the activities, generally of a number of organizations probably including the NAACP.", "start": 2972.213, "stop": 2984.471, "duration": 12.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "What is -- what's the date of that law, Mr. Butler?", "start": 2984.471, "stop": 2991.086, "duration": 6.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "You Honor, that was one of the acts which was passed about two weeks ago in which it has not yet been signed by the Governor.", "start": 2991.086, "stop": 3002.125, "duration": 11.04}, {"text": "There is some -- there is more doubt in the minds of most people that he will sign that law than he will on one of the others because if -- if my information is correct, he did not sponsor that Bill through the legislation.", "start": 3002.125, "stop": 3016.542, "duration": 14.42}, {"text": "That was not one of the six laws that he sponsored.", "start": 3016.542, "stop": 3020.542, "duration": 4}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Is it?", "start": 3020.542, "stop": 3021.261, "duration": 0.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think I'm correct in that.", "start": 3021.261, "stop": 3022.497, "duration": 1.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "You don't need to be humorous.", "start": 3022.497, "stop": 3023.842, "duration": 1.35}, {"text": "The Governor isn't going to sign the Bills that he didn't sponsor.", "start": 3023.842, "stop": 3027.066, "duration": 3.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "He hasn't yet.", "start": 3027.066, "stop": 3028.002, "duration": 0.94}, {"text": "We have not been taken into his confidence as to what intends to do in the future.", "start": 3028.002, "stop": 3044.079, "duration": 16.08}, {"text": "Now, one last thing that I didn't cover in our principal argument and that is that so far as we know and so far as within the power of this School Board, if this Court orders at any time whether it would be Monday or whether it be at midterm or whether it'd be next spring, so far as the administration of the school is concerned at the present time, not taking into consideration what laws might be signed or put into effect.", "start": 3044.079, "stop": 3080.724, "duration": 36.64}, {"text": "We have no way of knowing that, but at least as of this time, there is no administrative obstacle of the School Board that would keep the present Negro children from being transferred from the all Negro Horace Mann School back over to Central High School.", "start": 3080.724, "stop": 3103.374, "duration": 22.65}, {"text": "Now, it seems to me that questions asked by some of the justices at this hearing and more particularly at the previous hearing were concerned about that.", "start": 3103.374, "stop": 3115.678, "duration": 12.3}, {"text": "Now, in making that statement, we should emphasize again that there are many things over which the School Board has no control.", "start": 3115.678, "stop": 3126.487, "duration": 10.81}, {"text": "But as of the present time, there is no administrative obstacle of the School Board that would prohibit those children, anyone or more of them from being changed from one school to another.", "start": 3126.487, "stop": 3140.681, "duration": 14.19}, {"text": "That is a process that is done in a limited way throughout the school year on occasions where circumstances dictate that it should be done.", "start": 3140.681, "stop": 3153.363, "duration": 12.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "But I understood you last time to say that was the intention of the Board not to make such transfers, did you not?", "start": 3153.363, "stop": 3163.696, "duration": 10.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir, I don't think I said that, Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 3163.696, "stop": 3164.572, "duration": 0.88}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "I asked you this morning, counsel.", "start": 3164.572, "stop": 3166.588, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "You said that the Board is going to -- if we affirmed that the Board would sit on its hands and wait to see what happens.", "start": 3166.588, "stop": 3175.081, "duration": 8.49}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I think it will for a few days to see whether or not the Governor signs these bills because there are some bills in there that for all practical purposes take the administration of the school system in Little Rock away from this Board.", "start": 3175.081, "stop": 3190.681, "duration": 15.6}, {"text": "Now, if it is taken away from the Board completely, they may have no alternative.", "start": 3190.681, "stop": 3197.348, "duration": 6.67}, {"text": "The point I'm making is and I believe -- I believe it was Your Honor that asked me that last time or perhaps Mr. Justice Clark as to whether or not school children were ever transferred from one school to another during the school year.", "start": 3197.348, "stop": 3211.783, "duration": 14.43}, {"text": "And I wanted to emphasize that that is not an unusual thing.", "start": 3211.783, "stop": 3218.108, "duration": 6.33}, {"text": "It's done all the time for various reasons and there is no fixed rule in the Little Rock School system that just because you are registered at the beginning of the year in one school, absolutely requires you to stay there the balance of the year.", "start": 3218.108, "stop": 3234.123, "duration": 16.01}, {"text": "There is no such fixed term policy.", "start": 3234.123, "stop": 3238.143, "duration": 4.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "This -- may I ask you this question?", "start": 3238.143, "stop": 3239.488, "duration": 1.34}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3239.488, "stop": 3239.965, "duration": 0.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- (Inaudible).", "start": 3239.965, "stop": 3242.49, "duration": 2.52}, {"text": "These bills or one of the bills on the Governor's desk now, which if signed wouldn't formally legislate this Board out of office, but do I understand you correctly to say it's provision would in effect by the terms of the statute transfer the present Board's power into some state agency?", "start": 3242.49, "stop": 3266.198, "duration": 23.71}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "That -- that is my opinion of that particular Bill, yes, sir.", "start": 3266.198, "stop": 3270.86, "duration": 4.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "So that they defunct this while they still be normally members of the School Board or not, they'd defunct this?", "start": 3270.86, "stop": 3276.711, "duration": 5.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir.", "start": 3276.711, "stop": 3294.299, "duration": 17.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor General.", "start": 3294.299, "stop": 3296.113, "duration": 1.81}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.", "start": 3296.113, "stop": 3305.661, "duration": 9.55}, {"text": "The Government comes to this Court and asks to promptly affirm the Court of Appeals.", "start": 3305.661, "stop": 3316.292, "duration": 10.63}, {"text": "Reinstate the order of Judge Davis and make the judgment or order of this Court in such form that it will be effective without the problem of mandate or other procedures upon notice to the parties, so that the action will be noticed to all interested parties at the earliest possible dates and certainly before school opens on September 15.", "start": 3316.292, "stop": 3354.653, "duration": 38.36}, {"text": "We think that this case, as I told the Court before, involves the question of maintenance of law and order, not only in this community and the State of Arkansas, but throughout this country.", "start": 3354.653, "stop": 3373.703, "duration": 19.05}, {"text": "The Brown decision as the Government interprets and understands is quite different from what was related to the Court by counsel for the school district.", "start": 3373.703, "stop": 3392.406, "duration": 18.7}, {"text": "This Court said that segregation in public school system maintained by the State is unconstitutional.", "start": 3392.406, "stop": 3407.493, "duration": 15.09}, {"text": "It thereby declared that it is a constitutional right of people not to be segregated by reason of race in the attendance of public schools.", "start": 3407.493, "stop": 3425.673, "duration": 18.18}, {"text": "Now, a constitutional right is what we regard in this country as the most precious rights of all the legal rights we have, because it is declared in our basic document creating a union.", "start": 3425.673, "stop": 3444.23, "duration": 18.56}, {"text": "And constitutional rights are present and perceived rights and this Court had that in mind in its consideration of the second Brown decision and what kind of relief should be granted.", "start": 3444.23, "stop": 3461.562, "duration": 17.33}, {"text": "It was greatly disturbed and I -- I for one was also disturbed and I'm sure other counsel were about the question of whether there can be a postponement for one moment of the present and personal constitutional right.", "start": 3461.562, "stop": 3484.424, "duration": 22.86}, {"text": "And it seemed to us and I think the Court deliberated and thought it through that the right has been declared and then it was a consideration not of how long you can postpone these rights.", "start": 3484.424, "stop": 3503.493, "duration": 19.07}, {"text": "That argument was made to this Court in the first Brown case.", "start": 3503.493, "stop": 3508.401, "duration": 4.91}, {"text": "It was said here time after time.", "start": 3508.401, "stop": 3511.475, "duration": 3.07}, {"text": "“If you just leave us alone, we'll handle this problem ourselves and we'll give them equal protection under the laws, just give us time,” and the Court rejected that argument.", "start": 3511.475, "stop": 3526.583, "duration": 15.11}, {"text": "The same argument was made at the time of the argument about relief and the Court rejected it again, but the Court said, “The principle you must consider in this matter is that this relief is to be given forthwith unless there are equitable factors which you with the burden of proof can show justify some delay of this constitutional right.", "start": 3526.583, "stop": 3561.105, "duration": 34.52}, {"text": "But the principal is that you're entitled to the right forthwith unless there is proof that satisfies a Court that there has to be a delay,” and that delay should be for the very shortest time possible under the efforts of everyone in good faith to give to these people the rights that they have been entitled to for many years.", "start": 3561.105, "stop": 3588.676, "duration": 27.57}, {"text": "That's the way we read the Brown decision and I think that's what this Court said in clear and unequivocal terms.", "start": 3588.676, "stop": 3599.569, "duration": 10.89}, {"text": "Now, the desegregation of schools has gone forward in many areas of this country.", "start": 3599.569, "stop": 3608.269, "duration": 8.7}, {"text": "It has gone ahead in the Border States, many areas without any difficulties whatever and in some of the areas of even of the deeper south.", "start": 3608.269, "stop": 3624.137, "duration": 15.87}, {"text": "What is there in this community, Little Rock and Arkansas was different?", "start": 3624.137, "stop": 3632.121, "duration": 7.98}, {"text": "Certainly, people with the pigment in their skin, black or white were involved in most cases, in most areas where the schools were desegregated without trouble between them.", "start": 3632.121, "stop": 3649.652, "duration": 17.53}, {"text": "The element in this case is lawlessness.", "start": 3649.652, "stop": 3653.892, "duration": 4.24}, {"text": "It is a community, a small number at first at least, maybe more later who decided they were going to defy the laws of this country and I say to you that that's a problem that's inherent in every little village, great city, or country areas of this United States.", "start": 3653.892, "stop": 3683.619, "duration": 29.73}, {"text": "There isn't a single policeman that isn't going to watch this Court and what it has to say about this matter that doesn't have to deal with people everyday who don't -- who don't like the law he is trying to administer and enforce.", "start": 3683.619, "stop": 3703.337, "duration": 19.72}, {"text": "And he has to go against that public feeling and will and do his duty.", "start": 3703.337, "stop": 3711.31, "duration": 7.97}, {"text": "That's the responsibility of every man in this country that's fit to occupy public office.", "start": 3711.31, "stop": 3723.984, "duration": 12.67}, {"text": "Now, there is another thing that I object to in the brief of the School Board here and in the argument and that's this idea that there are two sovereignties, one on this side, one on this side and they're equal.", "start": 3723.984, "stop": 3742.122, "duration": 18.14}, {"text": "Let's see how they fight it out and we'll join up with the one that wins.", "start": 3742.122, "stop": 3748.2, "duration": 6.08}, {"text": "There's nothing to that stuff and that's all it is.", "start": 3748.2, "stop": 3754.105, "duration": 5.91}, {"text": "This country, a union was created because of the need that the states found for some kind of union that would resolve the bitter controversies that arose between the states and it was because this confederation was so unsuccessful in trying to carry on a Government for the people in this small country then that it was decided.", "start": 3754.105, "stop": 3792.883, "duration": 38.78}, {"text": "That was a major force in the creation of this United States and that was back in 1787, a long time ago.", "start": 3792.883, "stop": 3809.489, "duration": 16.61}, {"text": "And in the consideration of the problem, what they'd lived through for years in this unsuccessful Government that they had to deal with, they poured over the problem of what are you going to do.", "start": 3809.489, "stop": 3828.151, "duration": 18.66}, {"text": "We want to keep these two sovereignties.", "start": 3828.151, "stop": 3830.953, "duration": 2.8}, {"text": "We want to keep the benefit of the State and the Union.", "start": 3830.953, "stop": 3836.826, "duration": 5.87}, {"text": "The states to carry out the function of local order, maintaining law and order and the various functions of the state government and on the other hand, the national government with all of the functions that were delegated with.", "start": 3836.826, "stop": 3858.103, "duration": 21.28}, {"text": "But they passed the laws in a confederation.", "start": 3858.103, "stop": 3861.407, "duration": 3.3}, {"text": "The laws were good.", "start": 3861.407, "stop": 3863.191, "duration": 1.78}, {"text": "You look on -- you look at them on the books and you'll find many of them were excellent laws, but the states decided which ones they were going to enforce and some they did and some they didn't.", "start": 3863.191, "stop": 3877.082, "duration": 13.89}, {"text": "And so, you had havoc and this country had great difficulty in maintaining the revolutionary war in part because of the condition of its Government and the fact that it could not get support for the laws that were passed that would not be enforced.", "start": 3877.082, "stop": 3898.993, "duration": 21.91}, {"text": "So, in their contemplation, the founding fathers went over this matter very carefully and they finally concluded that there was only one way to handle it and that was by Article VI in the Constitution.", "start": 3898.993, "stop": 3921.137, "duration": 22.14}, {"text": "And in that, you'll recall the supremacy between a conflict or in a conflict between the federal government and the state government is disposed of.", "start": 3921.137, "stop": 3936.481, "duration": 15.34}, {"text": "In our basic governmental document for all time and it says this Constitution and the law is pursuant to it and the treaties made under its authority of the supreme law of the land.", "start": 3936.481, "stop": 3964.499, "duration": 28.02}, {"text": "Now, how anybody could say there could be any doubt about it with that in our basic Constitution?", "start": 3964.499, "stop": 3973.748, "duration": 9.25}, {"text": "It seems to me, impossible, but they didn't leave it just to that.", "start": 3973.748, "stop": 3979.784, "duration": 6.04}, {"text": "They went on to say that it was going to be binding upon all the courts, not only the federal courts but all the state courts, all the courts of this country wherever they sit are bound by that law not withstanding any laws to the contrary.", "start": 3979.784, "stop": 4007.917, "duration": 28.13}, {"text": "What else could they do?", "start": 4007.917, "stop": 4009.484, "duration": 1.57}, {"text": "This was their major problem in the Government they had just had that was so unsuccessful.", "start": 4009.484, "stop": 4019.282, "duration": 9.8}, {"text": "They decided that everyone who was an official in the legislature or the official of the Government, not only the federal government, but of also of every State in the Union should take an oath to support this Constitution.", "start": 4019.282, "stop": 4050.225, "duration": 30.94}, {"text": "And it was done deliberately and purposefully to deal with this very problem, so that each and every one of them would feel obligated as a man regards his oath to carry out the laws of this country.", "start": 4050.225, "stop": 4071.81, "duration": 21.59}, {"text": "And then, after that, this Constitution was not imposed upon any states or any people of this country.", "start": 4071.81, "stop": 4082.242, "duration": 10.43}, {"text": "It was submitted to them for their vote and they have ratified it because they wanted it and they have always wanted it and they want that provision in it.", "start": 4082.242, "stop": 4095.789, "duration": 13.55}, {"text": "So, I say to you, if the School Board has any doubt about what the law is, it can turn to the Constitution that it is under oath to support just as the members of this Court and myself.", "start": 4095.789, "stop": 4115.984, "duration": 20.2}, {"text": "And in accordance to the manner in which they have regard integrity of their oath, they can find where they should start to find the law and I say to them, “If they can't find it for themselves, they should look first to the Constitution.”", "start": 4115.984, "stop": 4135.595, "duration": 19.61}, {"text": "That's what the Constitution, our basic document says and then they can look to any federal laws or treaties.", "start": 4135.595, "stop": 4140.715, "duration": 5.12}, {"text": "And then, they can look down to see if there are anything in the content, if there is anything in the constitution of the State or the state laws or their own regulations that they should enforce, but I say I think without any proper challenge that their obligations before this country in their community and before this Court is to use all the power that they have and exhaust it to try to perform that oath and first start out with trying to carry out the obligations of the Constitution of the United States as interpreted by this Court.", "start": 4140.715, "stop": 4212.491, "duration": 71.78}, {"text": "Now, the indication in this brief -- argument is that the School Board has found out how the people of this community feel, how strong the feeling is against the desegregation of schools in accordance with the Constitution of United States.", "start": 4212.491, "stop": 4238.315, "duration": 25.82}, {"text": "And so, their plea actually to this Court is very simple.", "start": 4238.315, "stop": 4245.377, "duration": 7.06}, {"text": "Let us wash our hands of it.", "start": 4245.377, "stop": 4249.078, "duration": 3.7}, {"text": "It's a difficult problem and I don't mean to minimize for a moment that it isn't difficult, but I don't think anyone in public office was trying to do the right thing.", "start": 4249.078, "stop": 4267.697, "duration": 18.62}, {"text": "He has ever had an easy time of it.", "start": 4267.697, "stop": 4270.669, "duration": 2.97}, {"text": "He has difficult problems, difficult decisions to make and if you respect his conscience and his honor, he tries to carry it out to the best light he can see regardless of any force or violence or mass opposition.", "start": 4270.669, "stop": 4294.804, "duration": 24.14}, {"text": "I'm not willing to recognize that under the law, the School Board can separate itself from the State of Arkansas.", "start": 4294.804, "stop": 4305.382, "duration": 10.58}, {"text": "It is one of the governmental instrumentalities of that State.", "start": 4305.382, "stop": 4312.276, "duration": 6.89}, {"text": "This state action we're talking about is a state action that the Fourteenth Amendment prohibited.", "start": 4312.276, "stop": 4325.017, "duration": 12.74}, {"text": "And when the State is acting in violation of the rights of these people under the Constitution, whether the School Board participated in it itself, whether it sort of washed its hands of it or stood aside, it is still bound by it because it's in privity with it and this Court must look through it as a legal proposition and see that this in fact is state action that occurred all the time to make it difficult for this program to be carried out in accordance with the Constitution.", "start": 4325.017, "stop": 4372.15, "duration": 47.13}, {"text": "None of the proposals here for delay comply with any of the requirements suggested by this Court in the second Brown decision.", "start": 4372.15, "stop": 4384.892, "duration": 12.74}, {"text": "It requests for delay and modification of the plan should be made, none of it.", "start": 4384.892, "stop": 4393.437, "duration": 8.55}, {"text": "During the argument, if there is any doubt about it prior to that time, it was fully clarified.", "start": 4393.437, "stop": 4400.761, "duration": 7.32}, {"text": "We want to do nothing, just nothing.", "start": 4400.761, "stop": 4406.42, "duration": 5.66}, {"text": "We won't try to educate the people.", "start": 4406.42, "stop": 4409.435, "duration": 3.02}, {"text": "This is an educational process.", "start": 4409.435, "stop": 4410.94, "duration": 1.5}, {"text": "At least they could come forward and say, “We'll tell the people that this Supreme Court has spoken.", "start": 4410.94, "stop": 4417.706, "duration": 6.77}, {"text": "That's the law of the land.", "start": 4417.706, "stop": 4420.85, "duration": 3.14}, {"text": "It's binding.", "start": 4420.85, "stop": 4422.036, "duration": 1.19}, {"text": "We've got to do it.", "start": 4422.036, "stop": 4423.501, "duration": 1.47}, {"text": "The sooner we do it, the better.", "start": 4423.501, "stop": 4425.397, "duration": 1.9}, {"text": "Let's get started at it.”", "start": 4425.397, "stop": 4427.254, "duration": 1.86}, {"text": "They could at least come forward and say, “We would try to educate the people.”", "start": 4427.254, "stop": 4432.978, "duration": 5.72}, {"text": "The school board tried to educate the people during these two and a half years, but that's what they should do.", "start": 4432.978, "stop": 4440.598, "duration": 7.62}, {"text": "But they have a duty as a citizen, the highest duty of a citizen to obey the law and to support this Constitution.", "start": 4440.598, "stop": 4450.373, "duration": 9.77}, {"text": "They could at least offer that in every court they have appeared.", "start": 4450.373, "stop": 4454.573, "duration": 4.2}]}, {"speakerName": "Felix Frankfurter", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Solicitor, am I wrong in recalling that as a matter of fact, the School Board had aide ads merging there on the population of Little Rock?", "start": 4454.573, "stop": 4462.831, "duration": 8.26}]}, {"speakerName": "J. Lee Rankin", "textObjs": [{"text": "At one time, but I think that all of the presentation before the Court would indicate that the educational process in that regard could be worked on much greater and it could be continued at some length.", "start": 4462.831, "stop": 4484.307, "duration": 21.48}, {"text": "Now, the real suggestion is if you give us delay, maybe, there is no assurance.", "start": 4484.307, "stop": 4492.484, "duration": 8.18}, {"text": "That certainly is clear in this argument.", "start": 4492.484, "stop": 4495.516, "duration": 3.03}, {"text": "Maybe, we will be able to have the complexion or the attitude in the community change.", "start": 4495.516, "stop": 4506.316, "duration": 10.8}, {"text": "Maybe, the majority will change and at least be acquiescent to the School Board's program.", "start": 4506.316, "stop": 4521.333, "duration": 15.02}, {"text": "But how if there is no -- nothing that is going on that if the courts themselves, acquiesced in this delay, can you expect that all of a sudden the climate is going to change and be in favor of giving these rights.", "start": 4521.333, "stop": 4546.857, "duration": 25.52}, {"text": "I think it's an impossible suggestion.", "start": 4546.857, "stop": 4550.877, "duration": 4.02}, {"text": "I'd like to make one statement about the phrase all deliberate speed.", "start": 4550.877, "stop": 4558.21, "duration": 7.33}, {"text": "Some comment has been made from time to time, that that was a phrase that this Court adapted that had no particular meaning and it should be clarified as though it was coined for the occasion of the second Brown case, it was not.", "start": 4558.21, "stop": 4581.044, "duration": 22.83}, {"text": "It is an expression that has been known to the English Chancery law for many, many years.", "start": 4581.044, "stop": 4591.373, "duration": 10.33}, {"text": "It is the newest by this Court in several decisions.", "start": 4591.373, "stop": 4598.177, "duration": 6.8}, {"text": "First time that I ran across, it's being used and I may not have found the first one.", "start": 4598.177, "stop": 4605.86, "duration": 7.68}, {"text": "It was by Mr. Justice Holmes in 222 U.S.in Virginia against West Virginia.", "start": 4605.86, "stop": 4616.566, "duration": 10.71}, {"text": "It includes both the elements of acting deliberately and with speed and I think it was carefully chosen because of the problems that the Court recognized their work in this kind of a situation.", "start": 4616.566, "stop": 4634.356, "duration": 17.79}, {"text": "There had to be a deliberate, careful exclusion and inclusion in each case in order to satisfy the requirements of getting this constitutional right into being as rapidly as possible throughout this country and preserve the public school system which was the objective of this Court.", "start": 4634.356, "stop": 4676.436, "duration": 42.08}, {"text": "And in conclusion, let me say that on this Supreme Court building has carved the inscription “equal justice under law”.", "start": 4676.436, "stop": 4693.615, "duration": 17.18}, {"text": "All Americans take pride in this controlling principle of our Government.", "start": 4693.615, "stop": 4702.624, "duration": 9.01}, {"text": "It is there as a reminder of a great objective of this Court in all of its decisions.", "start": 4702.624, "stop": 4713.989, "duration": 11.36}, {"text": "Now, in the gravity of this new challenge to constitutional rights, I respectfully suggest that each time that it becomes an issue, the Court must say in a manner that cannot be misunderstood throughout the length and breathe of this land, there can be no equality of justice for our people if the law steps aside even for a moment at the command of force and violence.", "start": 4713.989, "stop": 4760.227, "duration": 46.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Marshall, do you have any response to Mr. Solicitor General?", "start": 4760.227, "stop": 4763.508, "duration": 3.28}]}, {"speakerName": "Thurgood Marshall", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have no response, Your Honor.", "start": 4763.508, "stop": 4765.035, "duration": 1.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler.", "start": 4765.035, "stop": 4766.832, "duration": 1.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, members of the Court.", "start": 4766.832, "stop": 4772.509, "duration": 5.68}, {"text": "Mr. Rankin has told the Court what he thinks the Court has said.", "start": 4772.509, "stop": 4777.976, "duration": 5.47}, {"text": "I'll try to limit my remarks by merely reading excerpts from the decisions.", "start": 4777.976, "stop": 4785.041, "duration": 7.07}, {"text": "In solving it down, it's simply that equitable principles should apply and that the local District Court should apply those flexible equity principles.", "start": 4785.041, "stop": 4795.537, "duration": 10.5}, {"text": "The Honorable Solicitor General says that only in cases where there is proof to show a cause for delay should delays be granted.", "start": 4795.537, "stop": 4806.182, "duration": 10.64}, {"text": "We submit, Your Honors that this record is replete with reasons for delay and we rest our case on those reasons I set forth in Judge Lemley's decision.", "start": 4806.182, "stop": 4822.154, "duration": 15.97}, {"text": "He further comments that there are places in the Deep South where integration has worked successfully.", "start": 4822.154, "stop": 4832.739, "duration": 10.58}, {"text": "What to me is the Deep South, I'm not aware of any places where such a process is successfully being carried on and I don't want to labor the point, but he does raise an interesting comment, it seems to me and that is -- will this Court forthwith virtually destroy the School Board and has tried to do its duty when places throughout what I call the Deep South at least have made no apparent effort even to formulate a plan.", "start": 4832.739, "stop": 4871.567, "duration": 38.83}, {"text": "I don't know that that's a proper argument in this case, but the Solicitor General has posed a question and I think it is a question that this Court must deal with.", "start": 4871.567, "stop": 4883.206, "duration": 11.64}, {"text": "Now, the Honorable Solicitor --", "start": 4883.206, "stop": 4886.879, "duration": 3.67}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "In saying that -- putting a case in terms of us destroying the School Board, I don't understand that.", "start": 4886.879, "stop": 4896.047, "duration": 9.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, perhaps my words were not chosen well, Mr. Justice Douglas.", "start": 4896.047, "stop": 4900.838, "duration": 4.79}, {"text": "It's -- it's a conflict that it is probably destroying as I see it.", "start": 4900.838, "stop": 4910.869, "duration": 10.03}, {"text": "Now --", "start": 4910.869, "stop": 4911.745, "duration": 0.88}]}, {"speakerName": "William O. Douglas", "textObjs": [{"text": "If the School Board --", "start": 4911.745, "stop": 4912.344, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "-- I think the -- in all candor, I think that the -- that the problem grew up by a change of the law of this Court.", "start": 4912.344, "stop": 4923.079, "duration": 10.73}, {"text": "Now, that's my very candid opinion about it.", "start": 4923.079, "stop": 4925.921, "duration": 2.84}, {"text": "I think all of this conflict would not have resulted, except for the Brown decision.", "start": 4925.921, "stop": 4932.329, "duration": 6.41}, {"text": "At least there wouldn't have been the (Inaudible) about it.", "start": 4932.329, "stop": 4935.521, "duration": 3.19}, {"text": "Now, we're not arguing that point and we are respectfully tried to stay off of it, but that is my candid opinion.", "start": 4935.521, "stop": 4945.947, "duration": 10.43}, {"text": "Now, as to -- and -- and I hope I will not be taken as appearing fictitious because I don't intend to be.", "start": 4945.947, "stop": 4954.155, "duration": 8.21}, {"text": "But the Honorable Solicitor General has says that there is nothing to discuss, the way he puts it about there being a conflict between two sovereignties.", "start": 4954.155, "stop": 4965.831, "duration": 11.68}, {"text": "Well now, the School Board has been under the impression that there has been such a conflict, the result of which caused troops to be within the area under one commander and a day or two later, under another.", "start": 4965.831, "stop": 4982.725, "duration": 16.89}, {"text": "Now, if that isn't a conflict between the federal government and the state sovereign, I'm not aware of what could be.", "start": 4982.725, "stop": 4993.842, "duration": 11.12}, {"text": "The Honorable Solicitor General refers to the Court provisions that the federal law is supreme and of course as I said before, all lawyers recognize that, but one of the basic problems, there are some students of the Constitution who have read other provisions such as the one that says that, “Rights not specifically delegated to the federal government shall be reserved to the states or to the people.”", "start": 4993.842, "stop": 5022.573, "duration": 28.73}, {"text": "Now, a good many people, not only in the South have been reading that provision of the federal constitution and have gotten alarm about the disregard of it.", "start": 5022.573, "stop": 5038.279, "duration": 15.71}, {"text": "Now, he says also that the School Board should use all of the powers if they have to --", "start": 5038.279, "stop": 5042.002, "duration": 3.72}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "I understood you though that is not the position of your Board.", "start": 5042.002, "stop": 5045.403, "duration": 3.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, sir.", "start": 5045.403, "stop": 5045.922, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Why are (Voice Overlap) --", "start": 5045.922, "stop": 5047.389, "duration": 1.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Only because the Solicitor General raised the question, Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 5047.389, "stop": 5054.675, "duration": 7.29}, {"text": "He says that the School Board should use all of the power they have to the outmost and I take it that his argument is implicit or carries implicitly in it that he expects them to go over the brink of the chasm into destruction, or as the in case of (Inaudible), that the law must be held -- upheld even to the destruction of the Republic.", "start": 5054.675, "stop": 5082.248, "duration": 27.57}, {"text": "Now, the School Board cannot separate itself.", "start": 5082.248, "stop": 5087.036, "duration": 4.79}, {"text": "It's true, as pointed out by the Honorable Solicitor General, but the prospect of this Board is if the State will separate it from its function and that's what one of their problems that we have involved in this.", "start": 5087.036, "stop": 5105.384, "duration": 18.35}, {"text": "Now, the School Board, according to the Solicitor General, should try to educate the people.", "start": 5105.384, "stop": 5114.999, "duration": 9.61}, {"text": "I'm not sure that this record will show it.", "start": 5114.999, "stop": 5118.522, "duration": 3.52}, {"text": "I believe it will in Judge Lemyley's opinion, but the fact is and it's undisputed that the Superintendent of Schools and other members of the School Board or -- or members of the School Board, he is not actually a member, went through the community of Little Rock for at least a solid year after the first Brown decision.", "start": 5118.522, "stop": 5144.072, "duration": 25.55}, {"text": "I think I'm correct in saying that in over a period of at least two years, he and others explained the plan, explained to the people of the area that in their -- that this had to be done in some form and if this was a plan that the School Board had felt was workable.", "start": 5144.072, "stop": 5167.569, "duration": 23.5}, {"text": "Now, that was done and it was done to the very best ability of that School Superintendent and that School Board.", "start": 5167.569, "stop": 5176.78, "duration": 9.21}, {"text": "If my memory serves me correctly, Mr. Blossom appeared some 250 times over a period of time in various groups, both in his office and in the public forum, trying to educate the people of that area as to the distressing problem and the probable solutions of it.", "start": 5176.78, "stop": 5198.863, "duration": 22.08}, {"text": "And he and the School Board felt that they had at least the acquiescence of the people of that community.", "start": 5198.863, "stop": 5208.306, "duration": 9.44}, {"text": "That obviously turned out to be an error in judgment.", "start": 5208.306, "stop": 5216.449, "duration": 8.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 5216.449, "stop": 5231.526, "duration": 15.08}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, sir, approximately there, Mr. Justice Whittaker.", "start": 5231.526, "stop": 5233.52, "duration": 1.99}]}, {"speakerName": "Charles E. Whittaker", "textObjs": [{"text": "(Inaudible)", "start": 5233.52, "stop": 5247.092, "duration": 13.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Richard C. Butler", "textObjs": [{"text": "That was the day of the beginning.", "start": 5247.092, "stop": 5248.527, "duration": 1.44}, {"text": "I would not say that that action by the Governor was actually the first or the very beginning of obvious determined opposition to this plan.", "start": 5248.527, "stop": 5260.566, "duration": 12.04}, {"text": "That was smouldering and came out during the summer of 1957 and I would say culminated in the action of the Government.", "start": 5260.566, "stop": 5272.356, "duration": 11.79}, {"text": "Now, there are a lot of people that have different opinions about what caused what, what's the cause and what's the result.", "start": 5272.356, "stop": 5280.828, "duration": 8.47}, {"text": "The actual sequence of events was that there were some outspoken opposition.", "start": 5280.828, "stop": 5287.223, "duration": 6.39}, {"text": "There was outspoken opposition by various people during the summer of 1957 and at the beginning of the school year or thereabouts in September of 1957 the Governor did call out the troops.", "start": 5287.223, "stop": 5302.77, "duration": 15.55}, {"text": "Thank you very much.", "start": 5302.77, "stop": 5303.916, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Earl Warren", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Butler, I would again thank you and your School Board and Mr. Marshall for facilitating this argument and you, Mr. Solicitor General and all of you for the frank and thorough manner in which you have discussed the issues.", "start": 5303.916, "stop": 5322.124, "duration": 18.21}, {"text": "The Court will now stand in -- in recess until the further order of the Court.", "start": 5322.124, "stop": 5332.728, "duration": 10.6}]}]}], "decidedBy": "Warren Court", "arguedOn": "Aug  29, 1958; Sep  11, 1958", "petitioner": "William G. Cooper et al., Members of the Board of Directors of the Little Rock, Arkansas, Independent School District, et al.", "respondent": "John Aaron, et al.", "docket": "1 MISC", "citation": "358 US 1 (1958)", "justiaLink": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/358/1", "lowerCourt": "United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit", "grantedOn": "", "decidedOn": "Sep 12, 1958", "wikiData": {"title": "Cooper v. Aaron", "Litigants": "Cooper v. Aaron", "ArgueDate": "September 11", "ArgueYear": "1958", "DecideDate": "September 12", "DecideYear": "1958", "FullName": "William G. Cooper, et al., Members of the Board of Directors of the Little Rock, Arkansas, Independent School District, and Virgial T. Blossom, Superintendent of Schools v. John Aaron, et al.", "USVol": "358", "USPage": "1", "ParallelCitations": "78 S. Ct. 1401; 3 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 5; 1958 [[LexisNexis|U.S. LEXIS]] 657; 79 Ohio L. Abs. 452", "Prior": "", "Subsequent": "Opinion announced September 29, 1958", "Holding": "This Court cannot countenance a claim by the Governor and Legislature of a State that there is no duty on state officials to obey federal court orders resting on this Court's considered interpretation of the United States Constitution in ''Brown v. Board of Education'' (1954).", "SCOTUS": "1957-1958", "PerCuriam": "yes", "Concurrence": "Frankfurter", "LawsApplied": "[[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. XIV]]; [[Supremacy Clause]]"}}